<seg id="1">Report on the results of the parallel controls carried out in 2005 on the administration of value added tax between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Opening Word</seg>
<seg id="3">The submitted material informs about the progress and results of parallel inspections carried out by the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic, which were focused on the area of value added tax administration and the use of the VIES (Value Added Tax Information Exchange System).</seg>
<seg id="4">In May 2004, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic joined the European Union, so the revenue from value added tax affects not only the national budgets of both countries, but also the budget of the European Union as a whole.</seg>
<seg id="5">Parallel control actions were aimed in particular at checking the tax authorities' procedures for verifying the amount of value added tax paid on commercial transactions between Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="6">The introduction of the VIES system has enabled the electronic exchange of information on the registration of VAT payers in the Member States of the European Union and on the commercial transactions carried out by them.</seg>
<seg id="7">The mismatch between the VIES data and the data in the VAT return submitted by the payer should alert the tax administrator to suspicious cases and allow the detection of tax evasion or fraud.</seg>
<seg id="8">The benefits of the parallel controls were not only in the exchange of information on the procedure of the tax or tax authorities in the administration of value added tax, but in particular in the examination of the use of the VIES system in the control of the application of the right to exemption from value added tax in intra-community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="9">The lessons learned from the implementation of parallel controls contribute to the development of mutual cooperation and will be used in the implementation of further parallel controls in cooperation with the control institutions of the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the results of parallel inspections of the administration of value added tax for the period from 1.5.2004 to 30.6.2005</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">Inspection number: (CZ) 05/19 (SK) 22/2005</seg>
<seg id="13">Subject of the audit: (CZ) Value Added Tax Administration, (SK) Control of the procedure of tax authorities in the administration, control and enforcement of value added tax and fulfilment of tasks within the VIES system for the exchange of information between EU Member States</seg>
<seg id="14">The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the SAO) and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic) concluded on 12 September 2005 the Contract on Cooperation in Audit Activities.</seg>
<seg id="15">The object of the contract was cooperation in parallel audits “Value Added Tax Administration”, included in the audit plan of the SAO CR for 2005 under No. 05/19 and “Control of the tax authorities’ procedure for the administration, control and enforcement of value added tax and fulfilment of tasks within the VIES system for the exchange of information between EU member countries”, included in the audit plan of the SAO SR under No. 22/2005.</seg>
<seg id="16">The control actions carried out in parallel had the character of a coordinated control.</seg>
<seg id="17">The result of the joint coordinated inspection was processed within the meaning of the European Implementing Regulation No 31 for INTOSAI control standards.</seg>
<seg id="18">The cooperation consisted in the exchange of information to the extent provided for in the contract concluded and the preparation of a joint final report on the outcome of the parallel checks.</seg>
<seg id="19">The purpose of the coordinated inspection was to verify selected cases of supply and acquisition of goods in suspicious commercial transactions between VAT payers from the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the Czech Republic) and the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the Slovak Republic).</seg>
<seg id="20">Both parties contractually undertook to provide each other with information from public sources, from the electronic system VIES (Value Added Tax Information Exchange System) and data on received and sent requests to verify commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="21">The checks were carried out in parallel between June and December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the Czech Republic, the audit was carried out by the State Budget Department and the territorial departments of Central Bohemia, Northwest Bohemia, Southern Bohemia, Southern Moravia, Central Moravia and Northern Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited bodies were the Ministry of Finance and 12 financial offices: the Financial Office in Mladá Boleslav, the Financial Office in Kolín, the Financial Office in Teplice, the Financial Office in Karlovy Vary, the Financial Office in Tábor, the Financial Office in Brno III, the Financial Office in Znojmo, the Financial Office in Zlín, the Financial Office in Šumperk, the Financial Office in Ostrava I, the Financial Office for Prague 7 and the Financial Office for Prague 9.</seg>
<seg id="24">The audit on the territory of the Slovak Republic was carried out by the Financial and Tax Section of the SAO of the Slovak Republic in cooperation with the Expoziturami SAO of the Slovak Republic Banská Bystrica and Košice at 9 selected tax offices: Tax Office of Bratislava I, Tax Office of Komárno, Tax Office of Trenčín, Tax Office of Prievidza, Tax Office of Zvolen, Tax Office of Dolný Kubín, Tax Office of Košice II, Tax Office of Košice V and Tax Office of Michalovce.</seg>
<seg id="25">Objective of controls:</seg>
<seg id="26">The aim of the parallel audits was to examine the procedure of the financial and tax authorities in the administration of value added tax (hereinafter "VAT") after the integration of the Czech Republic and Slovakia into the single internal market of the European Union (hereinafter "EU") and to examine the use of the electronic information system VIES, in particular when checking the application of the VAT exemption.</seg>
<seg id="27">The audited coordinated inspection period covered the period from 1.5.2004 to 30.6.2005.</seg>
<seg id="28">Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions An electronic VIES system is in place in EU Member States to allow tax authorities to check whether the supplier has been authorised to exempt the taxable transaction from VAT and to check in the country of destination whether the purchaser has duly declared and taxed the acquired goods.</seg>
<seg id="29">The VIES system is not centralised within the EU, with each Member State developing its own system.</seg>
<seg id="30">The audit found differences in national VIES systems in the Czech Republic and Slovakia in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="31">The recapitulative statements indicate the values of deliveries to other EU Member States, the values of services provided are not included in the recapitulative statements.</seg>
<seg id="32">Data from recapitulative statements submitted by Czech payers are processed in the Czech Republic at the level of the tax authorities, where they are compared with data on supplies of goods to other EU Member States listed in VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="33">The tax authorities transmit the data from the recapitulative statements to the Ministry of Finance (CLO), which sends them to other EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="34">In SR, data from recapitulative statements filed by Slovak payers at tax offices are only converted into electronic form and processed centrally at the Tax Directorate of SR (CLO).</seg>
<seg id="35">In the Czech Republic, payers report the value of supplies of goods and services to other EU Member States on separate rows of VAT returns, which makes it possible to compare the values stated in the recapitulative statements with the values of supplies of goods according to VAT returns and to identify their possible differences.</seg>
<seg id="36">In the SR, the values of goods and services supplied to other EU Member States are shown in aggregate on the common line of the VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="37">Consequently, in the SR, the system does not allow the automatic identification of differences between the values of supplies of goods according to VAT returns and recapitulative statements.</seg>
<seg id="38">Separate reporting of the value of supplies of goods in VAT returns makes it possible to use the results of data comparisons when checking the VAT exemption of supplies of goods to the EU.</seg>
<seg id="39">The delivered data from recapitulative statements submitted by payers in other EU Member States are processed into Customs and compared with the value of acquisition of goods stated by payers from the Czech Republic or Slovakia in their VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="40">In the Slovak Republic, these data are sent to the tax authorities and the tax authorities themselves decide which cases of differences to check.</seg>
<seg id="41">In the Czech Republic, the Ministry of Finance (CLO) determines which quantified differences between the values of supplies and acquisitions of goods must be verified by the tax administrators and sends a list of these cases to the local tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="42">This ensures that, for the most important derogations, it will be verified whether the VAT on the acquisition of goods was correctly declared.</seg>
<seg id="43">The audit also highlighted some problems in the VAT administration system, complications caused by different reporting of intra-Community transactions (i.e. supplies and acquisitions of goods made by payers from different EU Member States):</seg>
<seg id="44">Aggregate reports are submitted in the EU for each calendar quarter and the maximum period for processing and sending data to other EU Member States is set at 3 months from the end of the relevant quarter.</seg>
<seg id="45">The reduction of the period for which recapitulative statements are submitted to one month, together with the shortening of the processing time, would allow earlier access to VIES data.</seg>
<seg id="46">Tax authorities would thus be able to check more effectively whether the VAT on intra-community acquisitions was correctly declared.</seg>
<seg id="47">At the same time, the submission of VAT returns and recapitulative statements for the same tax period (month) would allow faster verification of whether the payer has declared identical values for the supply of goods to the EU in both the recapitulative statement and the VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="48">Differences between the values of deliveries of goods declared by EU payers and the values of acquisitions of goods declared by Czech and Slovak payers were due, among other things, to different reporting of data on intra-Community delivery and acquisitions in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="49">These included, for example, the inclusion of received advances in the recapitulative statements, or the reporting of intra-community supplies in the supplier's recapitulative statement in a quarter other than the intra-community acquisitions in the acquirer's VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="50">Unifying the conditions for reporting such data within the EU would make the control activities of the tax administrations of the Member States more effective.</seg>
<seg id="51">The cooperation of the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO SR was also focused on the examination of selected intra-community transactions carried out between the two countries.</seg>
<seg id="52">Together, a total of 40 cases of commercial transactions between 29 Czech and 32 Slovak tax entities were examined where there were doubts about their completion or suspicion of VAT evasion.</seg>
<seg id="53">The SAO of the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic found the following facts:</seg>
<seg id="54">tax subjects have declared in their VAT returns, for the purpose of unduly obtaining excess VAT, the execution of intra-Community transactions which were not actually carried out;</seg>
<seg id="55">tax subjects reported intra-community supplies in the context of carousel shops where there was a deliberate multiple decrease in the value of supplies in order to draw excess VAT deductions;</seg>
<seg id="56">suppliers declared in their VAT returns and recapitulative statements the intra-Community supply of goods exempt from VAT to purchasers who were so-called "lost companies" and did not declare the tax on the goods acquired;</seg>
<seg id="57">Suppliers made intra-Community supplies of goods exempt from VAT to taxable persons not registered for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="58">In such cases, the supply should not have been exempt from VAT and should have been subject to tax in the supplier's country;</seg>
<seg id="59">Suppliers declared intra-community supplies in their VAT returns at a higher value than the intra-community acquisitions declared by the acquirers, and in some cases VAT was declared incorrectly.</seg>
<seg id="60">The findings of the audit operation showed that the VIES system provides tax administrations with the information necessary to check the correct application of VAT in intra-community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="61">In particular, tax administrations should pay particular attention to the rigorous verification of differences between data reported by VAT payers and VIES data and the use of all information in tax procedures.</seg>
<seg id="62">The issue of value added tax after the accession of the Czech Republic and Slovakia to the EU</seg>
<seg id="63">Value added tax</seg>
<seg id="64">On 1 May 2004, the Czech Republic and Slovakia became members of the EU.</seg>
<seg id="65">Internal borders and border controls on the movement of goods within the EU have been abolished since EU accession.</seg>
<seg id="66">Until 30.4.2004, the VAT administrator was the competent tax or tax office, with the exception of the import of goods and occasional bus transport in the Czech Republic, where the tax administrator was the customs office.</seg>
<seg id="67">In connection with the adoption of the new Act No. 235/2004 Coll., on Value Added Tax (hereinafter referred to as "Act No. 235/2004 Coll."), or Act No. 222/2004 Coll., on Value Added Tax (hereinafter referred to as "Act No. 222/2004 Coll."), the administration of VAT on the acquisition of goods and services (formerly imports) from other EU member countries was transferred from the customs authorities to the tax or tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="68">The supply of goods in the Czech Republic according to the provisions of § 13 of Act No. 235/2004 Coll. means the transfer of the right to dispose of goods as owner.</seg>
<seg id="69">A supply of goods from the Czech Republic to another EU Member State is a supply of goods that have actually been shipped or transported to another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="70">According to the provisions of § 64 of Act No 235/2004 Coll., this is an exempt taxable transaction with the right to deduct VAT if the goods are supplied to a person registered for VAT in another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="71">In the Slovak Republic, according to the provisions of § 8 of Act No 222/2004 Z. z., a supply of tangible property is considered to be a supply of goods where there is a change in the right of ownership.</seg>
<seg id="72">A transfer of goods owned by a taxable person from the territory of the country to another Member State shall be regarded as a supply of goods if those goods are dispatched or transported by that person, or on his behalf, to another Member State for the purposes of his business.</seg>
<seg id="73">Under Paragraph 43 of Law No 222/2004, the supply of goods from the national territory to another Member State is exempt from VAT if the person acquiring the goods is a person identified for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="74">Purchase of goods from another EU Member State in the Czech Republic according to the provisions of § 16 of Act No. 235/2004 Coll. means acquisition of the right to dispose as owner of goods that are dispatched or transported to the acquirer by a person registered for VAT in another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="75">The Czech payer purchases goods at the price without VAT and is obliged to declare VAT in the Czech Republic according to the provisions of § 25 of Act No. 235/2004 Coll., if he fulfils the conditions specified in § 73 of this Act, he is entitled to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="76">Purchase of goods in the territory of the country from another EU Member State in the Slovak Republic pursuant to the provisions of § 11 of Act No 222/2004 Coll. means the acquisition of the right to dispose as owner of movable tangible property dispatched or transported to the person acquiring the goods by or on behalf of the supplier or the person acquiring the goods to the territory of the country from another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="77">Tax liability in the Slovak Republic is incurred by the payer when acquiring goods in the Czech Republic from another Member State in accordance with the provisions of § 20 of Act No 222/2004 Z.z.</seg>
<seg id="78">The taxpayer may deduct VAT in accordance with the provisions of § 49 of Act No. 222/2004 Z. z. if the tax is applied by him on the acquisition of goods in the territory of another Member State in accordance with the provisions of §§ 11 and 11a of this Act.</seg>
<seg id="79">In accordance with the provisions of § 17 of Act No. 235/2004 Coll., or § 45 of Act No. 222/2004 Coll., a trilateral transaction is a transaction concluded between three persons registered for VAT in three different EU Member States where the object of the transaction is the supply of the same goods between these three persons.</seg>
<seg id="80">Intracommunal transactions are supplies and acquisitions of goods made between VAT payers from different EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="81">The total volumes of intra-community transactions between the Czech Republic and Slovakia are shown in the following table.</seg>
<seg id="82">VIES</seg>
<seg id="83">In order to control the exercise of the right to VAT exemption in intra-Community supplies of goods, a VAT information exchange system has been set up within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="84">It includes the VIES electronic system, which allows the tax authorities of the EU Member States to check whether the supplier was entitled to exempt the taxable transaction from VAT and vice versa, whether the purchaser duly declared and taxed the acquired goods.</seg>
<seg id="85">The VIES information system is not centralised within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="86">Each Member State is developing its own VIES system.</seg>
<seg id="87">National systems operate on a common principle and are interconnected through a common EU communication network, the so-called CCN (Common Communication Network; see diagram below).</seg>
<seg id="88">In the Czech Republic, the VIES system was connected to an automated tax information system (hereinafter referred to as "ADIS"), in the Slovak Republic to the application software of the tax information system (hereinafter referred to as "APV DIS").</seg>
<seg id="89">These systems are used by the financial and tax authorities as technical support for executive and management activities in the administration of taxes and duties.</seg>
<seg id="90">International administrative cooperation</seg>
<seg id="91">Through international administrative cooperation, the tax administration of each EU country obtains information about tax entities that it would not be able to obtain on its own without such cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="92">The main objective of international administrative cooperation is the fight against tax evasion and tax losses.</seg>
<seg id="93">Under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003, each Member State establishes, within an internal organisational structure, a central unit for administrative cooperation between EU Member States in the management of VAT, the so-called CLO (Central Liaison Office).</seg>
<seg id="94">In the Czech Republic, the Ministry of Finance – the Central Financial and Tax Directorate, where the Department of International Cooperation in the Administration of VAT (hereinafter referred to as “MF CLO”) has been established, performs tasks arising from international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="95">The function of the Customs Office in the Slovak Republic is fulfilled by the Tax Directorate of the Slovak Republic, Department of International Administrative Cooperation (hereinafter referred to as ‘DG CLO’).</seg>
<seg id="96">These units inter alia communicate with EU foreign administrations in particular in the areas of information exchange within the VIES system, spontaneous information and information exchange at the request of EU tax administrations, coordination of multilateral (simultaneous) tax inspections, verification of VAT identification numbers of persons registered in other EU Member States and communicate with the European Commission.</seg>
<seg id="97">In order to verify a particular intra-community transaction or to obtain additional information related to a particular tax entity, the tax authorities send requests for information to the EU via the Ministry of Customs or the Directorate of Customs.</seg>
<seg id="98">Through these requests, they obtain information from the requested Member States which they can use to determine VAT correctly.</seg>
<seg id="99">Requests for information are mostly sent electronically between the CLOs of the EU Member States, using a standardised SCAC form.</seg>
<seg id="100">Selected audit findings when verifying commercial transactions</seg>
<seg id="101">The cooperation of the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO SR was focused mainly on the examination of selected intra-community transactions carried out between the two states and on the level of use of information obtained through international cooperation by financial and tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="102">The SAO of the Czech Republic required the SAO of the Slovak Republic to examine in 30 cases commercial transactions between 19 Czech and 25 Slovak tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="103">The SAO of Slovakia requested the SAO of the Czech Republic to examine in 10 cases commercial transactions between 7 Slovak and 10 Czech tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="104">Examination of intra-community transactions revealed, among other things:</seg>
<seg id="105">o</seg>
<seg id="106">The SAO of the Czech Republic asked the SAO of the Slovak Republic to verify the procedure of the tax administrator, who was sent a reply to the request for information.</seg>
<seg id="107">The Slovak Tax Office, using the SCAC form, requested verification of the supply of goods (footwear) in the 3rd quarter of 2004 from a Slovak payer in the value of SKK 2,847,000.</seg>
<seg id="108">The tax office in the Czech Republic replied that the Czech payer stated the acquisition of goods of this value only in the additional VAT declaration and the same goods were delivered back to Slovak tax entities in the value of CZK 2,550,000 by the end of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="109">On the basis of the international cooperation of the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO SR, it was found that the locally competent tax office granted the Slovak supplier a full right to excess VAT deduction arising, inter alia, from this supply.</seg>
<seg id="110">This tax office did not provide information about the suspicion of re-export to the tax authorities of the locally competent buyers of goods imported back from the Czech payer.</seg>
<seg id="111">This will trigger further investigation of commercial activities in relation to possible carousel fraud.</seg>
<seg id="112">o</seg>
<seg id="113">The Czech tax administrator asked through the SCAC form to verify the delivery of a technology line to Slovakia worth CZK 4,850,000 in the second quarter of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="114">The tax proceedings carried out in Slovakia revealed that only part of the technology line was delivered, components worth CZK 3,395,000 were not delivered.</seg>
<seg id="115">The SAO of Slovakia, when examining this case, found that the VAT on the taxable transaction was declared by a Slovak tax entity for the amount of CZK 4,850,000 in the VAT return (hereinafter "DAP") for the tax period 7/2004.</seg>
<seg id="116">The SAO of the Czech Republic also found that the Czech payer reported an excess VAT deduction in the amount of CZK 655,000 in its VAT receipt for that quarter, which was created by the application of a VAT deduction from the purchase of this technology line from another domestic payer.</seg>
<seg id="117">Based on the results of the investigation, the Czech Tax Office concluded that the Czech and Slovak taxpayer had created a business relationship for the purpose of unduly obtaining an excess VAT deduction, disputed the realisation of the taxable transaction and did not recognise part of the right to deduct the tax amounting to CZK 647,000.</seg>
<seg id="118">o</seg>
<seg id="119">In 2004, the Slovak tax administrator, using the SCAC form, requested verification of the supply of goods (copying machines) to the Czech payer in the amount of SKK 24 246 thousand made in December 2002.</seg>
<seg id="120">These goods were purchased by a Slovak payer in November 2002 in Slovakia from another tax entity in the value of SKK 29 667 thousand and subsequently sold to a Czech payer.</seg>
<seg id="121">The Slovak taxpayer applied an excess VAT deduction for the relevant tax period.</seg>
<seg id="122">In a tax investigation carried out in the Czech Republic, it was found that the Czech tax entity did not cooperate with the tax administrator and did not file a DAP for the 4th quarter of 2002 or for the following period.</seg>
<seg id="123">The SAO of Slovakia found that the Slovak tax administrator did not recognise the right to an excess deduction of CZK 5,541,000 based on the results of the tax audit. Sk invoked in the DAP for the month of 11/2002 and established a tax liability of SKK 1 750 000.</seg>
<seg id="124">At the same time, that taxpayer was not granted an exemption from VAT in respect of the export of goods in December 2002.</seg>
<seg id="125">o</seg>
<seg id="126">The Czech tax administrator received an order from MF Customs to verify the value of the purchased goods for the 3rd quarter of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="127">According to the VIES data, the Czech payer should have purchased goods (paint thinner) from SR in the value of 3 767 thousand SKK.</seg>
<seg id="128">This taxpayer did not cooperate with the tax administrator, did not file a DAP and was charged VAT in the amount of CZK 0 ex officio for the months 7 to 12/2004.</seg>
<seg id="129">The Czech tax administrator asked through the SCAC form to verify whether deliveries of goods from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic took place, in what quantity and price (according to invoices).</seg>
<seg id="130">In reply, the Slovak Tax Office sent a copy of the invoice, the bill of lading and a request for payment of the invoice.</seg>
<seg id="131">The SAO of Slovakia found that the Slovak payer was granted an exemption with the right to deduct VAT on this supply.</seg>
<seg id="132">The SAO of the Czech Republic found that the Czech tax administrator assessed the response to the request for information received from the Slovak Republic as evidence that the company had purchased goods from another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="133">On the basis of further investigation, the tax office in the Czech Republic will ask the superior authority to review the tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="134">o</seg>
<seg id="135">The Slovak company supplied goods (particle board products) to, among others, an American company which deposited these goods in the Czech Republic in a free customs zone.</seg>
<seg id="136">The operator of that free zone was named on the invoices as the consignee of the goods.</seg>
<seg id="137">In 2004, for example, a US company purchased from a Slovak payer particle board tiles worth USD 57 600 (at a unit price of USD 100 per piece), which it placed in a free customs zone.</seg>
<seg id="138">Subsequently, the company transferred ownership of the goods to a Swiss company, amounting to USD 14 400 (unit price of USD 25 each) and the goods were re-exported to the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="139">The goods were not unloaded in the Czech Republic, but left the area of the free customs zone on the same means of transport.</seg>
<seg id="140">The Slovak tax administrator initiated tax inspections of individual tax periods of 2004 and 2005 at the supplier of goods on suspicion of carousel transactions.</seg>
<seg id="141">The verification of the underlying transactions was requested from the Czech locally competent tax authorities using several SCAC forms.</seg>
<seg id="142">Individual responses gradually created an image of the shops and confirmed the involvement of stakeholders from the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic in the carousel shops.</seg>
<seg id="143">The SAO of the Czech Republic in cooperation with the SAO of the Slovak Republic found that in these business relations there was a deliberate multiple decrease in the value of goods.</seg>
<seg id="144">On the basis of the information received, the Tax Directorate of the Slovak Republic concluded that the carousel trade in question is free price formation (i.e. the import of undervalued goods and their overvaluation by domestic companies in the chain between the importer and the exporter) which is not in breach of the VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="145">Under the current legislation, the payment of excess VAT to export companies cannot be prevented as they fulfil all the conditions of the law to exempt supplies from VAT.</seg>
<seg id="146">o</seg>
<seg id="147">The Czech payer's VAT registration was cancelled on 12 July 2005.</seg>
<seg id="148">On 27 October 2005, this entity became a taxpayer again on the basis of a voluntarily submitted application for VAT registration.</seg>
<seg id="149">The Czech taxpayer entered into the DAP for the month of 8/2005 (i.e. the period when he was not a VAT payer) the value of the acquisition of goods (printing press) from the Slovak Republic in the amount of CZK 1,174,000 and claimed the right to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="150">This value corresponded to a supply of goods from a Slovak payer in the amount of SKK 1,530,000, which the Slovak payer listed in the DAP as a supply of goods to another EU Member State with the right to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="151">The Slovak tax administrator requested to verify this supply using the SCAC form, because the Slovak supplier did not prove how he acquired the goods delivered to the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="152">The SAO of the Czech Republic found that the Czech payer does not cooperate with the tax administrator and does not reside at the address specified in the Commercial Register.</seg>
<seg id="153">As part of the international exchange of information, a local investigation will be carried out in the Czech Republic by the local tax administrator in order to verify the data.</seg>
<seg id="154">o</seg>
<seg id="155">The Slovak payer included in the recapitulative statement for the 3rd quarter of 2004 the delivery of goods in the value of CZK 956,000. To a tax entity from the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="156">The VAT number of the Czech entity was marked as incorrect by the VIES system.</seg>
<seg id="157">A verification in the database of payers revealed that such a TIN was never assigned in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="158">According to invoices issued by the Slovak payer, it was the execution of electrical assembly works on real estate in the Czech Republic, it was not the delivery of goods from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic, but the provision of services.</seg>
<seg id="159">The services were invoiced without VAT, as the Czech entity informed the Slovak entity that it is registered as a VAT payer in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="160">The Slovak tax authority requested to verify these facts using the SCAC form.</seg>
<seg id="161">The SAO of the Czech Republic inquired at the local tax authority in the Czech Republic and found that the tax entity listed on the invoices as a customer was never registered as a VAT payer in the Czech Republic, did not declare the tax on received services from the Slovak entity and did not declare the tax on the acquisition of goods.</seg>
<seg id="162">Neither a local investigation nor a tax inspection was carried out on the Czech entity, its current whereabouts are unknown.</seg>
<seg id="163">On the basis of the international exchange of information, the Czech tax administrator learned that the Czech tax entity became a VAT payer by law by accepting the service.</seg>
<seg id="164">The Slovak tax entity will be audited for the first to fourth quarters of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="165">o</seg>
<seg id="166">The Slovak payer included in the recapitulative statement for the 3rd quarter of 2004 the delivery of goods in the value of CZK 1,055,000. To the Czech payer.</seg>
<seg id="167">According to invoices issued by the Slovak payer, it was the execution of electrical assembly works on real estate in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="168">It was not a matter of delivering goods from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic, but of providing services.</seg>
<seg id="169">The Slovak tax authority requested to verify these facts using the SCAC form.</seg>
<seg id="170">The SAO of the Czech Republic inquired with the local tax authority in the Czech Republic that the Czech entity was a VAT payer at the time of the delivery and a local investigation was carried out to verify the acquisition of goods from other EU Member States in the 3rd quarter of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="171">On the basis of this on-the-spot investigation, it was found that this case was not really a purchase of goods, but a purchase of services, which was also declared by the Czech entity in the regular DAP.</seg>
<seg id="172">The tax office also found that the Czech entity did not pay the correct amount of VAT for the tax period of the 3rd quarter of 2004 as a result of a bad procedure in the calculation of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="173">The taxpayer shall submit an additional DAP.</seg>
<seg id="174">The SAO, when questioned by the local tax office, found that the Slovak payer had misstated the provision of the service in the recapitulative statement and would be subject to a tax audit for the first to fourth quarters of 2004.</seg>
