<seg id="356">Cooperation in the field of information exchange is governed by Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003.</seg>
<seg id="357">The maximum time limit for replying to the EIT was set at 3 months in Article 8 of that regulation.</seg>
<seg id="358">The conditions for the admissibility of applications are governed by the Decision of the Commission of the European Communities of 15.11.2004, which stipulates that, unless the participating States agree otherwise, the GI must relate to commercial transactions of at least EUR 1 500 excluding VAT.</seg>
<seg id="359">If the GI concerns a commercial transaction with a value of less than EUR 15 000 excluding VAT, the requested authority may refuse to reply in view of its workload.</seg>
<seg id="360">The following diagram illustrates the procedure of handling incoming RUs by the tax administration of the Czech Republic, including the internal time limits set for processing at each organizational level.</seg>
<seg id="361">In SR, the time limit for the discharge of the GI by the tax authorities was set at 2 months in order to comply with the three-month deadline under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003.</seg>
<seg id="362">From 1 May 2004 to 30 June 2005, MF CLO received a total of 29 GIs and 3 SPIs from the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="363">Of the 29 GIs received, 26 (i.e. 89.7%) were discharged within the prescribed period of 3 months and 3 (i.e. 10.3%) were discharged after that period.</seg>
<seg id="364">In the same period, DG CLO from the Czech Republic received a total of 71 RUs and 7 SPIs.</seg>
<seg id="365">Of the 71 GIs received, 64 (i.e. 90.1%) were processed within the prescribed period of 3 months, 5 (i.e. 7.0%) were processed after this period (for the remaining 2 cases it was not possible to determine the period of execution from the submitted materials).</seg>
<seg id="366">The following chart contains more detailed data on the processing time of RUIs received by MF CLO, respectively DR CLO.</seg>
<seg id="367">The following table contains the reasons for sending the RU, as stated on the SCAC forms.</seg>
<seg id="368">Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="369">Compliance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 on administrative cooperation in the field of VAT, as well as the use of the VIES system for the exchange of information between EU Member States, in particular for checking the application of the VAT exemption, was examined on the basis of international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="370">International cooperation has made it possible to examine selected intra-community transactions between VAT payers from the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="371">An examination of the selected transactions revealed that, on the basis of an international exchange of information, the tax administrations of both countries had uncovered cases of companies carrying out fictitious intra-community business transactions in order to obtain excess VAT deductions, as well as cases where the purchasers did not declare the correct amount of VAT on the received supplies of goods.</seg>
<seg id="372">The audit also found differences in the processing and use of VIES data by the tax administrations of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="373">The audit also pointed to problems caused by different reporting of data on intra-Community supplies and acquisitions of goods in different EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="374">Unifying the conditions for reporting such data within the EU would make the control activities of the tax administrations of the Member States more effective.</seg>
<seg id="375">An examination of the procedure of the tax authorities in the administration of VAT and the use of the VIES system revealed that the tax authorities did not make sufficient use of all the possibilities of the VIES system and the relevant legal authorisations.</seg>
<seg id="376">Furthermore, it was found that the VIES system did not in all cases provide up-to-date information on the supply of goods and on the validity of the VAT registration of tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="377">The SAO SR compared the data on the occurrence of erroneous data in the SH, processed before the start of the audit, with the data processed after the completion of the audit.</seg>
<seg id="378">Comparison of these data showed that the audit of the SAO SR had an impact not only on the reduction of the number of SH with erroneously reported DINs, but also on the reduction of the number of uncorrected errors in SH.</seg>
<seg id="379">In case of discrepancies in the reported data, the SAO asked the tax authorities to carry out local investigations or tax inspections.</seg>
<seg id="380">The SAO of the Czech Republic did not have such an option under the applicable legislation in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="381">The findings of the audit work showed that the VIES system provided tax administrations with the basic information necessary to check the correct application of VAT in intra-community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="382">Given that there remains scope for tax evasion in this area, increased attention needs to be paid to intra-community transactions in the VAT administration.</seg>
<seg id="383">Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="384">This report was drawn up in the Czech, English and Slovak languages and signed by the President of the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic and the President of the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
</p>
