<p>
<seg id="1">Parallel control of the administration of value added tax and excise duties between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Opening Word</seg>
<seg id="3">This information document gives an overview of the progress and results of the parallel audits carried out by the Supreme Audit Office and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic, which were focused on the area of value added tax and excise tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="4">The cooperation between the SAIs of both countries was carried out on the basis of a cooperation agreement on control activities concluded in February 2004.</seg>
<seg id="5">The theme of the parallel control actions was chosen in view of the fact that indirect taxes contribute significantly to the revenues of the national budgets of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="6">The construction of value added tax, allowing the refund of excess deductions, provides scope for tax fraud or evasion.</seg>
<seg id="7">High rates of excise duties, especially on tobacco and tobacco products, alcohol and mineral oils, mean high profits for those who escape taxation by illegally selling these goods.</seg>
<seg id="8">Tax fraud is a problem not only in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, but also in other countries of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="9">In view of the need to address this issue comprehensively throughout the European Union, the VAT Working Group has been created by the supreme audit institutions of the Member States of the European Union, in which the supreme audit institutions of both countries are actively involved.</seg>
<seg id="10">The greatest benefit of the control actions carried out can be seen not only in the exchange of experience, but especially in the joint effort to identify problem areas of indirect tax administration in order to reduce the scope for tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="11">The experience and knowledge gained will be used in the framework of the planned controls of indirect taxes, aimed in particular at the involvement of the tax authorities of both states in the VIES system, which makes it possible to control the movement of goods between the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="12">Report on the results of the audit of the administration of value added tax and excise duties for the years 2002 and 2003</seg>
<seg id="13">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="14">Control number: (CZ) 04/07 (SK) 18/2004</seg>
<seg id="15">Object of control:</seg>
<seg id="16">(CZ) Value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="17">(SK) Control of the procedure of the tax administrator in the administration, control and enforcement of value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="18">On 11 February 2004, the Supreme Audit Office (SAO) and the Supreme Audit Office (SAO) of the Slovak Republic (SAO SR) were signed. The object of the contract was cooperation in parallel audits "Value Added Tax and Excise Tax", included in the Audit Plan of the SAO for 2004 under No. 04/07 and "Audit of the Tax Administrators' Procedure for Administration, Control and Enforcement of Value Added Tax and Excise Taxes", included in the Audit Plan of the SAO SR under No. 18/2004.</seg>
<seg id="19">The cooperation consisted in exchanging information to the extent provided for in the contract concluded and in drawing up a joint final report on the outcome of the checks.</seg>
<seg id="20">In the contract, both parties undertook to provide each other with information from public sources, from the customs administration database and from tax entity files kept by the tax authorities in the Czech Republic and the tax authorities in the Slovak Republic, which the contracting parties could not obtain when checking the application of value added tax and excise duties on imports and exports from sources in the territory of the respective state.</seg>
<seg id="21">The checks were carried out in parallel between January and August 2004.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the territory of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as "the Czech Republic"), the audit was carried out by the State Budget Department and the territorial departments of South Bohemia, North-East Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and Northern Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited bodies were the General Directorate of Customs and 12 selected financial offices: the Financial Office for Prague 1, the Financial Office for Prague 3, the Financial Office in České Budějovice, the Financial Office in Frýdek-Místek, the Financial Office in Hodonín, the Financial Office in Jihlava, the Financial Office in Kostelec nad Orlicí, the Financial Office in Kroměříž, the Financial Office in Písek, the Financial Office in Rožnov pod Radhoštěm, the Financial Office in Ústí nad Orlicí, the Financial Office in Velký Meziříčí.</seg>
<seg id="24">The audit on the territory of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as "SR") was carried out by the Tax and Customs Administration Section of the SAO SR in cooperation with the SAO Expoziturami SR Banská Bystrica and Košice at 10 selected tax offices:</seg>
<seg id="25">Tax Office Bratislava for selected tax entities, Tax Office Bratislava III, Tax Office Trnava, Tax Office Pooh-chov, Tax Office Banská Bystrica I, Tax Office Liptovský Mikuláš, Tax Office Žilina I, Tax Office Žilina II, Tax Office Košice I and Tax Office Košice IV.</seg>
<seg id="26">Objective of control</seg>
<seg id="27">The aim of the audits was to verify the fulfilment of the duties of the tax and tax authorities and customs authorities in the administration of value added tax and excise duties with a focus on the collection of these taxes on imports and exports of goods and services.</seg>
<seg id="28">The aim of the international cooperation was to verify imports and exports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and Slovakia in the customs database of the Czech Republic and the customs database of the Slovak Republic and their subsequent verification in tax returns at the relevant financial and tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="29">The audited period covered the years 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="30">2. Recapitulation of control results</seg>
<seg id="31">2.1. General evaluation of control activities</seg>
<seg id="32">Within the framework of international cooperation, the SAO provided 22,206 items of the Single Customs Declarations (hereinafter referred to as "JCD") on imports and exports of goods between the Czech Republic and Slovakia from the Czech Customs Database and the SAO provided the SAO with 30,221 items of the JCD from the SR Customs Database.</seg>
<seg id="33">Comparison of selected JCD items from the customs database of the Czech Republic and the customs database of the Slovak Republic was performed.</seg>
<seg id="34">Out of 5,883 selected JCD items from the customs database of the Czech Republic, a total of 43% of the related JCD items were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="35">Out of the 12 343 selected JCD items from the SR Customs Database, a total of 26 % of the related JCD items were allocated.</seg>
<seg id="36">On the basis of the unassigned JCD items, the tax authorities selected files of tax entities, whose reported imports and exports were further verified in cooperation with the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="37">Based on the exchange of information from the documents of the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and Slovakia and the financial and tax authorities, the realization of reported imports and exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic was verified on the territory of the second state.</seg>
<seg id="38">The SAO and the SAO of Slovakia conducted a joint pilot inspection at the border customs crossing Starý Hrozenkov - Drietoma, during which both parties cooperated closely in verifying the accuracy of the data on the movement of goods between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="39">The audit did not find any deficiencies in the registration of selected cases of imports and exports of goods carried out in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="40">International cooperation has made it possible to examine trade transactions between trading partners from both countries and has highlighted shortcomings in the registration of imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="41">2.2. Summary of control results</seg>
<seg id="42">In the area of international cooperation, the SAO and the SAO scrutinized imports and exports of alcohol and spirits, tobacco and tobacco products, computers and computer components, mobile phones and their parts, as well as other goods.</seg>
<seg id="43">The SAO requested verification of the realisation of exports of goods declared for 40 JCD with a total statistical value of CZK 15,301,093 and the SAO requested verification of exports with a statistical value of CZK 56,989.</seg>
<seg id="44">The SAO and the SAO of the Slovak Republic found, among other things, the following facts:</seg>
<seg id="45">- commercial transactions were not declared in the same way on both sides, which made it difficult to identify the corresponding imports and exports in the customs database of the Czech Republic and the customs database of the Slovak Republic,</seg>
<seg id="46">- errors in entering data into customs databases made it impossible to identify certain imports or exports,</seg>
<seg id="47">- for some exports from the Czech Republic, the corresponding imports to the Slovak Republic have not been demonstrated.</seg>
<seg id="48">In such cases, there is a reasonable suspicion of fictitious exports of goods for the purpose of improper application of value added tax deductions.</seg>
<seg id="49">- tax subjects did not fulfil certain statutory obligations when reporting imports and exports in value added tax returns;</seg>
<seg id="50">- shortcomings have been identified in the activities of the tax or tax authorities in the administration of value added tax and excise duties and in their interaction with customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="51">In the area of value added tax and excise duties, attention to international trade will continue to be needed in order to effectively minimise tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="52">In particular, it is important to improve the quality of the work of tax administrators in the administration of value added tax.</seg>
<seg id="53">Effective control of excise duties is based on control of document circulation, systematic physical control of goods and mutual exchange of information on import and export of goods.</seg>
<seg id="54">3. Description of the situation regarding value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="55">Value added tax</seg>
<seg id="56">Value added tax (hereinafter referred to as "VAT") was levied by the tax or tax authorities on taxable transactions carried out within the territory of the country and by the customs authorities on importation of goods.</seg>
<seg id="57">The tax revenue was determined by the tax authorities by the difference between the collected own tax liability and the refunded excess VAT deductions.</seg>
<seg id="58">VAT revenue at customs offices was determined by the amount of tax collected by them.</seg>
<seg id="59">In accordance with the basic principles of the VAT mechanism, the tax collected by the customs authorities was reflected in the tax deductions applied at the tax or tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="60">For most tax and tax authorities, excess VAT deductions exceeded tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="61">VAT is one of the key taxes in terms of state budget revenues, as it accounted for about 31% of the tax revenues of the state budget of the Czech Republic and about 42% of the tax revenues of the state budget of the Slovak Republic in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="62">Total VAT collection in the Czech Republic amounted to CZK 162.9 billion in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="63">The tax and customs authorities collected a total of CZK 394.3 billion in VAT in 2003 and the excess VAT deductions returned totalled CZK 231.4 billion.</seg>
<seg id="64">Total VAT collection in Slovakia amounted to SKK 83.8 billion in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="65">The tax and customs authorities collected 187.0 billion SKK in VAT in 2003 and the excess VAT deductions returned totalled 103.2 billion SKK.</seg>
<seg id="66">Excise duties</seg>
<seg id="67">The collection of excise duties (hereinafter referred to as the ‘SPD’) was carried out by the competent tax and tax authorities and, when importing products subject to the SPD, by the customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="68">SpD's share of the tax revenue of the state budget in the Czech Republic amounted to approximately 16% in 2003 and approximately 19% in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="69">The total collection of State Treasury funds collected in the Czech Republic by financial and customs authorities in 2003 amounted to CZK 85.6 billion and in the Slovak Republic amounted to SKK 38.0 billion.</seg>
<seg id="70">4. Progress of control action</seg>
<seg id="71">The cooperation between the SAO and the SAO of the Slovak Republic took place in two stages.</seg>
<seg id="72">In the first stage, the comparison of imports and exports of selected commodities from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia was carried out; in the second stage, the results of this comparison were used for mutual verification of the implementation of selected trade transactions between the Czech Republic and Slovakia and for inspections carried out on the territory of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="73">4.1.</seg>
<seg id="74">Preparation of control action</seg>
<seg id="75">The first proposal for cooperation in parallel VAT and VAT audits was presented at a working meeting of representatives of the SAO and the SAO of the Slovak Republic in April 2003.</seg>
<seg id="76">In November 2003, a coordination meeting was held at which, among other things, the selection of commodities - goods which presented a significant risk in complying with customs and tax rules: - alcohol and spirits, tariff lines Nos 2207 and 2208, - tobacco and tobacco products, tariff lines Nos 2401, 2402 and 2403, - computers and computer components, tariff lines Nos 8471 and 8473 30, - mobile telephones and their accessories, tariff lines Nos 8525 20 91, 8525 20 99, 8529 90 40.</seg>
<seg id="77">The two parties agreed that the selection of tax entities for inspection will be carried out: a) from unallocated items found by comparing exports and imports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and Slovakia, b) from entities carrying out imports and exports regularly or in one lump sum in a large volume, c) based on findings from inspections carried out by selected financial and tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="78">4.2. Comparison of customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="79">In the first stage, a mechanism of mutual assignment of JCD items registered in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia was tested on a sample of imports and exports of selected commodities for the month of October 2002.</seg>
<seg id="80">Subsequently, a part of exports from the Czech Republic was compared with imports to the Slovak Republic in 2002 and vice versa for selected commodities according to the customs tariff:</seg>
<seg id="81">- 2207 Undenatured ethyl alcohol of an alcoholic strength by volume of 80% vol or higher; ethyl alcohol and other spirits, denatured, of any strength,</seg>
<seg id="82">- 2208 Undenatured ethyl alcohol of an alcoholic strength by volume of less than 80% vol; spirits, liqueurs and other spirituous beverages,</seg>
<seg id="83">- 2401 Unmanufactured tobacco; tobacco waste,</seg>
<seg id="84">- 2402 Cigars, cheroots, cigarillos and cigarettes, of tobacco or of tobacco substitutes,</seg>
<seg id="85">- 2403 Other manufactured tobacco and tobacco substitutes; homogenised or reconstituted tobacco; tobacco extracts and essences;</seg>
<seg id="86">- 8525 20 91 Transmission apparatus containing reception equipment: For cellular network (mobile phones),</seg>
<seg id="87">- 8525 20 99 Transmission apparatus incorporating reception apparatus:</seg>
<seg id="88">- 8529 90 40 Parts suitable for use solely or principally with the apparatus of headings 8525 to 8528.</seg>
<seg id="89">Other: Parts of apparatus falling in subheadings 8525 10 50, 8525 20 91, 8525 20 99, 8525 40 11 and 8527 90 92.</seg>
<seg id="90">JCD items from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia were mutually assigned based on the agreement of the individual paragraphs of the JCD (e.g. invoiced price, quantity, weight, registration number of the vehicle transporting the load, date of crossing the national border, tariff item, etc.).</seg>
<seg id="91">The results of the comparison are shown in the following tables and graphs.</seg>
<seg id="92">The cross-referencing of individual imports and exports was hampered, inter alia, by the fact that commercial transactions were not declared in the same way on both sides.</seg>
<seg id="93">For example, exports from the Czech Republic declared on one export JCD were declared on the territory of the Slovak Republic on multiple import JCDs, or the export JCD had a different number of items from the import JCD.</seg>
<seg id="94">Other factors that affected the success of the referencing were the different composition of data in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia, as well as the time shift between the registration of exports in the customs database of one country and the registration of corresponding imports in the customs database of the other country.</seg>
<seg id="95">The results of the comparison were used in the selection of control samples at audited financial and tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="96">Priority was given to certain tax entities that carried out imports or exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia that could not be identified in both databases.</seg>
<seg id="97">In addition, some tax entities were selected for the verification of business transactions reported in VAT returns, for which data on imports or exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia were found in both databases.</seg>
<seg id="98">4.3. Pilot check at the border customs crossing Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma</seg>
<seg id="99">The border customs crossing point for pilot control was selected on the basis of a joint analysis of unassigned JCD items in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="100">On the basis of a bilateral agreement between the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and Slovakia, the use of control sheets was introduced at the border customs crossing points between the Czech Republic and Slovakia from 1.6.1998.</seg>
<seg id="101">The aim of this measure was to eliminate customs and tax evasion as far as possible, to ensure an overview of the movement of commercial transport vehicles in the customs area and to create the conditions for comparing customs registers with each other.</seg>
<seg id="102">The joint pilot inspection was carried out between 8.3.2004 and 26.3.2004 and aimed at examining this customs control system.</seg>
<seg id="103">Procedure for the use of checklists at the Old Hrozenkov-Drietoma border crossing point:</seg>
<seg id="104">1) Weighing the vehicle, issuing the control sheet and handing it over to the driver.</seg>
<seg id="105">2) Parking of the vehicle in the designated sector in the parking lot.</seg>
<seg id="106">Customs clearance in the check-in hall of the Police of the Czech Republic, Police of the Slovak Republic, Customs Administration of the Czech Republic, Customs Administration of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="107">The check-in was confirmed by individual files stamping on the inspection sheet.</seg>
<seg id="108">3) Bringing the vehicle into the physical inspection area.</seg>
<seg id="109">Presentation of the inspection sheet, JCD, or other documents to the customs official - verification of the completion of all prescribed acts and documents.</seg>
<seg id="110">Performance of a physical check by the appropriate ingredients.</seg>
<seg id="111">Release of a vehicle from the customs area.</seg>
<seg id="112">Note: When importing goods into the Czech Republic, the weighing of the vehicle was carried out directly by employees of the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="113">When the goods were imported into the Slovak Republic, the weighing of the vehicles was carried out by the staff of the authorised legal entity.</seg>
<seg id="114">The vehicles were registered in the computerised register after weighing.</seg>
<seg id="115">4.3.1. Control sample</seg>
<seg id="116">Exports from the Czech Republic to Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="117">The control sample was selected on the basis of an analysis of records from the customs database of exports of the Czech Republic in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="118">The composition of the export control sample is shown in Table 4.</seg>
<seg id="119">4.3.2. Checklists and their records Exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="120">When exporting from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic, the control sheets were issued and registered by the Customs Administration of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="121">The Customs Administration of the Czech Republic recorded the registration numbers of these control sheets in the electronic database of exports.</seg>
<seg id="122">From the number of 453 JCD items, the SAO found 256 cases of imports into the Slovak Republic according to data from the customs database of the Czech Republic and Slovakia. The remaining 197 JCD items were identified by the SAO SR in cooperation with the staff of the Drietoma border crossing point.</seg>
<seg id="123">Exports from Slovakia to the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="124">When exporting from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic, the control sheets were issued and registered by the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="125">From the total number of 339 JCD items of the selected control sample, the SAO in cooperation with border customs crossing staff assigned the corresponding registration numbers of the control sheets to the 295 JCD items.</seg>
<seg id="126">The remaining 44 cases were identified in the register by the employees of the border customs crossing Drietoma and the export of goods from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic was confirmed.</seg>
<seg id="127">The SAO and SAO audit did not find any deficiencies in the registration of selected cases of imports and exports of goods in 2002 at the border customs crossing Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma.</seg>
<seg id="128">4.4. Selected audit findings when verifying commercial transactions</seg>
<seg id="129">Within the framework of international cooperation, the realization of imports and exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic was verified from documents of customs administrations and financial or tax offices in the territory of the other state.</seg>
<seg id="130">For selected tax entities, the following were verified:</seg>
<seg id="131">- whether the submitted JCDs were registered in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia,</seg>
<seg id="132">- the fulfilment of the legal conditions for the application of the deduction of VAT on importation, the refund of excess VAT and the application of the VAT exemption on exportation.</seg>
<seg id="133">The verification of commercial transactions revealed:</seg>
<seg id="134">1. The SAO of Slovakia requested verification of the export of alcohol in the statistical value of 56 989 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="135">The SAO identified the corresponding imports in the Czech customs database with a statistical value of CZK 42,624. r</seg>
<seg id="136">2. A company engaged in the import and export of photographic equipment and accessories claimed an excess VAT deduction of CZK 3,740,664 in its VAT return for the month of December 2002.</seg>
<seg id="137">In order to check reported exports from the Czech Republic, the SAO selected 3 JCD (16 items) with a statistical value of CZK 1,274,822.</seg>
<seg id="138">The SAO of Slovakia identified 3 corresponding import JCDs (17 items) with a statistical value of 1,724,321 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="139">VAT was paid to the competent customs office in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="140">3. In 2002, a company whose main business was the trade in optical equipment claimed a total excess VAT deduction of CZK 4 1 36 000 higher than the tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="141">The SAO selected an export JCD (32 items) with a statistical value of CZK 7,154,124 to verify the reported business activity.</seg>
<seg id="142">The SAO of Slovakia found that this JCD corresponds to the import JCD (12 items) with a statistical value of 9 653 827 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="143">VAT was paid to the competent customs office in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="144">4. The company involved in, inter alia, the purchase of goods for resale and sale did not report any exports of goods in the VAT returns filed in 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="145">According to the customs database of the Czech Republic, the statistical value of goods exports in 2002 totalled CZK 3,439,888.</seg>
<seg id="146">Based on these facts, the SAO selected 5 export JCDs (5 items) for verification in the total statistical value of CZK 669,839.</seg>
<seg id="147">The SAO of Slovakia identified 5 corresponding import JCDs (5 items) with a statistical value of 1 012 656 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="148">The audit of the SAO of the Slovak Republic at the relevant tax office showed that the declared imports were made and VAT was paid.</seg>
<seg id="149">5. The company, whose business was, among other things, the purchase of goods for resale and sale, production, installation and repair of electrical machinery and appliances, reported in 2002 in VAT returns the export of goods worth CZK 12,966,706.</seg>
<seg id="150">According to the Czech customs database, the total value of exports in 2002 was CZK 14,474,381.</seg>
<seg id="151">The SAO submitted 17 export JCDs (59 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 2,975,122.</seg>
<seg id="152">The SAO of Slovakia identified 13 JCD (50 items) in the customs database SR with a statistical value of 3 621 370 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="153">The Slovak customs database failed to identify the corresponding import JCD to 4 export JCDs (9 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 399,776.</seg>
<seg id="154">The relevant tax office in SR verified these imports with the taxpayer.</seg>
<seg id="155">The tax entity listed on the JCD as an importer to the Slovak Republic stated in the minutes of the local investigation that it did not carry out the imports declared on the Czech export JCD.</seg>
<seg id="156">The SAO of the Slovak Republic therefore asked the local tax office to carry out a tax audit of VAT and corporate income tax for the tax years 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="157">6. According to the customs database of the Czech Republic, a company engaged in the import and sale of cigarettes exported tobacco stickers in 2002 with a statistical value of CZK 7,338,199 and in 2003 with a statistical value of CZK 12,228,545.</seg>
<seg id="158">The company did not report any exports in its VAT returns in 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="159">The SAO selected 5 export JCDs (5 items) for verification in the total statistical value of CZK 2,471,598.</seg>
<seg id="160">For 4 export JCDs (4 items) in the total statistical value of 2 246 860 CZK, the SAO SR identified 7 JCDs (7 items) in the customs database SR in the statistical value of 2 919 514 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="161">The export JCD (1 item) in the statistical value of CZK 224,738 failed to assign the corresponding import in the customs database of SR.</seg>
<seg id="162">7. The software company did not report exports of goods in its 2002 and 2003 VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="163">According to the Czech customs database, the statistical value of goods exports in 2002 and 2003 totalled CZK 1,630,198.</seg>
<seg id="164">The SAO selected 9 JCD (9 items) for verification in SR, totalling CZK 755,588.</seg>
<seg id="165">In the customs database SR SAO SR identified 8 JCD (8 items) in statistical value 915 601 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="166">The export JCD (1 item) with a statistical value of CZK 68,286 could not be assigned to the corresponding import in the SR customs database.</seg>
<seg id="167">In these cases, it was not possible to identify the corresponding imports to 6 JCD in the customs database with a statistical value of CZK 692,800.</seg>
<seg id="168">Of which:</seg>
<seg id="169">- to 2 export JCDs from the customs database of the Czech Republic with a statistical value of 293 024 CZK, the corresponding import JCD could not be identified in the customs database of the Slovak Republic (see points 6 and 7).</seg>
<seg id="170">Due to a certain error rate in entering data in the customs database, it was not possible to identify certain registered imports, e.g. in cases where the importer's name was missing or there was an error in the tax identification number (TIN).</seg>
<seg id="171">Therefore, it cannot be concluded with certainty that these exports did not take place.</seg>
<seg id="172">- to 4 export JCDs from the customs database of the Czech Republic, imports corresponding to exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic in the statistical value of CZK 399,776 were not proven (see point 5).</seg>
<seg id="173">In such cases, there are reasonable grounds for suspecting that goods have been fictitiously exported for the purpose of wrongfully claiming a VAT deduction.</seg>
<seg id="174">5. Control of imports and exports of goods and services within the scope of control of selected financial and tax authorities</seg>
<seg id="175">5.1. Control sample</seg>
<seg id="176">In order to verify the fulfilment of the obligations of tax entities in the import and export of goods and services and to evaluate the level of cooperation between the tax and customs authorities, the files of tax entities were selected at the audited financial and tax offices according to the following criteria:</seg>
<seg id="177">1. tax subjects were selected from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia: (a) with the highest volume of imports, (b) with the highest amount of VAT charged, (c) with the highest volume of exports,</seg>
<seg id="178">2. tax entities were selected from the register of the tax or tax authorities according to the amount of: (a) VAT deductions applied on importation, (b) excess VAT deductions applied, (c) VAT refund entitlement, (d) VAT exemption applied on exportation,</seg>
<seg id="179">3. tax entities that have been subject to a tax audit.</seg>
<seg id="180">The sampling was carried out irrespective of the country of destination, with a focus on risky commodities.</seg>
<seg id="181">5.2. Inspection findings in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="182">An overview of imports into the Czech Republic and exports from the Czech Republic for risky commodities in 2002 and 2003 is given in the following table:</seg>
<seg id="183">5.2.1. Inspection of selected sample at financial offices</seg>
<seg id="184">The SAO focused on:</seg>
<seg id="185">- the procedure of the tax authorities in verifying the correctness of reported VAT,</seg>
<seg id="186">- cooperation between the tax authorities and the customs administration,</seg>
<seg id="187">- comparison of data from the customs database with the JCD database at the tax offices, focusing on the comparison of the declared value, the application of the correct VAT rate following the customs classification of goods or services, or comparison of the data on the JCD and the accompanying invoices with the data in the customs database,</seg>
<seg id="188">- comparison of data from VAT returns on transactions carried out and received from abroad with data in the JCD database at tax offices or in the customs database;</seg>
<seg id="189">- how to verify the right to VAT exemption when exporting goods or providing services abroad,</seg>
<seg id="190">- a comparison of the volume of exports of goods or services declared in VAT returns with data from the customs database.</seg>
<seg id="191">The JCD database at the tax offices contained only records of those imports and exports for which taxable persons were obliged to include the import or export in the tax return.</seg>
<seg id="192">The audited tax authorities examined the files of tax subjects who had reported imports totalling CZK 60,396,379,000 in the 2002 and 2003 VAT returns and corresponding VAT totalling CZK 12,644,052,000.</seg>
<seg id="193">In addition, the files of tax entities reporting exports in the tax returns for 2002 and 2003 totalling CZK 47,323,111,000 were checked.</seg>
<seg id="194">According to the Customs Database of the Czech Republic, in 2002 and 2003, the tax subjects whose imports and exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic were examined carried out imports into the Czech Republic from the Slovak Republic with a total VAT base of 3 759 352 thousand CZK, VAT of 767 607 thousand CZK and exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic with a total statistical value of 1 989 090 thousand CZK.</seg>
<seg id="195">The identified differences between the records in the JCD database at the tax offices and in the customs database of the Czech Republic were examined as follows:</seg>
<seg id="196">- JCD items that were missing from the customs database of the Czech Republic were requested directly at the General Directorate of Customs of the Czech Republic,</seg>
<seg id="197">- JCD items that were missing from the Tax Offices database were checked for cancellations,</seg>
<seg id="198">- for JCD items for which different values were found between the customs database of the Czech Republic and the database of financial offices, the respective JCD was requested from the General Directorate of Customs of the Czech Republic in written form including the attached invoices.</seg>
<seg id="199">The audit revealed that the JCD database at the tax offices did not contain, for example, records of import JCDs with a total value of VAT of CZK 3,622,000 and records of export JCDs with a total statistical value of CZK 9,359,000.</seg>
<seg id="200">5.2.1.1. Differences found</seg>
<seg id="201">A comparison of the JCD database at the tax offices and the cumulative tax liabilities for 2002 and 2003 in the VAT returns for a selected sample of tax entities revealed the following differences:</seg>
<seg id="202">The differences in values were mainly due to:</seg>
<seg id="203">- The time difference between the realisation of imports and the exercise of the right to deduct VAT charged on the importation of goods.</seg>
<seg id="204">The taxpayer could exercise the right of deduction in respect of the importation of goods within three years of the end of the tax year in which the goods were placed under the relevant scheme or, in the case of the temporary importation scheme, within three years of the end of the tax year in which that scheme ceased.</seg>
<seg id="205">- The time difference between the realisation of the export and the moment when the taxpayer received the JCD.</seg>
<seg id="206">The taxpayer was required to enter the details of the exports carried out exempt from the obligation to apply output tax in the VAT return at the earliest for the tax period in which the goods left the territory of the country if he also had the tax document which was the JCD.</seg>
<seg id="207">- Failure of taxable persons to comply with the obligations to declare imports and exports in VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="208">In some cases, tax subjects did not include correct data on imports and exports in their VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="209">The fact that tax subjects were not required to attach JCD lists to their VAT returns made it more difficult for the tax authorities to check the right to deduct or exempt VAT.</seg>
<seg id="210">5.2.2. Synergies between financial and customs authorities</seg>
<seg id="211">During the audited period, refunds or remissions of import or export duties and VAT were made on the basis of decisions taken by the customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="212">Tax subjects were required by law to reduce the previously exercised right to deduct VAT by the amount of tax refunded by the customs office in the tax return for the period in which the tax was refunded.</seg>
<seg id="213">No legislation provided for the sending of information on changes in the amount of customs duties and VAT from customs offices to tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="214">Some audited tax offices received this information, but irregularly or with significant delays and only from some customs offices.</seg>
<seg id="215">One audited IRS did not receive this information at all.</seg>
<seg id="216">If the tax office did not receive information about changes in the amount of customs duties and VAT directly from the customs office, it did not have the data needed to check the fulfilment of the legal obligation of the tax subjects.</seg>
<seg id="217">In 2002, the customs authorities refunded VAT in the amount of more than CZK 319 million and in 2003 in the amount of more than CZK 398 million.</seg>
<seg id="218">The results of the audit showed persistent shortcomings in the activities of the tax authorities, some systemic errors in the cooperation of the tax authorities with the customs authorities and the non-fulfilment of some obligations of the tax payers submitting VAT and VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="219">In particular, weaknesses were found in the administration of VAT and VAT in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="220">a) in case of cancellation of VAT registrations, the fulfilment of the obligation of the payers to pay VAT on the commercial property registered or which should have been registered on the date of cancellation of the registration, with which the payer applied a tax deduction, was verified only rarely,</seg>
<seg id="221">(b) the tax authorities have not consistently used the possibility to carry out tax inspections or local investigations.</seg>
<seg id="222">This has in some cases led to a lack of verification of the validity of the right to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="223">(c) the official records and minutes of the oral hearing do not contain all the necessary data to substantiate the legitimacy of the excess VAT deductions applied;</seg>
<seg id="224">(d) the tax authorities did not sufficiently verify the imports and exports declared in the VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="225">5.3. Control findings in SR</seg>
<seg id="226">5.3.1. Inspection of selected sample at tax offices</seg>
<seg id="227">The SAO scrutinized or audited the selected sample for tax years 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="228">After analysing the submitted tax returns and requests for tax refunds from selected tax entities of the SAO SR, the Tax Office requested to secure the relevant JCDs documenting the import and export, invoices and proof of payment of the tax.</seg>
<seg id="229">Subsequently, the SAO scrutinized whether the submitted JCDs were registered in the customs database of imports and exports and whether the decisive facts and legal conditions were fulfilled in the application of the deduction of input tax for imports, in the refund of excess VAT deduction, in the application of the exemption from export tax and in the refund of the SPD.</seg>
<seg id="230">The SAO of the Slovak Republic audited selected cases of imports and exports of goods between the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic according to the number of JCD items and the sum of statistical values listed in the following table.</seg>
<seg id="231">In total, imports in the statistical value of 856.2 million SKK were checked, which represents 5.11% of the total value of imports of selected commodities from the Czech Republic into the SROV.</seg>
<seg id="232">Exports of selected commodities were checked in the total statistical value of SKK 176 million, which represents 6.87% of the total value of exports of selected commodities from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="233">In addition, 618 cases of imports of other goods and services (mainly white goods, packaging technology and software) from EU countries to Slovakia were checked for a total statistical value of SKK 532.8 million.</seg>
<seg id="234">5.3.2. Synergies between tax and customs authorities</seg>
<seg id="235">The SAO scrutinized the tax offices and found discrepancies between the data recorded in the customs database of the Slovak Republic and the data reported in specific VAT returns, e.g.:</seg>
<seg id="236">– 2 tax subjects (natural persons) declared imports of goods with a total value of SKK 1 589 261 in their tax returns, on the basis of which they claimed a refund of excess VAT.</seg>
<seg id="237">During local investigations carried out at the initiative of the SAO, tax subjects were not able to prove to the tax office the validity of the application of the input tax by the relevant documents on the completion of imports and payment of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="238">- the tax entity (s. r. o.) in the tax return for the tax period January 2003 declared the received taxable transaction in the value of SKK 77 167 576, the export of goods in the value of SKK 18 006 041 and applied an excess VAT deduction in the amount of SKK 17 157 101.</seg>
<seg id="239">It is apparent from the VAT returns filed for 2003 that the difference between the volume of purchases and exports of SKK 59 161 535, which arose in January 2003, was not made up during the whole of 2003.</seg>
<seg id="240">In the above cases, the SAO asked the relevant tax authorities to carry out a tax audit of the applied excess VAT deductions.</seg>
<seg id="241">- in another case, the tax entity (s. r. o.) for the tax period January to June 2002 indicated in the VAT returns the export of goods with a total value of SKK 87 199.</seg>
<seg id="242">A verification in the customs database of the Slovak Republic revealed that the taxpayer had exported a statistical value of SKK 296 747 during that period.</seg>
<seg id="243">The Tax Office carried out several on-the-spot inspections at the company's registered office and found that the company's managing director (a UK citizen) had travelled and the company had left the leased premises without terminating the lease in August 2002.</seg>
<seg id="244">At the time of the SAO audit, the tax administrator filed a report with the law enforcement authorities on suspicion of tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="245">The SAO of Slovakia, based on the results of the audit at selected tax offices, states that the biggest problems in the administration and control of VAT and VAT were mainly in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="246">- failure to make use of the possibility to carry out VAT tax audits on problematic tax subjects, in particular in cases of application of a high value of excess VAT deductions;</seg>
<seg id="247">- the tax inspection reports did not contain an inventory of the documents checked</seg>
<seg id="248">- JCD on import and export of goods,</seg>
<seg id="249">- insufficient screening of declared imports and exports of goods in tax returns;</seg>
<seg id="250">- a lengthy procedure for tax authorities to take decisions, in particular in the context of the assessment procedure, with the consequence that the right to assess penalties is extinguished;</seg>
<seg id="251">- non-compliance with legal conditions when granting tax deferrals,</seg>
<seg id="252">- failure to compensate VAT arrears within the deadline for the refund of excess VAT,</seg>
<seg id="253">- insufficient use of all forms of security and recovery of tax arrears.</seg>
<seg id="254">On the basis of the audited shortcomings, the SAO of the Slovak Republic requested the relevant tax authorities to carry out a tax audit of VAT with a focus on the validity of applied excess VAT deductions for 14 tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="255">Measures were taken at all audited tax offices to remedy the deficiencies detected by the audit, the performance of which will be monitored and audited by the SAO SR.</seg>
<seg id="256">6. Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="257">International cooperation has made it possible to examine trade transactions between trading partners from both countries and has highlighted shortcomings in the registration of imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="258">The inspections also revealed persistent deficiencies in the fulfilment of the obligations of VAT and VAT payers, in the activities of the financial and tax authorities, in the system of cooperation and exchange of information between tax and customs administrations, which ultimately reduced the effectiveness and efficiency of tax inspections.</seg>
<seg id="259">The findings also showed that the tax authorities in the Czech Republic have at their disposal within the tax information system basic data on imports and exports from the customs database of the Czech Republic. In SR, there is no similar system for transmitting information on imports and exports of goods between customs and tax administrations.</seg>
<seg id="260">The procedure for verifying the performance of the VAT and VAT administration was not the same due to the different legislation and conditions in the two countries.</seg>
<seg id="261">The SAO verified the necessary data from information obtained at the Czech Customs Administration and from documents available at audited financial offices. The SAO verified the execution of commercial transactions from documents of tax entities requested through tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="262">If irregularities were found, he asked the tax authorities to carry out tax inspections.</seg>
<seg id="263">Parallel controls carried out in the area of VAT and SPD have assessed the state of administration of these taxes in the period prior to accession to the European Union and pointed to the need for further cooperation in this area.</seg>
<seg id="264">Mutual cooperation will be further enhanced in the monitoring of the activities of the financial and tax authorities in connection with the adoption of the new VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="265">One of the new obligations relating to the delivery of goods to other Member States of the European Union is the submission of a so-called recapitulative statement.</seg>
<seg id="266">This declaration must be made by all VAT payers who have made a supply of goods to a person registered for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="267">Tax administrators are obliged to enter the data from the recapitulative statements into the VIES (VAT Information Exchange System), to which tax administrators from the Member States of the European Union have access.</seg>
<seg id="268">The tax or tax authorities then have the possibility to compare these data with the data contained in the submitted VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="269">Furthermore, this system is used to verify the validity of the VAT registration number of persons registered for VAT, to verify the validity of the VAT exemption applied to the supply of goods to another Member State and to check the proper taxation of goods.</seg>
<seg id="270">The implementation of parallel audits showed the possibilities of cooperation between the SAO and the SAO of Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="271">The results of these control actions will be confronted with the outputs of the upcoming control actions, which will focus, among other things, on the examination of the VIES system, which is intended to prevent tax evasion in so-called "intra-community deliveries".</seg>
<seg id="272">Given the importance of VAT and SPD for budgetary revenue, control activities need to focus primarily on monitoring and identifying risk areas in order to reduce the scope for tax evasion of indirect taxes.</seg>
<seg id="273">Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="274">This report was drawn up in the Czech, English and Slovak languages and signed by the Vice-President of the Supreme Audit Office and the President of the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
</p>
