<doc docid="testsuite-segment_65-KA_04_23" genre="news" origlang="cs" sysid="CUNI-Transformer2020">
<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the results of the check in asylum facilities in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">State property and funds intended for securing the activities of the Administration of Refugee Facilities of the Ministry of the Interior</seg>
<seg id="3">Audit action No. 04/23 "State property and funds intended for securing the activities of the Refugee Facilities Administration of the Ministry of the Interior"</seg>
<seg id="4">Control action No 15/2004 "Control of hospodárenia with the property of the state and financial means intended to provide asylum and temporary refuge cudzincom in SR"</seg>
<seg id="5">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="6">Population migration is one of the global phenomena that have become an inseparable part of the current development phase of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="7">It is mainly caused by the flight of citizens from their country of origin or last permanent residence from persecution, in particular for racial, religious, national, political reasons, as well as from the consequences of military conflicts and ethnic cleansing.</seg>
<seg id="8">Their aim is to obtain asylum and integration into society, especially in one of the advanced democratic countries of Europe.</seg>
<seg id="9">A large group also consists of foreigners whose migration is caused by unfavourable economic and living conditions.</seg>
<seg id="10">Migration is not a new phenomenon.</seg>
<seg id="11">The adoption of the 1951 Geneva Agreement and the 1967 New York Protocol on the Status of Refugees, by which the governments of the signatory countries undertook to apply them in their foreign policy orientations, already provided concrete principles for refugee assistance.</seg>
<seg id="12">The Czech and Slovak Federative Republic ratified the New York Protocol in 1991 and the Geneva Agreement in 1992.</seg>
<seg id="13">After the split in 1993, both the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic declared their position on the refugee issue by continuing to comply with the adopted international documents and confirmed their binding force within the framework of national legislation by a legal act.</seg>
<seg id="14">Both republics have enshrined the granting of asylum in their constitutional laws.</seg>
<seg id="15">Parallel checks carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic focused on the asylum process and related issues, the results of which are contained in a joint final report.</seg>
<seg id="16">The cooperation between the SAIs of both countries was implemented on the basis of the "Contract for Cooperation in Control Activities" (hereinafter referred to as "the Contract") concluded in April 2004.</seg>
<seg id="17">The two Parties have undertaken in the Treaty to provide each other with information on the legislation governing the asylum procedure in the other Contracting Party, selected statistics on the number of asylum seekers and the results of the asylum process, as well as information on asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="18">The aim of the parallel control action was to identify the same problem areas and to highlight the consequences that this entails for population migration.</seg>
<seg id="19">Cooperation consisted of the unification of the programme of control actions, the exchange of information to the extent provided for in the Treaty and the preparation of a joint final report on the outcome of the controls.</seg>
<seg id="20">During the first joint meeting, which took place from 5.4. to 7.4.2004, the same topics of audited issues and control procedures were established in the preparation of audits.</seg>
<seg id="21">At the second meeting, which took place from 28.6 to 30.6.2004, the common points for the programme of the audit action were specified.</seg>
<seg id="22">During the third joint meeting, which took place during the audit operation from 8.11 to 10.11.2004, an exchange of experience from the on-going inspections took place.</seg>
<seg id="23">The forms of the outputs from the checks have been specified and the structure and content of the Joint Final Report, which was drawn up between 14.2 and 17.2.2005 at the last joint meeting, have been preliminarily established.</seg>
<seg id="24">The checks were carried out in parallel between September 2004 and January 2005.</seg>
<seg id="25">In the Czech Republic, the audit was carried out by inspectors of the Defence and Security Department and selected territorial departments.</seg>
<seg id="26">The audited bodies were the Ministry of the Interior (hereinafter referred to as "MV") and the Refugee Facilities Administration of the Ministry of the Interior (hereinafter referred to as "SUZ").</seg>
<seg id="27">In the Slovak Republic carried out the inspection of the section of defence, vnútra and štátnych úradov.</seg>
<seg id="28">The audited entity was the Migration Office of the Ministry vnútra SR (MÚ).</seg>
<seg id="29">The audited period covered the years 2001, 2002 and 2003 (the audited period).</seg>
<seg id="30">In some cases, statistical data covering a longer period of time are also used in the joint report.</seg>
<seg id="31">2. Recapitulation of control results</seg>
<seg id="32">2.1. Evaluation of control activities</seg>
<seg id="33">- the asylum process, - the asylum facilities, - the management of state funds and assets, - the internal control system.</seg>
<seg id="34">The mutual exchange of gained experience between the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic took place at the stage of preparation and implementation of the audit actions.</seg>
<seg id="35">This exchange allowed a more thorough evaluation of the submitted documents and an analysis of the causes of the identified differences in the security of the asylum process.</seg>
<seg id="36">This made it possible to focus on the crucial issues affecting the activities of asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="37">Ultimately, this had a positive effect on the quality of the audit work carried out.</seg>
<seg id="38">2.2 Summary of control results</seg>
<seg id="39">The harmonisation of the asylum law of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic with European Union (EU) documents has been the subject of European Commission evaluation reports on the preparedness of both countries for accession to the EU.</seg>
<seg id="40">Legislation in this area has continued since both countries joined the EU, with a view to further alignment with EU law.</seg>
<seg id="41">The number of asylum seekers in the Czech Republic increased significantly in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="42">In the Slovak Republic, the number of applicants has been on a steadily increasing trend, with a significant increase in applicants in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="43">The Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, within the meaning of international agreements, provide financial and material security to asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="44">The national budget of both countries allocates the necessary funds for this purpose.</seg>
<seg id="45">The amount of expenditure drawn from the national budget of both countries is influenced mainly by the number of applicants, the duration of the asylum procedure until the granting or non-granting of asylum, as well as the state of health of the applicants.</seg>
<seg id="46">Some of the levies collected are comparable in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="47">The Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic established asylum facilities in which they gradually created suitable conditions for the stay of the asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="48">Asylum facilities shall provide asylum seekers with accommodation, meals, health care and basic material and hygiene equipment during their stay.</seg>
<seg id="49">At the same time, free-time courses are organised and cultural and sporting opportunities are created for applicants.</seg>
<seg id="50">Asylum facilities include reception and residence centres and, in the Czech Republic, integration centres.</seg>
<seg id="51">The cost per day of stay depends on the availability and facilities of the centre and is comparable in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="52">In the Czech Republic, the capacity of asylum facilities is basically stabilised.</seg>
<seg id="53">In the Slovak Republic, it is expected to increase by almost 1 000 places in the next two years.</seg>
<seg id="54">The aim is to create the conditions for applicants, a growing number of whom are expected to continue in the coming years in the context of the application of the Dublin Convention.</seg>
<seg id="55">In the Czech Republic, the largest part of the approved budget expenditure was spent on the provision of services. The main expenditure under this heading was the cost of accommodation and meals for applicants in the asylum facilities operated under the contract, the cost of health care provided to asylum seekers and the cost of a permanent security service for the protection of asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="56">Expenditure on salaries, payments for work carried out and insurance premiums also accounted for a significant share of total expenditure.</seg>
<seg id="57">In the Slovak Republic, the budgetary management of the security of the migration policy and the asylum process was marked by many budgetary measures that addressed the justified demands related to the increase in the number of asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="58">Expenditure on wages, salaries and insurance, expenditure on materials and services and expenditure on security services accounted for a significant share of current expenditure.</seg>
<seg id="59">The results of the audit in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic highlighted some similar shortcomings that did not have a major impact on the financial management and management of state assets.</seg>
<seg id="60">These were deficiencies in particular in the use of State Budget funds contrary to the purpose for which they were intended by the Act on the State Budget, where current expenditure covered actions having the character of technical evaluation of fixed tangible assets.</seg>
<seg id="61">The Act on Accounting in Inventory and in Non-Compliance with Chart of Accounts was also violated.</seg>
<seg id="62">In the Czech Republic, minor deficiencies were also found in the disposal of state property when it was passed on to another person without a contract.</seg>
<seg id="63">Failure to comply with the deadline for reporting changes to the Land Registry data violated the Land Registry Act and leaving waste for disposal to a person who was not a person authorised to handle waste was a violation of the Waste Act.</seg>
<seg id="64">Furthermore, in the Slovak Republic, deficiencies in the provision of unreasonably high advances for electricity and gas consumption, deficiencies in public procurement and in the management of state assets were found when the state's records were not sufficiently secured and the method of disposing of unneeded assets was not demonstrated.</seg>
<seg id="65">The internal control system has been ensured in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic within the meaning of the generally binding legislation in force, which regulates the way financial control is carried out.</seg>
<seg id="66">No deficiencies were found in the submitted written documentation.</seg>
<seg id="67">The Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic, despite some shortcomings, evaluate positively the progress of SUZ and MU in providing services for asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="68">Based on the findings of the audit, the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic note that, despite the significant increase in the number of asylum seekers in recent years, the respective organisational units of both countries have managed the tasks related to the care of asylum seekers to an adequate level.</seg>
<seg id="69">The evaluation shows that the system is functional and stable.</seg>
<seg id="70">The results of the audit were discussed with interested statutory representatives of the relevant organisational units of the state on the Czech and Slovak sides.</seg>
<seg id="71">Based on the results of the audit, we recommend that the positive methodological experience of the audit be used for further joint audit actions within the framework of international cooperation of supreme audit institutions.</seg>
<seg id="72">3. Legislative framework</seg>
<seg id="73">In both the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, the right of asylum is based on the 1951 Geneva Convention (Convention Relating to the Status of Refugees and the 1967 New York Protocol).</seg>
<seg id="74">The first legislation was implemented by Act No. 498/1990 Coll., on Refugees.</seg>
<seg id="75">In the Czech Republic, Act No. 325/1999 Coll., on Asylum and on the Amendment to Act No. 83/1991 Coll., on the Police of the Czech Republic, has been in force since 1 January 2000.</seg>
<seg id="76">This Act has been amended a total of five times (by Act No 2/2002 Coll., Act No 217/2002 Coll., Act No 320/2002 Coll., Act No 519/2002 Coll., and Act No 222/2003 Coll.).</seg>
<seg id="77">Two other amendments to Act No. 325/1999 Coll., on Asylum, are currently in the legislative process, and the adoption of further amendments will be linked to European legislation.</seg>
<seg id="78">At the time of the creation of Act No 325/1999 Coll., on Asylum, the area of asylum was part of the 3rd pillar of the EU and asylum documents were political documents in terms of binding force.</seg>
<seg id="79">Already during the adoption of this law, efforts were made to make it as compatible as possible with EU law.</seg>
<seg id="80">A major change for asylum policy within the EU was the transfer of asylum issues from the 3rd to the 1st pillar, when the right of asylum became part of Community law from 1.5.1999 on the basis of the Treaty of Amsterdam.</seg>
<seg id="81">This shift has triggered the need to create appropriate legislation, i.e. to create legal instruments with appropriate legal force.</seg>
<seg id="82">The compatibility of Czech asylum law with EU documents has been the subject of regular evaluation reports by the European Commission.</seg>
<seg id="83">Key Community regulations in the area of asylum were adopted shortly before or after the Czech Republic's accession to the EU and their transposition deadline had not yet expired at the time of the Supreme Audit Office's audit.</seg>
<seg id="84">Once they have been implemented into Czech law, the Czech Republic will be obliged to notify the European Commission of how it has transposed them.</seg>
