<seg id="1">Joint Report on Parallel Checks on Motorway Construction Expenditure Prague – Dresden</seg>
<seg id="2">Opening Word</seg>
<seg id="3">Without trans-European transport networks, a modern, dynamic and, above all, united Europe would be hard to imagine.</seg>
<seg id="4">Quality transport networks are a prerequisite for maintaining and raising the standard of living of Europeans.</seg>
<seg id="5">Creating the conditions for fast, safe, reliable and cheap transport of people and goods is an important task for the state administration.</seg>
<seg id="6">It is a very demanding task both in organisational and technical terms and in financial terms.</seg>
<seg id="7">European efforts at sustainable mobility often find it difficult to compromise with Europe's interest in maintaining a healthy and human-friendly environment.</seg>
<seg id="8">The construction of transport infrastructure, also thanks to the necessary measures for the benefit of the environment, is financially demanding.</seg>
<seg id="9">Considerate procedures and decision-making by the state administration in the preparation and acquisition of transport constructions can bring significant savings in public financial resources that can be used for the benefit of citizens in other ways.</seg>
<seg id="10">One of the roles of audit institutions is to actively identify deficiencies that have led to lower than achievable economy, efficiency and effectiveness of expenditure on transport infrastructure construction.</seg>
<seg id="11">The audit institutions should not only alert the public administration to the shortcomings identified, but recommend measures to improve the situation, for the benefit of citizens, for the benefit of Europe.</seg>
<seg id="12">Short Summary</seg>
<seg id="13">The two supreme audit institutions of the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as Germany and the Czech Republic), the Bundesrechnungshof (hereinafter referred to as BRH) and the Supreme Audit Office (hereinafter referred to as the SAO), carried out parallel audits of expenditure on the construction of the Prague-Dresden motorway (motorway D 8 in the Czech Republic and motorway A 17 in Germany) in 2005 and 2006.</seg>
<seg id="14">The motorways are connected by a border bridge co-financed by both countries.</seg>
<seg id="15">Thanks to cooperation with the SAO, BRH was able to carry out a thorough check of the effectiveness of the funds spent on the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="16">Based on the close cooperation with BRH, the SAO obtained the necessary data on the German costs of bridges and tunnels for comparative purposes.</seg>
<seg id="17">The Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany concluded a contract for the construction of a border bridge in 2000.</seg>
<seg id="18">According to the construction process, the completion date was finally scheduled for the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">However, in the course of awarding the contract, the Road and Motorway Directorate of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the RMD) made errors which led to an extension of the competition period and a shortening of the construction period.</seg>
<seg id="20">The contract with the contractor was therefore signed later than expected.</seg>
<seg id="21">The contractor agreed to build the bridge in a shorter time and ensure its completion in 2006.</seg>
<seg id="22">As a result, however, the RMD had to accept a significant increase in the price of the bridge.</seg>
<seg id="23">As part of the joint inspection work, the prices of bridges on the D 8 and A 17 motorways were compared on the basis of the conversion per square metre of the bridge construction area.</seg>
<seg id="24">Statistical analysis of prices made it possible to identify bridges with high costs per square metre of area.</seg>
<seg id="25">Analysis revealed that the border bridge was the most expensive bridge in the group of large bridges with a length of over 100 meters.</seg>
<seg id="26">The price increase could also be attributed to the delay in the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="27">When analysing the tunnel construction costs, the auditors found that the tunnel prices on the D8 motorway were significantly higher than those of comparable tunnels in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="28">BRH and the SAO now have a database of prices of bridges and tunnels on which they will be able to rely in future checks on the effectiveness of the funds used for transport infrastructure purposes.</seg>
<seg id="29">For the construction of bridges, both audit institutions recommend: standardization of bridge structures and use of combined steel-concrete and special structures only in cases where prestressed reinforced concrete bridges are not adequate.</seg>
<seg id="30">The main features of the collaboration were its team spirit and informality.</seg>
<seg id="31">During the parallel inspection, the auditors shared their specific knowledge and skills.</seg>
<seg id="32">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="33">This report informs about the progress and results of parallel inspections of funds spent on the construction of a motorway connecting Dresden and Prague (D 8 in the Czech Republic and A 17 in Germany).</seg>
<seg id="34">The audits focused on the economy, efficiency and effectiveness of the expenditure incurred.</seg>
<seg id="35">Parallel audits were carried out by BRH in Germany and SAO in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="36">Parallel inspections took place in 2005 and 2006.</seg>
<seg id="37">The SAO audited the economy, efficiency and effectiveness of expenditure amounting to approximately CZK 20 billion including VAT (approximately EUR 690 million) on the border section of the D8 motorway, which has the number 0807.</seg>
<seg id="38">Of this amount, € 64 million from European funds (ISPA) were planned to be used.</seg>
<seg id="39">In addition to a parallel audit carried out jointly with the SAO, the BRH audited the preparation and construction of the A17 motorway in 2003 and 2005.</seg>
<seg id="40">The funds spent on the construction of all three sections of the A17 motorway amounted to around €670 million, of which €277 million will be co-financed by European funds (EFRE).</seg>
<seg id="41">The motorway from Prague to Dresden is part of the Trans-European Transport Corridor IV. Dresden – Central and Southern parts of Eastern Europe – Istanbul.</seg>
<seg id="42">The D8 motorway runs from Prague through Ústí nad Labem to the state border.</seg>
<seg id="43">The A17 motorway runs from the Czech Republic/Germany border to Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="44">At the time of the inspection, the border sections of both motorways were under construction.</seg>
<seg id="45">These sections were put into operation on 21 December 2006.</seg>
<seg id="46">On the German side, the motorway is finished until Dresden, while on the Czech side of the D8 motorway it is not finished, because the section No. 0805 of 16.4 km through the Bohemian Central Mountains between Řehlovice and Lovosicemi is still in the preparatory phase.</seg>
<seg id="47">According to the plan, section No.0805 between Prague and Ústí nad Labem is to pass through the protected landscape area of the Bohemian Central Mountains.</seg>
<seg id="48">According to forecasts made in the Czech Republic in 2001, the traffic intensity on the border section No 0807 of the D 8 motorway should be 22 940 vehicles per day in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="49">According to German forecasts, traffic at the Czech border will total about 25,000 vehicles per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="50">In 2000, Germany and the Czech Republic concluded an agreement between the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic on the interconnection of the German motorway A 17 and the Czech motorway D 8 at the common state border by the construction of a border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="51">Both countries are involved in the construction of the bridge, so the control of the construction of this bridge was an important aspect of the parallel checks carried out by both control institutions.</seg>
<seg id="52">Cooperation between BRH and SAO</seg>
<seg id="53">Since mid-2005, the two supreme audit institutions have been discussing close cooperation in the inspection of the construction of the motorway connecting Prague and Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="54">Both sides had serious reasons for such cooperation:</seg>
<seg id="55">1.</seg>
<seg id="56">Germany participates financially in the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="57">Its planning and construction rests on the RMD.</seg>
<seg id="58">Therefore, BRH itself did not have the opportunity to carry out an inspection of that construction project.</seg>
<seg id="59">2.</seg>
<seg id="60">The SAO did not have the comparative database needed to assess whether the funds were used economically in terms of the overall level of costs for bridges and tunnels on D 8.</seg>
<seg id="61">3.</seg>
<seg id="62">The SAO needed to make sure that the expenditures were effective, taking into account the main technical parameters of the motorway, especially the arrangement of bridges and tunnels, which should allow the same quality of travel on both sides of the border.</seg>
<seg id="63">Following preparatory negotiations, an Agreement on the coordinated control of the D 8/A 17 motorway was signed by the presidents of the two supreme audit institutions on 4 January 2006.</seg>
<seg id="64">The joint working meetings of the auditors of BRH and SAO took place during the whole year 2006 at an interval of approximately six to eight weeks.</seg>
<seg id="65">The meetings addressed current problems and tasks, in particular the preparation of a uniform methodology for the control of the prices of bridges and tunnels, the exchange of findings from the control of the construction of the border bridge and the preparation of joint reports.</seg>
<seg id="66">The continuous exchange of information was an important sign of cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="67">While BRH carried out most of the work on comparing technical parameters of bridges and tunnels and tendering procedures, the SAO prepared a methodology for controlling the prices of bridges and tunnels.</seg>
<seg id="68">The applicable legal standards for government control differ between the two countries in the way control actions are closed.</seg>
<seg id="69">For these reasons, the two SAIs drew their own audit conclusions on their findings during their inspections.</seg>
<seg id="70">This report reflects the results achieved by the parallel controls.</seg>
<seg id="71">The cooperation will be concluded by the signing of the final communiqué in the first half of 2007.</seg>
<seg id="72">Border bridge construction</seg>
<seg id="73">In a contract of 2000, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany agreed on a date of completion of the construction of the border bridge in 2005, as far as possible.</seg>
<seg id="74">The two parties then agreed to postpone the deadline until the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="75">The RMD acted as an investor.</seg>
<seg id="76">Germany accounts for 42.13% of the construction of the bridge.</seg>
<seg id="77">In the period up to 1999, the RMD proposed that the border bridge should have a prestressed reinforced concrete structure.</seg>
<seg id="78">In 1999, in agreement with its partners in Germany, the RMD agreed to a coupled steel-concrete structure.</seg>
<seg id="79">This decision was justified by the reduction of the number of double pillars from seven to five and the consequent environmental benefits of such a solution for the valley.</seg>
<seg id="80">In addition, the comparative calculations carried out by the RMD indicated that the steel-concrete coupled construction should be a less costly option.</seg>
<seg id="81">But there was an error in the calculations.</seg>
<seg id="82">They stated that the new bonded steel-concrete structure would be only 397 m long.</seg>
<seg id="83">It's actually 5% longer.</seg>
<seg id="84">During the award of the contract for the border bridge, the RMD made serious errors.</seg>
<seg id="85">It did not prepare procurement documents adequately describing the assessment criteria and sub-criteria for the comparison of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="86">This error resulted in the evaluation and evaluation committee and the Director-General evaluating the tenders in a subjective and problematic manner.</seg>
<seg id="87">The unsuccessful tenderer contested the results of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="88">A subsequent investigation by the Office for the Protection of Competition led to the conclusion of the contract for the award of the works contract later than originally envisaged.</seg>
<seg id="89">This meant that the 2004 summer construction season, after evaluation of the bids, was wasted and the time allocated for construction was shortened.</seg>
<seg id="90">The construction company agreed to build the bridge in a shorter time, but at the cost of significantly increasing costs.</seg>
<seg id="91">The procedure offered included the double installation of the bridge superstructure, a change in the structure of the pillars and the installation and fitting-out of the assembly areas.</seg>
<seg id="92">In addition, the construction company was not able to procure the originally designed type of steel in due time.</seg>
<seg id="93">The new type of steel – at a cost of about €4 million, which had to be paid in full by the RMD – made it possible to reduce the time taken to implement the corrosion protection, which in turn made it possible to reduce the overall construction time of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="94">Compared to the net price of €18.3 million offered in the tender, the total cost of the construction of the border bridge will increase significantly as a result of the accelerated procedure and other modifications in the funding.</seg>
<seg id="95">The reduced time allocated to construction work resulted in a price increase of around €5.9 million.</seg>
<seg id="96">Currently, the net cost is around €25.9 million, not taking into account the automatic price increase (as of October 2006).</seg>
<seg id="97">Comparison of bridge and tunnel prices</seg>
<seg id="98">The two supreme audit institutions analysed the prices of bridges on the D8 and A17 motorways in order to identify bridges whose price was too high and to compare the prices of bridges on the German and Czech sides.</seg>
<seg id="99">The analysis was based on methods of mathematical statistics.</seg>
<seg id="100">Furthermore, tunnels on the D8 were compared with similar tunnels on motorways in Germany (A 71, A 38 and A 4).</seg>
<seg id="101">There are no similar tunnels on the A-17.</seg>
<seg id="102">In preparing this part of the inspection, it was important to identify precisely the relevant prices.</seg>
<seg id="103">The two supreme audit institutions have established the following principles for the comparison of bridge prices: based on the actual price paid for the bridge excluding value added tax (VAT rates differ in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic and are subject to changes); do not take into account prices for special bases of the bridge; convert prices in CZK into € according to the European Central Bank rate valid on 30.12.2005 (CZK 29 = € 1).</seg>
<seg id="104">On both D 8 and A 17 there are bridges of various constructions (steel-concrete, prestressed reinforced concrete, bonded steel-concrete and steel) and of different sizes.</seg>
<seg id="105">In order to ensure the homogeneity of the studied structures, the bridges were divided into groups according to the type of construction.</seg>
<seg id="106">Within these groups, the size of the bridge was also taken into account in the analyses.</seg>
<seg id="107">Concrete bridges were by far the most common type of construction on both sides of the border (20 bridges on the D8, 36 bridges on the A17).</seg>
<seg id="108">The analysis focused mainly on this group of bridges, as the numerical size of the set allowed the use of mathematical and statistical methods with a high degree of reliability of the results.</seg>
<seg id="109">The inspections found that the prices per m 2 of concrete bridges on both D 8 and A 17 depend on the size of the bridge (its length, area): the larger the bridge, the lower the price per m2 of bridge construction.</seg>
<seg id="110">For German bridges, the price dependence on size was stronger than for Czech bridges (see graphs below).</seg>
<seg id="111">Two concrete bridges on the A 17 and four on the D 8 have been identified and their price is significantly higher.</seg>
<seg id="112">In order to find these bridges, a method was used that allowed to find atypical values in the set of numbers, and a regression analysis that took into account the dependence of the price of the bridge on its size (for the determination of atypically expensive bridges, the distance from the regression curve upwards is decisive).</seg>
<seg id="113">However, information on the atypically high price of those bridges should only be considered as an indicator of which bridges should be targeted.</seg>
<seg id="114">In order to draw a generally applicable conclusion, the causes of the high price in each case identified should be analysed.</seg>
<seg id="115">One such cause may be inefficient administrative measures, or environmental protection requirements or any other plausible reason.</seg>
<seg id="116">Given that the Czech concrete bridges are on average longer than the German ones (see table below), the proven negative dependence of the price of the bridge on its length could lead to the assumption that the Czech bridges should be cheaper.</seg>
<seg id="117">The hypothesis of lower prices of Czech concrete bridges is also supported by lower labour costs in the construction sector in the Czech Republic compared to Germany.</seg>
<seg id="118">On the contrary, the results of the analysis show that the prices of concrete bridges on D 8 are higher than on A 17.</seg>
<seg id="119">In the course of the joint discussions, two possible causes have been identified:</seg>
<seg id="120">1.</seg>
<seg id="121">In Germany, most bridges are awarded as separate contracts.</seg>
<seg id="122">Such an award allows small and medium-sized regional firms to compete for the contract.</seg>
<seg id="123">In the Czech Republic, many bridges are awarded as part of a contract for a part of the motorway route, which is several kilometres long.</seg>
<seg id="124">Small and medium-sized companies do not participate in such a competition because the contract is too big for them.</seg>
<seg id="125">2.</seg>
<seg id="126">There is more variability in bridge construction in the Czech Republic than in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="127">In this context, the SAO found that the type of bridge construction was decided long before its construction.</seg>
<seg id="128">The decision is taken at the time when the application for a territorial decision is submitted to the RMD.</seg>
<seg id="129">Although the RMD selects types of bridges from several variants at this time, economy plays a smaller role in the decision-making process.</seg>
<seg id="130">A general conclusion on the prices of bridges in the Czech Republic and Germany could only be reached on the basis of a thorough analysis of the construction works market in both countries, which would, however, go beyond the scope of this control action.</seg>
<seg id="131">The boundary bridge is the most expensive bonded steel concrete bridge on D 8 and A 17.</seg>
<seg id="132">In the case of tunnels, it was found that tunnel prices on D 8 are twice as high as tunnels in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="133">However, a comparison of the main construction-technical parameters of the tunnels on the D8 with the tunnels in Germany did not show any significant difference.</seg>
<seg id="134">Significant price differences could be attributed to the fact that there is no real competition in the tunnel construction industry in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="135">However, the small number of tunnels did not allow for any generally applicable conclusions.</seg>
<seg id="136">Effectiveness and efficiency of the construction of the Dresden-Prague motorway</seg>
<seg id="137">A separate Czech Republic was established in 1993.</seg>
<seg id="138">In the same year, the government approved the concept of developing a motorway network.</seg>
<seg id="139">The D8 motorway was to be gradually extended from Prague to the state border with Germany.</seg>
<seg id="140">Section No. 0805 through the Bohemian Central Mountains should have been acquired before the border section No. 0807.</seg>
<seg id="141">The Czech Republic acquires the D8 motorway as part of the programme financing.</seg>
<seg id="142">In programme no. 327 220 „Construction of the D8 motorway Prague – Ústí nad Labem – state border of the Czech Republic/Germany” two objectives of the construction of the D8 motorway were set:</seg>
<seg id="143">1.</seg>
<seg id="144">to improve the connection between Prague and Ústí nad Labem – a national goal;</seg>
<seg id="145">2.</seg>
<seg id="146">Improve the connection between Prague and Berlin within the framework of the IV Trans-European Transport Corridor Berlin – Istanbul – an international objective.</seg>
<seg id="147">According to the programme, the construction of the section leading through České středohoří should have been completed in June 2008 and the construction of the border section No. 0807 in June 2007.</seg>
<seg id="148">It should be added here that the date of completion is not identical to the date of commissioning.</seg>
<seg id="149">The SAO found that the preparation of the construction of the section leading through the Czech Central Mountains is now in the stage of an official zoning decision.</seg>
<seg id="150">Environmental activists challenged the decision with lawsuits.</seg>
<seg id="151">No final judgment is given on the actions.</seg>
<seg id="152">Therefore, it cannot be excluded that the section leading through České středohoří will be completed several years later than indicated in the programme documentation.</seg>
<seg id="153">In the summer of 2006, the Czech Ministry of Transport proposed to postpone the completion date of section 0805 to 2010.</seg>
<seg id="154">As a result of these facts, the construction of the border section did not achieve the national objective of improving the connection between Prague and Ústí nad Labem.</seg>
<seg id="155">The RMD carried out an estimate of capital expenditure for the border section D 8 No 0807 and the section No 0805 through the Bohemian Central Mountains in the years 1999-2001.</seg>
<seg id="156">The estimated capital expenditure included in the investment costs amounts to about €639 million in total for both sections 0805 and 0807.</seg>
<seg id="157">Table 2: Results of the economic assessment (EIRR)</seg>
<seg id="158">All the motorways and expressways under consideration were opened, both sections of the D8 were opened in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="159">On the northern part of the border section, the traffic intensity of 18,000 vehicles per day in 2010</seg>
<seg id="160">All the motorways and expressways under consideration were opened, both sections of the D8 were opened in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="161">On the northern part of the border section, the traffic intensity of 22,000 vehicles per day in 2010</seg>
<seg id="162">All the motorways and expressways under consideration were opened, both sections of the D8 were opened in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="163">On the northern part of the border section, the traffic intensity of 25,000 vehicles per day in 2010</seg>
<seg id="164">The economic analysis carried out in 2001 was based on the assumption that the border section and the section through the Czech Central Mountains would be completed in time.</seg>
<seg id="165">At the time of the inspection, however, it is clear that the section through the Bohemian Central Mountains will not be opened at the original date.</seg>
<seg id="166">This will reduce the above EIRRs.</seg>
<seg id="167">The cost of both sections, net of VAT, as at 31.12.2005, was €897 million, i.e. 27.4% higher than the cost level used in the economic analysis in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="168">However, there is a risk that section 0805 will be run on a different, more costly route, which would affect the above-mentioned economic viability threshold.</seg>
<seg id="169">Economic analysis has shown that the construction of both sections of the motorway is economically viable with a traffic intensity of at least 18 000 vehicles per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="170">The forecast for 2008 amounted to 22 940 vehicles, but the study dealing with the issue of bypass routes for the missing section through the Czech Central Mountains counts on the traffic intensity of 12 600 to 13 750 vehicles per day, which pushes the investment below the economic viability threshold.</seg>
<seg id="171">With a higher load on bypass routes for the missing section through České středohoří, there is a high probability of congestion and thus an increase in external costs, which were not foreseen in the original economic analysis.</seg>
<seg id="172">The above mentioned reduction in revenues and increase in costs means that the already low EIRR that the construction of the border section D 8 should have had will not be achieved.</seg>
<seg id="173">Construction of the D 8 border section is therefore inefficient.</seg>
<seg id="174">The construction of the A 17 motorway also involved similar cost overruns as the two sections of the D 8.</seg>
<seg id="175">As part of the overall economic assessment of the 1992 Federal Road Development Plan for long-distance transport, the Federal Ministry of Transport of Germany calculated a cost of about €320 million.</seg>
<seg id="176">The resulting cost-benefit ratio was 4.6.</seg>
<seg id="177">In the meantime, however, costs have risen sharply to about €670 million, reducing the cost-benefit ratio by more than half.</seg>
<seg id="178">In addition to a parallel audit carried out jointly with the SAO, the BRH audited the preparation and construction of the A17 motorway in 2003 and 2005.</seg>
<seg id="179">The BRH found that the competent State approval authority had requested an off-road tunnel for the third section of A17, which was not needed.</seg>
<seg id="180">During the inspection, BRH managed to convince the Federal Ministry and the German Road Construction Administration that the tunnel was not necessary.</seg>
<seg id="181">This resulted in savings of around €10 million in construction costs alone and €0.15 million in annual operating costs.</seg>
<seg id="182">In its assessment of Section A 17, the BRH found that the construction project had not been properly prepared.</seg>
<seg id="183">This is illustrated by the following example:</seg>
<seg id="184">At the preparatory stage, the Road Construction Administration did not investigate the bedrock conditions in the Dölzschen rocks because the site was difficult to access.</seg>
<seg id="185">This was done after the tunnel excavator hit the rock.</seg>
<seg id="186">Tests have shown that the rocks inside are more weathered than anticipated during the selection process.</seg>
<seg id="187">Costly measures such as anchoring, grouting and protective nets against falling rocks had to be taken, costing around €3.3 million.</seg>
<seg id="188">The Road and Motorway Directorate had to bear the costs not only of other emergency operations, such as security measures in the rocks of Dölzschen, but also of measures that would not have been necessary if the construction project had been properly prepared first.</seg>
<seg id="189">Expenditure of this kind includes costs related to interruption of construction operations (€3.2 million), additional training of drilling personnel (€0.5 million) and rising wages and expenditure on goods due to project duration overruns (€7 million).</seg>
<seg id="190">The cost overrun thus amounted to around €10.7 million, which did not correspond to any added value.</seg>
<seg id="191">On the basis of the lessons learned from this and other audited projects, BRH asked the Federal Ministry to apply stricter guidance in its supervision of road construction works.</seg>
<seg id="192">In doing so, the Federal Ministry should give the Road and Motorway Directorates the necessary impetus to introduce quality assurance systems.</seg>
<seg id="193">Benefits of cooperation for BRH and SAO Cooperation fulfilled the intention of both audit institutions.</seg>
<seg id="194">BRH gained control knowledge about the preparation, commissioning and progress of the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="195">The two supreme audit institutions have built up a database of bridge and tunnel prices on which future controls can be based.</seg>
<seg id="196">The SAO found that the main construction and technical parameters of bridges, tunnels and the route of the D 8 motorway did not differ from those of the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="197">The auditors of the two institutions involved in the cooperation gained new experience which they can use in further inspections.</seg>
</p>
