<p>
<seg id="1">Public works contracts and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint report on the parallel audit performed by the Czech Supreme Audit Office (SAO) and the German Federal Court of Auditors (BRH)</seg>
<seg id="3">Introduction and Overview</seg>
<seg id="4">Public procurement of goods and services by contracting authorities is very important for both the state and the private sector.</seg>
<seg id="5">The role of the State is to use public resources in the most efficient and economical way and to ensure fair and regulated free competition.</seg>
<seg id="6">In the European Union (EU), public procurement is a key factor for the success of the Single Economic Area.</seg>
<seg id="7">The EU has set thresholds above which the contracting authority must meet certain requirements in order to guarantee a broad and unrestricted competitive environment across the EU.</seg>
<seg id="8">EU Member States must therefore transpose European procurement law into their national legislation and put it into practice.</seg>
<seg id="9">The Czech Republic and Germany have already done so.</seg>
<seg id="10">For public contracts below the EU thresholds, the regulation of their award remains a national competence.</seg>
<seg id="11">Moreover, public procurement is prone to corruption with a consequent high potential for harm.</seg>
<seg id="12">Therefore, contracting entities are obliged to take reasonable measures in their procurement procedures to prevent corruption and unfair favouritism (prevention of corruption).</seg>
<seg id="13">In January 2011, the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (Czech SAI – SAO) and the Federal Court of Auditors of Germany (German SAI – BRH) agreed to perform parallel audits in the area of procurement procedures and prevention of corruption in land and transport buildings.</seg>
<seg id="14">Cooperation has also focused on the area of European procurement law as transposed into national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="15">Controls included procurement below European thresholds in order to sanction the area of corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="16">The audit findings of the two supreme audit institutions are summarised in a joint report, which is, among other things, addressed to international organisations such as the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).</seg>
<seg id="17">Areas of control and institutions audited</seg>
<seg id="18">The BRH assessment is based on the sweeping inspections of the above-mentioned areas carried out by the German building authorities responsible for federal transport and land construction between 2011 and 2012.</seg>
<seg id="19">For example, highways and large-scale civil engineering projects were evaluated.</seg>
<seg id="20">The BRH included findings from past inspections in the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="21">The SAO's evaluation is based on audits carried out during the years 2008 to 2012, which focused on construction of roads, railway lines, water projects, large buildings (hospitals, cultural facilities, universities) and some other buildings in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="22">In Germany, federal public procurement is mostly carried out by provincial building authorities.</seg>
<seg id="23">In the Czech Republic, public procurement in the area of transport infrastructure is the responsibility of the state institutions for road and railway construction.</seg>
<seg id="24">In the field of building construction, public procurement is carried out by entities receiving budget funds.</seg>
<seg id="25">In both countries, the services of external experts are also used at the various stages of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="26">The evaluation should take into account differences in public procurement legislation and the specificities of the construction market in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="27">Structure of the Public Procurement Act in both countries</seg>
<seg id="28">In Germany, the conduct of European procurement procedures is governed by laws and sub-statutory standards.</seg>
<seg id="29">Procurement procedures limited to Germany shall be governed by budgetary law and the relevant administrative acts.</seg>
<seg id="30">The internal administrative rules contain numerous additional provisions for both European and national procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="31">Further details on the requirements of European procurement law and the prevention of corruption are enshrined in the so-called procurement manuals of the federal government, in which the requirements are elaborated or formulated in greater detail with regard to legal precedents in the area of procurement law.</seg>
<seg id="32">In the Czech Republic, public procurement is governed by the Public Procurement Act and other legislation relating to contracts with a value above and below European thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="33">The procurement law underwent substantial changes in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="34">The new rules reinforced the transparency of procurement procedures, opened the way for more competition and reduced opportunities for corruption during procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="35">Basic aspects of procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="36">As far as European procurement procedures are concerned, open and restricted procedures in particular need to be applied in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="37">In Germany, contracts below the European threshold are awarded in accordance with national rules (public call for competition, restricted call for tenders, negotiated procedures), but these are practically identical to the above conditions for European procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="38">Public procurement in Germany is characterised by the principle of preference for open procedures (where candidates are invited on a European scale) and public calls for participation (only in the case of national procedures).</seg>
<seg id="39">In open procedures and invitations to tender, any candidate may submit a tender.</seg>
<seg id="40">Another important feature of German procurement law is support for small and medium-sized companies.</seg>
<seg id="41">This is achieved mainly by dividing the total contract into commercially specific lots and by dividing it into sub-contracts.</seg>
<seg id="42">By awarding contracts divided into these lots, the largest possible number of candidates is given the chance to participate in the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="43">The two characteristics of German procurement law are time-tested tools for obtaining good value for money.</seg>
<seg id="44">There are more than 330,000 construction companies with 1.9 million employees registered in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="45">In the Czech Republic, the conditions of European procedures must be applied also in cases of public procurement with a value below the EU limit.</seg>
<seg id="46">An exception is the simplified below-threshold procedure, where the contracting authority may use less demanding procedures.</seg>
<seg id="47">In accordance with European law, Czech procurement law includes the conditions under which the contract must be awarded in order to ensure competition and achieve a favourable price.</seg>
<seg id="48">Current Czech legislation allows contracting authorities to choose between an open procedure and a restricted procedure.</seg>
<seg id="49">There are 85,000 construction companies registered in the Czech Republic, of which about 1,900 have 20 or more employees.</seg>
<seg id="50">Total volume of contracting authorities' public works contracts and proportion of individual procedures in both countries</seg>
<seg id="51">In 2011, the total volume of construction works in Germany amounted to EUR 7 675 billion.</seg>
<seg id="52">CZK 1,138 billion (15 %) of which was accounted for by the share of public contracts which, in addition to those awarded by the federal government, included contracts awarded by individual Länder and municipalities.</seg>
<seg id="53">The total volume of projects of federal road and land constructions (without the construction of railways and water constructions) amounted to CZK 212.5 billion.</seg>
<seg id="54">In 2011, the composition of federal works and transport contracts was as follows: 80,7 % open procedures and public calls; 12,7 % restricted management and calls;</seg>
<seg id="55">6.6% negotiated procedures and direct award of contracts; 33.2% is the share of European procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="56">The volume of public construction contracts in the Czech Republic reached 118.6 billion CZK in 2011, which was about 25% of the total volume of all construction works.</seg>
<seg id="57">In 2009, the value reached CZK 194.0 billion, which was 37% of the total.</seg>
<seg id="58">Structure of tender types in 2011: 65,1 % open procedures; 14,3 % restricted procedures; 9.5% negotiated procedures; 8.4% simplified procedures for low-threshold contracts; 2.7% other proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="59">These figures include all public supply, service and works contracts awarded by contracting authorities in 2011.</seg>
<seg id="60">These figures show that: parallel controls in both countries were targeted at a substantial part of public procurement procedures; The prevention of corruption, which must always be taken into account in procurement procedures, has a significant financial impact; it is of open importance. Procurement procedures are of key importance.</seg>
<seg id="61">Summary of main results</seg>
<seg id="62">The SAO and BRH carried out parallel audits of European works contracts with an emphasis on the prevention of corruption in their respective countries.</seg>
<seg id="63">The audits focused on comparing legislation in both countries and the EU and on the implementation of public contracts in the field of land and transport construction.</seg>
<seg id="64">The following are the key findings:</seg>
<seg id="65">The EU Public Procurement Directive has been transposed into national law in both countries (points 1 and 3.1).</seg>
<seg id="66">Preventing corruption is not only the aim of the EU directive, but also of the national procurement rules of the two countries, which differ partly in focus and detail.</seg>
<seg id="67">In both countries, the essential requirement to be fulfilled by the tender documents is to include all the information needed for the preparation of the tenders.</seg>
<seg id="68">The specification shall be neutral and shall not contain any requirements restricting competition.</seg>
<seg id="69">The procurement documents in Germany generally meet these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="70">The problem in the Czech Republic is the lack of definition of the subject of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="71">In Germany, the division of contracts into lots is required where possible in order to promote a competitive environment.</seg>
<seg id="72">According to BRH’s findings, this requirement is respected in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="73">The SAO audits showed that in the Czech Republic, very large public works in the field of road construction are awarded without being divided into parts or are divided into very significant parts. This may distort competition and lead to restrictions on only a few large companies.</seg>
<seg id="74">Such limitations of market potential may result in significant cost increases and risk unreliable price negotiations and impermissible agreements.</seg>
<seg id="75">The legislation in both countries allows contracting authorities, under certain conditions, to subcontract additional works if the need arises after the conclusion of the contract (point 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="76">In both countries, the requirements to correctly determine the type of procurement procedure are met.</seg>
<seg id="77">In the Czech Republic, contracting entities are free to determine one of the open procurement procedures, namely the open procedure or the restricted procedure, in accordance with the applicable regulations.</seg>
<seg id="78">German procurement and budget law rules enshrine the primacy of open procedures for both European tenders and national tenders, known as public calls for competition.</seg>
<seg id="79">Open tendering procedures in both countries allow more bidders to submit a bid and also reduce the risk of corruption by making it more difficult for bidders to collude illegally.</seg>
<seg id="80">At the same time, the best results in terms of value for money are achieved.</seg>
<seg id="81">In the case of large contracts where the estimated total price reaches or exceeds the EU thresholds, the audited contracting entities have always launched a European procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="82">The correct determination of the estimated value of the contract plays a very important role in the determination of the type of procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="83">In Germany, databases are used for objective pricing of public works in which values are based on completed construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="84">This is a sufficiently objective instrument.</seg>
<seg id="85">In the Czech Republic, databases are used only in the field of road construction but are not yet an effective tool (point 4.2).</seg>
<seg id="86">When awarding a works contract under European procurement procedures, it is necessary to publish prior information and a contract notice in order to strengthen competition by allowing candidates to prepare themselves in time for the submission of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="87">As a rule, the construction authorities audited complied with this requirement.</seg>
<seg id="88">In isolated cases, errors in the information released, incorrect application of provisions and/or a lack of controls may have impaired competition (item 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="89">There is a greater risk of manipulation when selecting candidates to take part in a restricted procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="90">Under EU law, the number of candidates invited must be high enough to guarantee genuine competition.</seg>
<seg id="91">The selection criteria shall be objective, non-discriminatory and published in good time.</seg>
<seg id="92">Beyond EU requirements, contracting entities in both countries should, as far as possible, rotate candidates who are invited to participate in the procedure when selecting suppliers.</seg>
<seg id="93">In Germany, there are partly very detailed requirements to prevent risks of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="94">In some cases, the audited contracting entities did not comply with these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="95">In the Czech Republic, selection decisions were not always credible (point 4.4).</seg>
<seg id="96">In both countries, contracting authorities must ensure during the procurement procedure that all candidates wishing to submit a tender receive the same information.</seg>
<seg id="97">Any agreements between those candidates and between them and third parties involved in the preparation of the specifications must be avoided as far as possible in order to avoid restricting competition by means of illegal agreements.</seg>
<seg id="98">In Germany, the measures are more thorough than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="99">However, the German contracting authorities audited did not meet this requirement in several cases (point 4.5).</seg>
<seg id="100">In both countries, the principle of cross-checking and transparency must be applied when opening envelopes.</seg>
<seg id="101">The requirements for labelling, documentation, protection and confidentiality of tenders are intended to limit the scope for manipulation and are particularly detailed in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="102">Checks in both countries found only a few cases of irregularities (point 4.6).</seg>
<seg id="103">The evaluation and evaluation of tenders is regulated procedurally in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="104">The relevant German measures are more comprehensive but have not always been respected by the audited contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="105">For example, contracting entities transmitted their tenders to third parties for consultation without prior assessment, without properly documenting any suspicious circumstances.</seg>
<seg id="106">The tenders were thus inadequately protected against subsequent manipulation (paragraph 4.7).</seg>
<seg id="107">For reasons of legal protection, tenderers must be informed about the intended contract award before the latter is finalised.</seg>
<seg id="108">This legal protection rule is also designed to prevent corruptive action.</seg>
<seg id="109">The law of the Czech Republic provides for judicial review of contract award procedures also for national tenders.</seg>
<seg id="110">Only in few cases, the notification of the enterprises was not appropriately ensured (item 4.8).</seg>
<seg id="111">The procurement documents for the audited contracting entities in both countries were not always complete or fully credible.</seg>
<seg id="112">In the case of several procurement procedures, the transparency requirements applied at European level were not always adequately respected in the minutes.</seg>
<seg id="113">Moreover, some of the weaknesses identified reduced the preventive anti-corruption function of the dossier.</seg>
<seg id="114">Contracting entities in both countries mostly fulfilled their reporting obligations (paragraph 4.9).</seg>
<seg id="115">Summary of the main principles of European procurement law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="116">European procurement law</seg>
<seg id="117">In order to ensure free competition in the EU, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted, inter alia, a Directive on the coordination of procedures for the award of public works contracts, public supply contracts and public service contracts to ensure the free movement of goods and services and a Directive on the coordination of laws, regulations and administrative provisions relating to the application of review procedures to the award of public supply contracts and public works contracts (the Remedies Directive), both of which were to be transposed into national law.</seg>
<seg id="118">The EU's general procurement principles include in particular: the requirement for a competitive environment; the requirement for equal treatment or non-discrimination; the requirement for transparency.</seg>
<seg id="119">EU procurement principles include The Directive on the coordination of public procurement procedures also includes provisions for construction projects with a total estimated value of € 5 million or more.</seg>
<seg id="120">These provisions shall affect: the content of the procurement documents; the type of procurement procedure used; the publication of certain information before, during and after the procedure; compliance with the deadline for receipt of tenders; qualification requirements that tenderers may be required to meet; criteria for selecting the most suitable tender.</seg>
<seg id="121">The legal protection of tenderers is governed by the Remedies Directive.</seg>
<seg id="122">In the event of a potential breach of procurement law, tenderers may have the contracting authority's decision reviewed in accordance with the review procedures.</seg>
<seg id="123">Both countries have transposed EU requirements into national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="124">Preventing corruption</seg>
<seg id="125">The importance of preventing corruption</seg>
<seg id="126">There is no legal definition in either country of what corruption actually means.</seg>
<seg id="127">In general, corruption is understood as an abuse of a personal (confidential) position for one's own benefit.</seg>
<seg id="128">As a rule, this means that such abuse is instigated by those who benefit from it.</seg>
<seg id="129">Corruption can be an obstacle to competition and can cause serious economic losses.</seg>
<seg id="130">Overall corruption-related damages are estimated to amount to 5% of world economic output.</seg>
<seg id="131">For the EU area, these costs are estimated at 1% of the EU's economic output.</seg>
<seg id="132">Where a contracting authority is involved in a contract, agreements restricting competition or allowing dishonest conduct may undermine confidence in the integrity, ability and overall work of the public administration.</seg>
<seg id="133">Preventing corruption is therefore an essential task for contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="134">Practices and procedures must be monitored, particularly in areas particularly prone to corruption, so that adequate measures can be taken to prevent it.</seg>
<seg id="135">Taking preventive measures and carrying out effective controls can substantially reduce the vulnerability of the decision-making process to corruption.</seg>
<seg id="136">As a rule, the award of works contracts is considered to be an area particularly prone to corruption.</seg>
<seg id="137">Measures to prevent corruption</seg>
<seg id="138">In Germany, corruption is prosecutable under criminal and labour law, in particular active and passive bribery, receiving and offering significant benefits.</seg>
<seg id="139">The German Federal Government has issued a manual of recommendations on the prevention of corruption in the federal administration, according to which the following principles are applied throughout the procurement process, outside the risk analysis: the priority of open procurement; the principle of multiple control and transparent decision-making; the separation of the planning, procurement and accounting phases; accurate and complete documentation of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="140">In addition, other measures having a preventive effect against corruption have become part of the procurement law.</seg>
<seg id="141">In 2011, the competent Federal Ministry of Information Technology introduced a system to monitor the procurement of federal roads.</seg>
<seg id="142">Using this system, data such as estimated costs, total value of the contract and involvement of private design firms can be fully recorded and analysed in order to identify potential irregularities.</seg>
<seg id="143">In the Czech Republic, corruption is prosecuted under criminal law, and the level of labour or civil law is also an option.</seg>
<seg id="144">The legal requirement of transparency, equal treatment and non-discrimination throughout the procurement process (preparation and implementation) is the most important part of preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="145">Anti-corruption measures in this area have been set out by the government in the "Government Anti-Corruption Strategy 2011-2012", which has been updated for 2013 and 2014.</seg>
<seg id="146">Some of these measures have been incorporated into the Public Procurement Act and subsequent implementing regulations.</seg>
<seg id="147">The new legislation includes the following basic provisions: lowering the thresholds for small-scale contracts; the obligation of prior notification by the contracting authority, including the justification for the contract; the prohibition on limiting the number of tenderers in restricted procedures and the abolition of the general possibility to limit the number of tenderers by drawing lots; obligation to publish contracts, including annexes; obligation to publish actual lists of subcontractors.</seg>
<seg id="148">Results of checks relating to the subsequent stages of the procurement procedure</seg>
<seg id="149">Procurement documents</seg>
