<seg id="418">Conclusions and recommendations/summary</seg>
<seg id="419">The two-stage information process with prior information and the publication of a notice of initiation is an important tool for meeting the requirements of transparency and strengthening the competitive environment in European procedures.</seg>
<seg id="420">By extending the obligation to publish prior information in the Czech Republic also for national procurement procedures and reinforcing this obligation in Germany for restricted procedures, both countries have increased the transparency of procurement procedures and improved the competitive environment.</seg>
<seg id="421">Selection of candidates in restricted procurement procedures</seg>
<seg id="422">Contrary to the open procedure, limited procurement procedures do not allow the participation of all potential candidates who would be interested.</seg>
<seg id="423">In restricted procedures, the contracting authority shall first select the potential suppliers that will be asked to submit a tender.</seg>
<seg id="424">European law requirements and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="425">EU provisions allow for a limit on the number of applicants in European restricted procedures.</seg>
<seg id="426">However, the restricted procedure requires at least five tenderers to be invited to submit a tender and, in the case of a negotiated procedure with publication, at least three potential tenderers must be invited.</seg>
<seg id="427">In any event, the number of candidates invited must be sufficiently large to ensure genuine competition.</seg>
<seg id="428">The selection criteria must be objective and non-discriminatory and published in advance.</seg>
<seg id="429">The selection of potential candidates to be invited is highly susceptible to manipulation, e.g. the preferences of some of them.</seg>
<seg id="430">Reducing competition to a few bidders can make it easier for them to collude.</seg>
<seg id="431">This has a negative impact on the outcome of the proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="432">Therefore, the contracting authority must take measures to prevent manipulation and ensure that it has effective control in order to ensure that the procedure is transparent and credible.</seg>
<seg id="433">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="434">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="435">The provisions for the selection of candidates are similar in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="436">In addition to the requirements of the European Directive, contracting entities should reward the tenderers they invite to submit a tender.</seg>
<seg id="437">Nor is it permissible to restrict competition from a regional point of view.</seg>
<seg id="438">Contracting entities shall document and justify the selection of tenderers and the selection process.</seg>
<seg id="439">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="440">In Germany it is required to invite at least three candidates in the case of a restricted procedure and several suitable candidates in the case of a negotiated procedure.</seg>
<seg id="441">Except in two cases, the new Czech regulations do not allow to limit the number of candidates approached in the case of restricted and negotiated procedures.</seg>
<seg id="442">In Germany, the ‘four eyes’ principle must be respected when selecting candidates.</seg>
<seg id="443">While one worker proposes a list, another must substantially modify the proposal, e.g. by removing a proposed candidate or appointing another.</seg>
<seg id="444">This is intended to avoid a situation where an individual can definitively identify the pool of candidates who will take part in the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="445">In the absence of such a provision, far-reaching illegal collusion between participants is allowed.</seg>
<seg id="446">The list of tenderers to be invited to submit a tender shall be confidential and shall not be divulged.</seg>
<seg id="447">Authorised independent experts are also obliged to do so.</seg>
<seg id="448">There is no similar measure or measure for the confidential treatment of the list of candidates in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="449">Under the German provisions, they may not nominate external companies but may submit proposals to the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="450">There is no such requirement in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="451">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="452">BRH</seg>
<seg id="453">Number of Leads</seg>
<seg id="454">Except in a few cases, the requirement to reach a minimum number of candidates was met.</seg>
<seg id="455">An analysis of almost 7 000 works contracts with a value below the national threshold showed that, in the case of restricted procedures, contracting authorities invited an average of 6,6 potential tenderers and, in the case of direct negotiated procedures, an average of 4,4 tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="456">Change of suppliers and regional restrictions</seg>
<seg id="457">In particular, in the area of building construction, the contracting authorities did not change the range of applicants interviewed, as they had good experience with those with whom they had previously cooperated.</seg>
<seg id="458">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="459">The contracting authorities argued that, in the case of a non-public procedure, they should ensure that they reach out to tenderers whose suitability they have already ascertained beforehand.</seg>
