<seg id="480">Summary</seg>
<seg id="481">In view of the high risk of manipulation in the selection of the winning bidder in restricted procurement procedures, both countries have put in place special measures to prevent undue restrictions of competition.</seg>
<seg id="482">The German rules limit such opportunities for manipulation by means of so-called cross-checking (the four-eyes principle), by maintaining the confidentiality of the list of candidates and by prohibiting external companies from making proposals for the selection of candidates.</seg>
<seg id="483">The Czech rules aim to prevent potential restrictions with a view to manipulation, in particular by an unlimited number of bidders.</seg>
<seg id="484">However, the audit found that some of the above rules were not sufficiently applied and that an inadmissible restriction of the pool of candidates was not prevented in some cases.</seg>
<seg id="485">Contracting entities are obliged to completely eliminate these shortcomings.</seg>
<seg id="486">Submission of tenders</seg>
<seg id="487">The stage of the procurement procedure where potential tenderers can draw up tenders on the basis of the tender documents they have received starts with the publication of the tender information and/or the invitation to tenderers.</seg>
