<seg id="603">The contracting authority must identify the most economically advantageous tender and, in particular, examine all appreciably low price tenders.</seg>
<seg id="604">Review and evaluation is particularly sensitive and susceptible to manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="605">For example, tenderers may be eliminated without a legitimate reason, or tenders that do not meet the requirements may be kept in competition.</seg>
<seg id="606">The outcome of the evaluation may be wrongly influenced by the preference or disadvantage of a tenderer, thereby preventing the selection of the most economically advantageous tender.</seg>
<seg id="607">The contracting authority must therefore take special measures in selecting the persons involved in the process and must ensure that they meet the requirements of good repute and technical knowledge.</seg>
<seg id="608">They also need to make sure that the process and the decisions taken are transparent and credible.</seg>
<seg id="609">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="610">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="611">In line with EU requirements, the relevant provisions in both countries require a step-by-step examination and evaluation of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="612">During the evaluation, the requirements to prove the suitability of the tenderers, the evaluation criteria and their weightings set out in the notice or the tender dossier may not be changed.</seg>
<seg id="613">The criteria laid down for assessing the suitability of candidates may no longer be applied.</seg>
<seg id="614">Further evaluation may only be carried out on the basis of evaluation criteria.</seg>
<seg id="615">The tenders submitted must first be examined from a formal point of view as to whether they are complete or do not include suspicious elements that might encourage manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="616">If tenderers are excluded from further examination and evaluation of their tenders, they must be informed immediately.</seg>
<seg id="617">Where the evaluation of the tenders reveals a disproportionately low tender price, the tenderer concerned must be given the opportunity to comment on the situation before any elimination of its tender.</seg>
