<seg id="648">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="649">BRH</seg>
<seg id="650">Assessment of suitability and award criteria</seg>
<seg id="651">Most of the procurement procedures examined were in line with the relevant requirements.</seg>
<seg id="652">In the case of certain recommendations made by self-employed potential suppliers, the contracting authorities did not themselves check the suitability of the tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="653">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="654">In some cases of procurement procedures, insufficient documentation was provided as to whether, in making the choice, the contracting authority took into account all published evaluation criteria or whether the selection decision was based solely on the price criterion.</seg>
<seg id="655">Selection of interested parties and confidentiality of tenders</seg>
<seg id="656">Some contracting authorities used the services of non-authorised persons, such as self-employed persons or employees of building authorities.</seg>
<seg id="657">They were integrated into the planning or implementation process of construction projects, performing functions that were to be performed exclusively by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="658">The contracting authorities tried to justify this by their insufficient human resources in the sector.</seg>
<seg id="659">In some cases, they used self-employed professionals to examine offers of services from persons who were not formally bound to preserve the confidentiality of offers and to carry out their contractual obligations with due diligence.</seg>
<seg id="660">As regards contracting authorities, there was generally no evidence of whether tenders held by self-employed professionals were available only to designated persons.</seg>
<seg id="661">Examination and mathematical control of tenders</seg>
<seg id="662">Some contracting authorities passed open envelopes for further examination to self-employed professionals without first carrying out the prescribed examination of tenders and mathematical examination and without documenting the results of such examination.</seg>
<seg id="663">In the event of any intent to manipulate, third parties could make changes to tenders which could not be identified by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="664">Examination of the documents revealed a number of cases where unusual elements in the tenders were not adequately identified or where data on prices and products were missing.</seg>
<seg id="665">Performance audits</seg>
<seg id="666">A sample check by one contracting authority revealed that in 75 % of procurement procedures, the most advantageous tenders deviated by more than 10 % from the estimated costs.</seg>
<seg id="667">One in 20 tendering procedures was cancelled due to inadequate tender prices.</seg>
<seg id="668">In many cases, there was a lack of evidence or sufficient documentation on the examination of tenders or on negotiations with tenderers for further clarification.</seg>
<seg id="669">Detailed information was also missing in many cases, e.g. on unit prices of the most important invoiced items.</seg>
<seg id="670">Changes in market prices or increases in material costs were often cited as reasons for deviations.</seg>
<seg id="671">The contracting authorities argued that the identification and demonstration of balancing prices was difficult.</seg>
<seg id="672">In the case of one call for tenders, made by an entity outside the circle of standard contracting entities, a price 66 % lower than the initial cost estimate was offered.</seg>
<seg id="673">No data were recorded on closer verification of cost or identification of reasons for deviations.</seg>
<seg id="674">In clarifying this issue, the contracting authority did not find any indication of price dumping on the part of the tenderer to whom the contract might be awarded.</seg>
<seg id="675">It was therefore not clarified whether the initial cost estimate was excessive or whether the price offered was too low.</seg>
<seg id="676">The contracting authority later classified the tenderer as a ‘low-cost company’ which was unable to meet either the quality requirements or the deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="677">In another procurement procedure, the contracting authority awarded the contract to a tenderer whose price was 35 % higher than the initial cost estimate.</seg>
<seg id="678">The contracting authority did not annul the procurement procedure, arguing that the tenderer in question could be presumed not to have based its pricing on unreasonably high costs.</seg>
<seg id="679">Suspicion of irregularities</seg>
<seg id="680">Two cases of irregularities were found in one contracting authority and reported to the firm responsible for technical supervision.</seg>
<seg id="681">In one procurement procedure, two tenderers submitted tenders containing identical price calculations, which prompted the contracting authority to exclude both tenders.</seg>
<seg id="682">The inspections did not reveal any significant shortcomings in the application of the other provisions.</seg>
<seg id="683">SAO</seg>
<seg id="684">Suitability check</seg>
<seg id="685">For many building projects, such as university buildings, roads and railways, contracting authorities did not exclude tenderers from participating in the procurement procedure even though they did not meet the requirements of the contracting authority as specified in the procurement specifications, or failed to provide evidence of qualification to the extent required, or, conversely, one contracting authority could not substantiate or explain the reason for the exclusion of a candidate who did.</seg>
<seg id="686">Rating</seg>
<seg id="687">In the case of the construction of a waste water treatment plant, it is true that the various evaluation criteria of the tendering procedure for the construction contractor were established, but they were not respected by the contracting authority during the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="688">For the railway infrastructure development action, the weightings of the evaluation criteria for the award of the contract were not determined at the start of the procedure but only at the beginning of the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="689">For the road repair project, the assessment of the criterion of ‘shortening the construction period’ was not carried out correctly.</seg>
<seg id="690">For the bidders in second and third place, the evaluation incorrectly indicated a greater reduction in construction time than indicated in their bids.</seg>
<seg id="691">Documentation of the reasons for the selection of the tenderer</seg>
<seg id="692">For the three housing promotion actions, the contracting authority did not substantiate the criteria on which it assessed the tenders received and how it selected the most suitable one.</seg>
<seg id="693">Correctness of the selection of suppliers of small-scale contracts connected with the construction of a road circuit with an expected price of up to 500 000 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="694">CZK could not be verified as the suppliers were selected only on the basis of telephone consultations on the price and the date of performance, but no documents about these negotiations were made.</seg>
<seg id="695">Summary</seg>
<seg id="696">In both countries, the rules for the verification and evaluation of bids are in line with EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="697">However, they differ with regard to the specific management steps and the choice of the individuals involved in the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="698">Unlike the Czech Republic, in Germany these steps of the procurement process are governed by stricter and more detailed requirements, especially as regards the application of the cross-principle and the protection of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="699">The same applies to the rules for verifying the appropriateness of the prices offered.</seg>
<seg id="700">In both countries, it was found in some cases that the substantive steps of the process in the verification and evaluation of tenders were not documented at all and, if so, only partially.</seg>
<seg id="701">The absence of control tools and transparency in decision-making during the examination and evaluation of tenders allows for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="702">The inspections showed serious deficiencies, such as the transmission of tenders to third parties without prior due diligence and the documentation of tenders by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="703">Where contracting entities entrust a third party with the performance of functions related to the screening and evaluation of tenders, appropriate measures and increased control of measures to prevent increased possibility of manipulation are necessary.</seg>
<seg id="704">When checking the validity of prices, the audited German contracting authorities did not in all cases use the complete set of available instruments and did not deal with their own price structure.</seg>
<seg id="705">In the Czech Republic, shortcomings were found in the evaluation of the suitability of tenders and the use of evaluation criteria.</seg>
<seg id="706">Completion of procurement procedure</seg>
<seg id="707">After examination and evaluation of the tenders, the procurement procedure is concluded by the award of the contract or the cancellation of the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="708">European law requirements and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="709">In the case of a European procedure, all tenderers must be informed in advance of the award decision.</seg>
<seg id="710">Suppliers shall have the opportunity to review the decision taken within a limited period of 10 or 15 days and to request a review if appropriate.</seg>
<seg id="711">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="712">The deadline of 10 days applies to electronic submissions and 15 days to other submissions.</seg>
<seg id="713">The contract may not be concluded before the expiry of that period or before the decision of the review procedure.</seg>
<seg id="714">Where the review body rejects the complaint and upholds the decision, candidates and tenderers must be given the opportunity to have the correctness of the application of procurement law reviewed by an independent court.</seg>
<seg id="715">This measure ensures that no contracting authority will be able to circumvent the legal protection of suppliers by swiftly implementing a procurement decision.</seg>
<seg id="716">The contracting authority shall document the course of the procedure appropriately.</seg>
<seg id="717">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="718">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="719">Both countries implemented management on information obligations.</seg>
<seg id="720">In both countries, the final decision on the outcome of the procurement procedure rests with the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="721">However, the latter cannot arbitrarily depart from the results of a properly carried out examination and evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="722">The contracting authority shall conclude the contract within a specified period of time.</seg>
<seg id="723">This is because, after that period, the tenderer is not bound by its tender.</seg>
<seg id="724">The content of the contract must not deviate from the winning bid.</seg>
<seg id="725">Unsuccessful tenderers are to be informed of the result in good time, indicating the reason why their bid was not accepted.</seg>
<seg id="726">Cancellation of a procurement procedure is permissible only if certain conditions are met, e.g. if the prices in the tenders do not correspond to the specifications.</seg>
<seg id="727">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="728">In the Czech Republic, the mandatory waiting period before the conclusion of a contract of 10 or 15 days applies to both European and national procedures.</seg>
<seg id="729">In Germany, an equivalent provision applies only to European procedures.</seg>
<seg id="730">In all other procedures in Germany, tenderers cannot be informed of the award of a contract before a decision on its EU provisions and a review award has been taken.</seg>
<seg id="731">In the Czech Republic, a procurement procedure must be cancelled if a single tender has been received or if only one tender meets the requirements for its consideration and evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="732">In Germany, a contract must be awarded even if a single tender has been received, provided that the tender fulfils the conditions set out in the procurement documents and is cost-effective.</seg>
<seg id="733">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="734">BRH</seg>
<seg id="735">The audits found few irregularities in the completion of the audited procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="736">In some European proceedings, companies have received letters of authorisation before the expiry of the notification period, which may invalidate the contract.</seg>
<seg id="737">Also, in several open procedures, empowerment letters contained modifications incompatible with the content of the tender, such as new deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="738">In some cases, contracting authorities did not meet the deadlines for awarding the contract.</seg>
<seg id="739">In one open procedure, the contracting authority selected the second most advantageous tender because a tenderer offering a price more than 50 % lower no longer wished to perform the contract at the price initially offered.</seg>
<seg id="740">SAO</seg>
<seg id="741">In one case, during the reconstruction and construction of a university, the contracting authority did not conclude a contract for work with the contractor in accordance with the draft contract contained in the tender of the selected tenderer.</seg>
<seg id="742">For some road repair and maintenance actions, the construction of a motorway and a ring road, contracts were concluded later than provided for by law.</seg>
<seg id="743">For building modifications in former military sites, the contracting authority sent a notice of selection of the most suitable tender to all tenderers after the statutory deadline had expired.</seg>
<seg id="744">Summary</seg>
<seg id="745">Both countries have implemented EU rules on the closure of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="746">Legal protection of unsuccessful candidates contributes to reducing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="747">The Czech Public Procurement Act includes the legal protection institute even in cases of contracts below the EU thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="748">In both countries it was found that the limited time limit for the conclusion of the contract was exceeded.</seg>
<seg id="749">This may cause adverse economic consequences and increase the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="750">In the future, contracting entities should eliminate such shortcomings in the conclusion of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="751">Documentation, notifications, information obligations</seg>
<seg id="752">The procurement process, with all its different stages, relevant findings and decisions, including the relevant justification, shall be documented in a transparent manner.</seg>
<seg id="753">The completion of the procurement procedure at European level must be published.</seg>
<seg id="754">The data on procurement procedures are summarised in EU statistics.</seg>
<seg id="755">European law requirements and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="756">The obligation to document procurement procedures is in line with the fundamental EU-wide requirement of transparency.</seg>
<seg id="757">Only proper and time-relevant decision-making and reasoning documentation guarantees transparency in the procurement process and, in particular, guarantees effective legal protection of the interests of each tenderer in cases where the value of the contract exceeds European thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="758">Appropriate documentation is also an essential part of anti-corruption measures, as the obligation to provide detailed reasons for individual decisions and their merits significantly reduces the scope for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="759">In the case of European procurement procedures, the contracting authority must notify the completion of the procedures to the EU’s Office of Official Publications within 48 days from the date of award of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="760">The Office publishes the notification in the Official Journal of the EU and this also fulfils the transparency requirement.</seg>
<seg id="761">The contracting authority must summarise the essential details of its procurement procedures and communicate them to the European Commission through the competent national ministries.</seg>
<seg id="762">On this basis, the European Commission publishes annual statistics to provide an overview of the development of the single market in the construction sector.</seg>
<seg id="763">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="764">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="765">Both countries have fully transposed into their national legislation the provisions of the European law on documentation and notification obligations.</seg>
<seg id="766">The provisions on documentation and notification for European statistics are almost identical in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="767">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="768">In the Czech Republic, the obligation to notify the award does not only apply to European procedures, but also to national procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="769">The notification period is only 15 days from the conclusion of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="770">In Germany, the obligation to notify procurement procedures, in addition to those that are mandatory under European law, applies only to restricted procedures exceeding the limit of €25,000 ($625,000) and direct procedures exceeding the limit of €15,000 ($375,000) including VAT.</seg>
<seg id="771">Below this limit, only interested parties shall be informed.</seg>
<seg id="772">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="773">BRH</seg>
<seg id="774">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="775">A large number of assignments have not been fully documented.</seg>
<seg id="776">The notification did not contain all the necessary information, such as the reasons for the delivery specifications and national rules.</seg>
<seg id="777">In one procedure, the contracting authority did not explain why it had concluded a contract with a tenderer whose tender did not contain the mandatory elements.</seg>
<seg id="778">Some of the required records were also missing in several cases.</seg>
<seg id="779">Publication of contract award</seg>
<seg id="780">In the case of some European procedures, the contracting authority erred in publishing the notice.</seg>
<seg id="781">In the case of several awards, there was no evidence of publication of the notice.</seg>
<seg id="782">Notification obligation</seg>
<seg id="783">The statistically verified files included the required minimum of information and were created and sent on time.</seg>
<seg id="784">Preliminary transparency</seg>
<seg id="785">In most cases, the contracting authority published information about the outcome of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="786">In the case of one contracting authority, the contract information was not published due to a communication error.</seg>
<seg id="787">It took the contracting authority six months to notice the error.</seg>
<seg id="788">Consequently, the outcome of the procedure was not made public during that period.</seg>
<seg id="789">SAO</seg>
<seg id="790">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="791">For events related to the organisation of a major sporting event, significant shortcomings were found in the documentation of the procurement procedure, such as incorrect quotation prices in the evaluation committee minutes.</seg>
<seg id="792">In addition, some documents about opening envelopes were not signed.</seg>
<seg id="793">Publication of contract award</seg>
<seg id="794">In preparation for the repair and maintenance of roads, the construction of a motorway and a ring road, the contract notices were sent out after the deadline or were not published.</seg>
<seg id="795">Summary</seg>
<seg id="796">The provisions on documentation and notification and notification obligations cover European requirements and are almost identical in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="797">This generally ensures the transparency of procurement procedures and final selection.</seg>
<seg id="798">The Czech reporting obligations are somewhat stricter compared to the German ones.</seg>
<seg id="799">The inspections revealed deficiencies substantially diminishing the value of documentation as a means of preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="800">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="801">Contracting entities should continue to enhance the transparency of their procurement procedures and fully comply with the notification and notification requirements.</seg>
<seg id="802">Summary evaluation and recommendations</seg>
<seg id="803">Parallel audits of the SAO and BRH focused on two areas that are essential for the public procurement process in both the Czech Republic and Germany, namely the application of EU procurement law and the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="804">EU legislation provides an opportunity for international competition within the EU to create a single European market.</seg>
<seg id="805">Measures to prevent corruption are not only aimed at avoiding or at reducing corruption, but also at preventing financial damage and possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the government.</seg>
<seg id="806">The audit findings of the two audit institutions – SAO and BRH – with regard to the application of the procurement law of both countries and the comparison of its relevant provisions give an internal view of common and different elements that can help both countries in further development and application of this law.</seg>
<seg id="807">Application of EU procurement law</seg>
<seg id="808">Both countries have transposed EU public procurement law into their national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="809">There is thus an important common basis for both countries to award public contracts and meet basic competition requirements. equal treatment of candidates; transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="810">Contracting entities reinforce these requirements in part by very far-reaching measures.</seg>
<seg id="811">The Czech Republic has extended the provisions on public procurement requiring a European procedure to procedures that are below the EU thresholds and are therefore governed by national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="812">However, the inspections showed that contracting entities are not always fully compliant with all relevant provisions of EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="813">German contracting authorities should continue to improve the quality of their procurement procedures in order to eliminate these irregularities, taking into account the implementation of EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="814">In the Czech Republic, the audits identified risks affecting the economy and the achievement of value for money.</seg>
<seg id="815">These include, in particular, the incomplete definition of the subject-matter of the contract, which resulted in additional works that were often unlawfully awarded, an insufficient definition of the estimated price, and the requisite qualifications, which narrowed the potential pool of tenderers and thus reduced competition in the field of transport construction in particular.</seg>
<seg id="816">Preventing corruption</seg>
<seg id="817">The joint inspections were not intended to detect cases of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="818">The reason was that both BRH and SAO did not have sufficient tools for this.</seg>
<seg id="819">However, they can check whether the competent authorities of both countries are taking measures to reduce corruption and manipulation in public procurement and how these measures are being applied.</seg>
<seg id="820">As regards the prevention of corruption, the two countries focused on different aspects.</seg>
<seg id="821">In particular, the German provisions allow for broad and unrestricted competition, transparency and controls as a central element in the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="822">In particular, the Czech regulations aim at enhancing the transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="823">BRH</seg>
<seg id="824">In Germany, there are general principles of corruption prevention that apply to the entire federal administration.</seg>
<seg id="825">These principles have also been incorporated into public procurement requirements and have been adopted to meet the specific needs of such procurement.</seg>
<seg id="826">The relevant provisions specify, sometimes with great precision, the means of complying with the requirements to prevent corruption during the procurement procedure and to select the persons involved.</seg>
<seg id="827">In the opinion of BRH, the principle of preference for open procurement procedures and calls for participation is a particularly appropriate instrument to substantially reduce the risk of corruption in public procurement, while restricting competition increases the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="828">Risk analysis and adequate controls (in particular the cross-checking principle), transparency requirements, tender documentation and various organisational measures are also effective mechanisms to prevent corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="829">The BRH therefore does not feel the need for substantial changes to the current provisions that public institutions have to comply with when awarding public contracts.</seg>
<seg id="830">Anti-corruption measures are widely applied in practice.</seg>
<seg id="831">Irregularities found in some areas highlighted weaknesses in compliance with certain requirements.</seg>
<seg id="832">Therefore, contracting entities should provide their staff with further training to familiarise them with anti-corruption requirements and further raise their awareness in this area.</seg>
<seg id="833">A significant part of the weaknesses identified relate to activities delegated by the building administration to private entrepreneurs.</seg>
<seg id="834">However, the lack of adequate controls on the delegation of powers increases the risk of abuse.</seg>
<seg id="835">Activities susceptible to manipulation and corruption should therefore only be transferred to third parties if the administration can guarantee a sufficient degree of protection against unauthorised interference.</seg>
<seg id="836">SAO</seg>
<seg id="837">In the Czech Republic, anti-corruption strategies have been adopted at government level, which also significantly affect the area of public procurement.</seg>
<seg id="838">The SAO audits took place during the period when one of the most important parts of this strategy was implemented, namely the significant amendment of the Public Procurement Act and the adoption of subsequent implementing regulations.</seg>
<seg id="839">The adopted strategy and new legislation can be effective steps to improve the situation.</seg>
<seg id="840">Under the new rules, for example, the contracting authority must justify the effectiveness of the contract, the determination of the estimated value of the contract, the adequacy of the qualification requirements, the establishment of the basic evaluation criteria and the method of evaluation of the tenders, and document and publish everything properly.</seg>
<seg id="841">Recommendations</seg>
<seg id="842">Overall, the SAO and the Czech National Bank (SAO) have a favourable opinion on ways of implementing EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="843">Their wide application in practice has confirmed that EU competition, equal treatment and transparency requirements form an appropriate basis for public procurement within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="844">The transnational model in place in the EU can also serve as a basis for similar projects aimed at facilitating and promoting international competition.</seg>
<seg id="845">Bearing in mind the great potential of material and non-material damage resulting from manipulation and corruption in connection with public procurement, both BRH and the SAO insist that it is the responsibility of contracting authorities to continue and improve measures against corruption and manipulation where possible.</seg>
<seg id="846">In particular, organisational structures and procurement processes should be continuously monitored for weaknesses and risks in order to identify and respond appropriately to the need for corrective action.</seg>
<seg id="847">Compared to the practice in Germany, it has emerged that the share of open procurement procedures in the Czech Republic, which give room to competition and substantially reduce the possibility of corrupt behaviour, should increase.</seg>
<seg id="848">The award of contracts in lots may also have a positive impact on the price achieved, where this is permissible and appropriate for the contracting authorities. A higher number of bidders puts pressure on the price achieved.</seg>
<seg id="849">The organisation of the procurement procedure also has an influence on the conduct of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="850">In Germany, it is organised by special state organisations, while in the Czech Republic, with the exception of transport constructions, it is organised by the central authorities themselves or through contractual organisations.</seg>
<seg id="851">The SAO and BRH wish to further develop their findings in their work, where appropriate, and to address them with their parliament and government beyond their joint project.</seg>
<seg id="852">Moreover, they are convinced that the principles of procurement law and their implementation, as described in this report, will also be of interest at the level of the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI), as these principles and findings are of general importance for the effective fight against corruption and for guaranteeing that public contracts are awarded under a regime of well-functioning and fair competition and that value for money is achieved.</seg>
<seg id="853">Attachments</seg>
</p>
