<doc docid="testsuite-segment_65-KA_15_33" genre="news" origlang="cs" sysid="CUNI-Transformer2020">
<p>
<seg id="1">JOINT FINAL REPORT on the Results of Parallel Inspections of the Administration of Excise Taxes in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint final report</seg>
<seg id="3">May 2017</seg>
<seg id="4">Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="5">Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="6">Opening Word</seg>
<seg id="7">The joint report presents the progress and result of international cooperation in parallel inspections carried out by the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic, focusing on the administration of excise duties in 2012-2015.</seg>
<seg id="8">Cooperation between supreme audit institutions of both countries was realized on the basis of a cooperation agreement between the SAO of Slovakia and the SAO of the Czech Republic in the performance of parallel audits focused on the administration of excise duties, which was concluded in August 2015.</seg>
<seg id="9">The topic of parallel controls was chosen based on the fact that both EU Member States are based on common European legislation in order to find out how it is applied at national level, how the excise tax administration system is set up and how the systems in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic are different.</seg>
<seg id="10">The greatest benefits of the control actions carried out were the exchange of experience, the identification of differences and the identification of good practice.</seg>
<seg id="11">Last but not least, it was beneficial to find that the international comparability of data on the performance and efficiency of excise duty administration is very limited without the implementation of parallel controls.</seg>
<seg id="12">Miloslav Kala,</seg>
<seg id="13">Karol Mitrik,</seg>
<seg id="14">President</seg>
<seg id="15">President</seg>
<seg id="16">Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="17">Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="18">on the results of parallel controls of the administration of the SPD in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="19">Summary and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="20">The legislation on excise duties in the Czech Republic and Slovakia and their administration complies with EU legislation and significantly exceeds EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="21">Differences have been found between the excise duty adjustment in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic; in the Czech Republic, it contributes to the effective administration of excise duties by verifying the economic stability of applicants for a permit and mandatory marking and dyeing of selected mineral oils and certain other oils; In Slovakia, the distribution of control stamps is simpler than in the Czech Republic and less burdensome for tax administrators.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the fight against excise tax evasion, the supervision of the movement of raw tobacco or tobacco raw material, the implementation of the fuel distributor institute and the registration of sellers of consumer alcohol packaging have proved to be good practice in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="23">Revenues from excise duties in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic are growing more slowly than other tax revenues.</seg>
<seg id="24">The EU's goals of reducing taxes on labour, introducing eco-saving measures and reducing dependence on tobacco and alcohol have not yet been met in the Czech Republic and Slovakia, not least because there is no indexation of excise duty rates in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="25">This results in a reduction in the importance of excise duties on total tax revenues and, as a result of increasing purchasing power, a real reduction in the tax burden of excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="26">The introduction of environmental measures has long been financially supported by the State, but these measures have a negative impact on excise revenue, which will have to be replaced in the future by other revenues or by a reduction in government expenditure.</seg>
<seg id="27">Administrative expenditure spent on administration of excise duties in both the Czech Republic and Slovakia has been growing for a long time, mainly due to wage growth, and their efficiency has been declining.</seg>
<seg id="28">In the SR, this efficiency is also negatively affected by expenditure on the computerisation of the administration of excise duties (IT expenditure) and by expenditure on the wages of employees performing permanent tax supervision in alcohol tax warehouses.</seg>
<seg id="29">The computerisation of the administration of excise duties in the Slovak Republic has not significantly reduced the number of tax administrations.</seg>
<seg id="30">The SAO of the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic recommend that the Slovak Ministry reconsider the validity of permanent tax supervision in alcohol tax warehouses.</seg>
<seg id="31">In the Czech Republic, the effectiveness of administrative expenditure was influenced by the fact that the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic did not apply procedures during the audited period that would lead to a reduction in the personnel requirements of the administration of excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="32">The number of comparable administrative acts of tax administrators was similar in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic in the individual years of the audited period, while the number of comparable tax entities in the Slovak Republic is about a third lower than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="33">Tax administrators in the Slovak Republic perform administrative tasks mainly in the form of physical exercise of tax supervision, while tax administrators in the Czech Republic emphasize remote supervision and risk analysis.</seg>
<seg id="34">Administration of excise duties in the Slovak Republic is administratively more demanding than in the Czech Republic and more costly due to the ratio of the number of tax transactions to the number of entities.</seg>
<seg id="35">The computerisation of the administration of excise duties in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic took place in different areas.</seg>
<seg id="36">In Slovakia, the administration of excise tax returns is fully electronized, in the Czech Republic, documents proving the taxation of selected products in free tax circulation are electronically transmitted.</seg>
<seg id="37">Both ways of computerisation support efficient administration of excise duties, and therefore the SAO of the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic recommend applying them not only in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="38">The total expenditure for the implementation of EMCS could not be compared as DG SR provided data on expenditure only for the upgrade of the system in the period 2011-2015, but expenditure was incurred before that period.</seg>
<seg id="39">Expenditure incurred in the aforementioned period for the EMCS upgrade alone was approximately 20% higher in Slovakia than the expenditure incurred in the Czech Republic for both the introduction of EMCS and the upgrade of this system in more than ten years.</seg>
<seg id="40">The excise tax administrators in the Czech Republic and Slovakia did not achieve comparable values of qualitative indicators when spending comparable expenditures.</seg>
<seg id="41">The level of supervision is comparable in both countries, but in the Slovak Republic the administration of excise duties is significantly more resource-intensive.</seg>
<seg id="42">The introduction of the electronic system for monitoring the movement of excise products (EMCS) made the administration of excise duties more efficient, but to a lesser extent in the Slovak Republic, as significantly higher expenditure was spent on the introduction of the system and its modernisation than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="43">Basic information</seg>
<seg id="44">The cooperation of the two audit institutions was carried out on the basis of the Cooperation Agreement during parallel inspections aimed at the administration of excise duties of 18.8.2015.</seg>
<seg id="45">The SAO of the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic agreed to perform parallel audits, which will primarily focus on the issue of excise tax administration and whose results will allow analysis, comparison and evaluation of the findings.</seg>
<seg id="46">The common audit issues on which the parallel controls were based were agreed.</seg>
<seg id="47">Characteristics of the subject-matter and objectives of the parallel check:</seg>
