<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the results of the parallel inspection of the VAT administration carried out in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Opening Word</seg>
<seg id="3">The Lima Declaration of 1977 stresses that supreme audit institutions (SAIs) have the power to audit all public financial operations.</seg>
<seg id="4">The Declaration calls for tax revenues to be controlled as far as possible.</seg>
<seg id="5">Organisation The European Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (EUROSAI) considers taxation to be one of the most important components of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="6">The VI EUROSAI Congress held in Bonn in 2005 addressed the audit of public revenues carried out by the SAI.</seg>
<seg id="7">The development of a specific strategy for the audit of public revenue is an important step towards optimising the control activities of the SAI.</seg>
<seg id="8">This applies in particular to taxation as the largest source of public revenue most susceptible to large losses.</seg>
<seg id="9">As national economies become increasingly interconnected and dependent, SAIs may to some extent be unable to carry out control activities without the cooperation of another State's SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="10">An example is the audit of internationally organised fraud, which causes substantial losses in the revenues of many countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">In order to combat this crime, the responsible authorities need to cooperate with each other.</seg>
<seg id="12">SAIs carrying out inspections in this area must be willing to establish closer cooperation between themselves.</seg>
<seg id="13">It was at the VI EUROSAI Congress in Bonn that the idea arose of carrying out an audit of the administration of value added tax (VAT) and the VIES system in the framework of the cooperation between the Supreme Audit Office and the Federal Court of Auditors, the Bundesrechnungshof.</seg>
<seg id="14">This was followed by careful preparation, with both parties first having to familiarize themselves with the legal environment and procedures in the administration of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="15">Based on the analysis of this information, a selection of control topics was made for inclusion in the control programme.</seg>
<seg id="16">Achieving an effective and efficient VAT administration is a long-standing challenge and individual Member States (in particular the Member States of the European Union) are looking for solutions to improve the system, simplify and make the collection of VAT more transparent.</seg>
<seg id="17">We believe that the results of our audit can serve not only to improve the work of tax administrations, but also as a basis for a proposal to improve the system of international exchange of information.</seg>
<seg id="18">Report on the results of parallel inspections of the VAT administration carried out in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="19">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="20">Inspection number: (CZ) 06/27 (D) VIII 2 – 2005 – 1215</seg>
<seg id="21">Object of control:</seg>
<seg id="22">(CZ) Administration of Value Added Tax after the Czech Republic's accession to the European Union</seg>
<seg id="23">(D) Examination of administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1925/2004</seg>
<seg id="24">Objective of control:</seg>
<seg id="25">(CZ) The aim of the audit operation in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedure of the financial authorities in the administration of value added tax after the integration of the Czech Republic into the single internal market of the European Union (hereinafter referred to as the EU) connected with the free movement of goods and services and to examine the use of the VIES system, in particular when checking the application of the right to exemption from value added tax on intra-Community supplies.</seg>
<seg id="26">(D) The aim of the audit was to examine the system of control of intra-Community value added tax, with a particular focus on administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax under the above-mentioned regulations.</seg>
<seg id="27">The result should be a report on weaknesses and recommendations for their elimination.</seg>
<seg id="28">System of exchange of information on value added tax The auditing operation was carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the SAO) and the German Bundesrechnungshof (hereinafter referred to as the BRH) in cooperation with each other on the basis of a contract concluded between the two auditing institutions on 8 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="29">The cooperation focused mainly on the examination of selected business transactions between payers from the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the Czech Republic) and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter referred to as the German Federal Republic), the use of information obtained through international cooperation between tax administrations and the comparison of the VAT administration systems of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="30">The joint final report on the results of the audits was prepared in accordance with the European Directive No. 31 for the implementation of the INTOSAI audit standards.</seg>
<seg id="31">The audited period covered the period from 1.5.2004 to 31.12.2005.</seg>
<seg id="32">Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions</seg>
<seg id="33">Parallel control in the area of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of a contract between the two SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="34">Beyond the main point - the exchange of information under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1925/2004 - the audit covered other topics, such as the registration of payers, VAT returns and recapitulative statements, which are closely linked to the main point.</seg>
<seg id="35">In addition, the audit included the legal situation in the area of international passenger bus transport and a comparison of some statistical data.</seg>
<seg id="36">A comparison of the VAT administration systems of the two countries revealed differences in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="37">1) VAT registration.</seg>
<seg id="38">While in Germany entrepreneurs are registered regardless of their turnover, in the Czech Republic the primary criterion (among others) for registration is exceeding the limit set in the VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="39">In the Czech Republic, payers are assigned only one tax identification number, which they also use in intra-community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="40">In Germany, taxpayers are assigned a tax number when registering for VAT, serving only for commercial transactions in the territory of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="41">If a German payer intends to carry out intra-community transactions, he must apply for a special identification number, the so-called VAT ID.</seg>
<seg id="42">As different forms of registration cause problems, the playing field should be levelled across the EU (see 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="43">2) International passenger bus transport.</seg>
<seg id="44">In the Czech Republic, international passenger bus transport is exempt from VAT with the right to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="45">In Germany, the part of the transport which takes place on German territory is subject to VAT.</seg>
<seg id="46">Efforts should be made at EU level to harmonise the situation within the meaning of Article 393 of Council Directive 2006/112/EC on the common system of VAT (see 4.2).</seg>
<seg id="47">3) VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="48">While in the Czech Republic taxpayers file VAT returns only for individual tax periods (months or quarters), in Germany taxpayers are obliged to file so-called preliminary VAT returns (monthly or quarterly) and after the end of the calendar year they have to file an annual VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="49">Unlike the Czech Republic, taxpayers in Germany are obliged to submit preliminary tax returns electronically.</seg>
<seg id="50">The introduction of an obligation to submit VAT returns electronically in the Czech Republic would increase the efficiency of the Czech tax administration (see 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="51">(4) Summary reports.</seg>
<seg id="52">While in the Czech Republic payers file summary reports at financial offices, in Germany payers file summary reports at the Customs Office.</seg>
<seg id="53">The data from the recapitulative statements are therefore available to the tax authorities in the Czech Republic immediately after their submission.</seg>
<seg id="54">The information from the recapitulative statements is only available to the German tax authorities after they have been processed into the CLO.</seg>
<seg id="55">Combating VAT fraud requires up-to-date information on intra-community transactions to be available as soon as possible.</seg>
