<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the outcome of international cooperation in excise duty administration inspections between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in 2006</seg>
<seg id="2">Opening Word</seg>
<seg id="3">The joint report informs about the progress and outcome of international cooperation in parallel inspections carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic, aimed at the administration of excise duties in the period after the accession of both countries to the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="4">The cooperation was implemented on the basis of a cooperation agreement on control activities concluded in February 2006.</seg>
<seg id="5">The subject of parallel controls was chosen in view of the fundamental change in the system of collection of excise duties which took place in the context of the integration of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic into the internal market of the European Union as from 1 May 2004.</seg>
<seg id="6">The functioning of the European Union's internal market requires the free movement of goods, including excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="7">The basic principle is to allow goods to circulate unencumbered up to the date of their final supply.</seg>
<seg id="8">In accordance with that principle, the new legislation adopted in both countries allows the movement of goods under tax supervision under a suspension arrangement.</seg>
<seg id="9">The system places great demands on the tax authorities and presupposes close cooperation between the competent administrative authorities of the Member States in the fight against tax fraud in this area.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the outcome of international cooperation in excise administration controls for the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005 1.</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">Control number: (CR) 05/34 (SR) 48/11</seg>
<seg id="13">Subject of the audit: (CR) Administration of excise duties (SR) Procedure of customs authorities in administration of excise duties</seg>
<seg id="14">The Supreme Audit Office (SAO) of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the "SAO") and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the "SAO SR") concluded the "Contract on Cooperation in Audit Activities" on 8 February 2006.</seg>
<seg id="15">The subject of the contract was cooperation in parallel audits “Administration of excise duties”, included in the audit plan of the SAO-CR for 2005 under No. 05/34, and “Control of the procedure of the customs authorities in the administration of excise duties”, included in the audit plan of the SAO-CR for 2006 under No. 48/11.</seg>
<seg id="16">Parallel checks had the character of a coordinated check.</seg>
<seg id="17">The cooperation consisted in the exchange of information which could not be obtained by the contracting parties during an inspection of the administration of excise duties in their national territory and in the preparation of a joint final report on the outcome of the inspections in the sense of the European implementing directives for the implementation of the INTOSAI auditing standards - Directive No 31.</seg>
<seg id="18">On the territory of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as "the Czech Republic"), the auditing groups from the State Budget Department and the territorial departments of Central Bohemia, Southern Bohemia, Western Bohemia, Northwest Bohemia, Northeast Bohemia, Southern Moravia, Central Moravia and Northern Moravia performed the auditing in the period from 7 February to 2 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">27 auditors were involved in the audit.</seg>
<seg id="20">The audited bodies were the Directorate-General for Customs (‘DG’) and 11 tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="21">Within the DG, 12 selected customs offices out of a total of 54 were audited.</seg>
<seg id="22">The auditing operation on the territory of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the Slovak Republic) was carried out by the Finance and Taxation Section of the SAO of Slovakia in cooperation with the SAO of Slovakia Banská Bystrica and Košice at 5 customs offices out of a total of 9 in the period from 13 February to 2 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="23">Eight inspectors were involved in the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="24">The aim of the parallel controls was to examine the customs authorities' handling of excise duties and compliance with the relevant legislation in force in both countries and in the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="25">International cooperation was focused on the procedure of tax administrators when supervising the transport of excise goods, in particular on the registration of initiated and terminated movements under the conditional exemption regime, and on the exchange of information within the framework of mutual administrative assistance between the excise tax administrators of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="26">2. Administration of excise duties</seg>
<seg id="27">The administration of excise duties in the Czech Republic was performed by the financial authorities until 31 December 2003.</seg>
<seg id="28">Since 1 January 2004, this agenda has been taken over by the customs authorities, which have so far collected excise duty only on importation.</seg>
<seg id="29">In the Czech Republic, mineral oils, alcohol, beer, wine and intermediate products and tobacco products are subject to excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="30">The state budget revenue from excise duties in the Czech Republic totalled CZK 82.8 billion in 2004, and excise duties accounted for 19.5% of the state budget revenue from taxes and duties amounting to CZK 424.7 billion.</seg>
<seg id="31">In 2005, the state budget revenue from excise duties amounted to CZK 103.6 billion and the share of the state budget revenue from taxes and fees amounting to CZK 460.4 billion was 22.5%.</seg>
<seg id="32">In 2004, the revenue from excise duty on mineral oils for the State Budget amounted to 80% of the total revenue from this tax and in 2005 it amounted to 90.9%.</seg>
<seg id="33">The difference to 100% of CZK 13 billion in 2004 and CZK 6.9 billion in 2005 was the income of the State Fund for Transport Infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="34">All excise duties in Slovakia have been administered by the customs authorities since 1 May 2004, with the exception of excise duty on mineral oil, which they have administered since 1 January 2002.</seg>
<seg id="35">Until then, excise duties were administered by the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="36">In Slovakia, mineral oil, alcohol, beer, wine and tobacco products are subject to excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="37">The revenue of the state budget from excise duties in the Slovak Republic in 2004 was a total of SKK 43.4 billion and the total tax revenue of SKK 209.5 billion was accounted for by excise duties of 20.7%.</seg>
<seg id="38">In 2005, the state budget revenue from excise duties was SKK 50 billion and the total tax revenue was SKK 222.6 billion. Excise taxes accounted for 22.5%.</seg>
<seg id="39">Graph 1 — Comparison of revenue of the state budget of the Czech Republic from taxes and fees and tax revenue of the state budget of the Slovak Republic with revenue from excise duties</seg>
<seg id="40">- Council Directive 92/12/EEC on the general arrangements for products subject to excise duty and on the holding, movement and monitoring of such products (hereinafter referred to as ‘Directive 92/12/EEC’), - Council Regulation (EC) No 2073/2004 on administrative cooperation in the field of excise duties (hereinafter referred to as ‘Regulation No 2073/2004’), - Commission Regulation (EEC) No 2719/92 on the accompanying official document for the movement of products subject to excise duty under suspension of excise duty (hereinafter referred to as ‘Regulation No 2719/92’), - Commission Regulation (hereinafter referred to as ‘excise movement within the Member State of excise duty) No 3649/EEC) for excise goods accompanying movement within the Member State of excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="41">The basic legislation governing the issue of excise duties in the Czech Republic is Act No. 353/2003 Coll., on Excise Taxes, as amended (hereinafter referred to as "Act No. 353/2003 Coll."), which has been in force since 1 January 2004.</seg>
<seg id="42">In the administration of excise duties in the Slovak Republic, the customs authorities are, inter alia, bound by the following generally binding legislation: - Law No 98/2004 Z. z. o spotrebnej dani z minerálneho oleja v znení neskorích predpisov (hereinafter ‘Law No 98/2004 Z. z. z.’), - Law No 104/2004 Z. z. z. o. </seg>
<seg id="43">2.1 Movement of excise goods under suspension of excise duty between Member States of the European Union</seg>
<seg id="44">The conditions of movement of excise goods under suspension of excise duty shall be governed by Directive 92/12/EEC in Title III — Movement of goods Articles 15 to 20.</seg>
<seg id="45">According to those provisions, the transport of those goods may be effected only by an authorised warehousekeeper, who means a natural or legal person authorised by the competent authorities of a Member State to manufacture, process, store, receive and dispatch products subject to excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="46">The consignee in another Member State may be an authorised warehousekeeper or an economic operator without the status of authorised warehousekeeper, but who may not store or dispatch such products under the duty suspension arrangement.</seg>
<seg id="47">Authorised warehousekeeper in the Czech Republic and Slovakia means the operator of a tax warehouse, the economic operator is the authorised recipient for the repeated or one-off receipt of products subject to excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="48">The movement of excise products under suspension of excise duty is possible under Directive 92/12/EEC only with an accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="49">The accompanying document shall be drawn up by the consignor in four copies before the transport begins, unless a further copy is required by the competent authorities of the Member State of dispatch.</seg>
<seg id="50">2.2 Procedure for the commencement and termination of the transport of goods under the conditional tax exemption regime between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="51">Transport from the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="52">The procedure for the commencement of transport is governed by Section 25(3) of Act No 353/2003 Coll., which states, inter alia:</seg>
<seg id="53">‘The operator of the tax warehouse shall, before the transport of the selected products begins, inform the customs office which is locally competent of the tax warehouse from which the transport is to begin;</seg>
<seg id="54">The transport of the selected products may be initiated only with the consent of that customs office.</seg>
<seg id="55">The customs office shall give its consent to the transport of the selected products without delay after the condition of securing the tax has been fulfilled.’</seg>
<seg id="56">The consignor in the Czech Republic may start the transport of all types of products subject to excise duty only with the consent of the locally competent customs office.</seg>
<seg id="57">The customs office shall give its consent to the commencement of the transport only if a guarantee of tax equal to the amount of tax due on the transported products is provided.</seg>
<seg id="58">The consignor shall be obliged to draw up an accompanying document in five copies before commencing transport.</seg>
<seg id="59">The customs office shall indicate on the accompanying document the consent to the start of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="60">Copy No 1 shall be kept by the consignor, copies No 2, 3 and 4 shall be handed over by the consignor to the carrier and copy No 5 shall be kept by the customs office authorising the transport.</seg>
<seg id="61">Under Slovak law, the consignee in Slovakia keeps copy No 2 of the accompanying document. They shall confirm receipt of the products on copies No 3 and No 4 and present both copies to the customs office with geographical jurisdiction.</seg>
<seg id="62">Copy No 3, certified by the customs office, shall be sent to the consignor no later than the 15th day of the month following the calendar month in which the products were received.</seg>
<seg id="63">Copy No 4 shall be kept by the customs office of the consignee.</seg>
<seg id="64">The transport is terminated by the receipt of the products by the consignee.</seg>
<seg id="65">The customs office in the Czech Republic, which authorised the start of the transport, shall decide on the release of the tax guarantee within 5 working days after the presentation of copy No.3 of the accompanying document, which shall be confirmed by the consignee and the Slovak customs office.</seg>
<seg id="66">Graph 2 — Circulation of the accompanying document for transport started in the Czech Republic and ended in the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="67">Transport from Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="68">The procedure for the transport of ethyl alcohol and tobacco products from the Slovak Republic to another Member State of the European Union was amended as follows until 31 December 2005:</seg>
<seg id="69">Pursuant to Paragraph 26(4) of Law No 105/2004 Z. z.</seg>
<seg id="70">‘When transporting a lieh from a tax warehouse in the tax territory to a tax warehouse or to an authorised consignee, or to a tax plenipotentiary in the inom Member State, an odosielatel’ (supplier) is obliged on the day of the start of the transport to send a copy of the first diel of the sprievodného document electronically or by fax to the customs office of Poprad; that copy is required to be sent to the customs office in writing to the piatich of the working days from the start of the transport. “</seg>
<seg id="71">Pursuant to Article 22(4) of Law No 106/2004 Z. z.</seg>
<seg id="72">‘When transporting tobacco products from a tax warehouse in the tax territory to a tax warehouse or to an authorised consignee, or to a tax plenipotentiary in the inom Member State, the odosielatel’ (supplier) is obliged, on the day of the start of the transport, to send a copy of the first diel of the sprievodné document electronically or by fax to the Colné úrad Poprad; it is obliged to send that copy to the colný úrad pisomne najor to those working days of the start of the transport. “</seg>
<seg id="73">In respect of the transport of other products subject to excise duty (mineral oil, wine and beer) during the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005 (hereinafter referred to as the ‘audited period’), the taxpayer was not required to notify the Poprad Customs Office or the competent customs office of the start of the transport under the duty suspension arrangement.</seg>
<seg id="74">The tax administrator became aware of the transport of these products only during a local investigation or tax inspection from the accompanying documents and accounting documents of the taxpayer.</seg>
<seg id="75">The consignor in Slovakia is obliged to draw up an accompanying document in four copies before the transport begins.</seg>
<seg id="76">Copy No 1 shall be retained by the consignor (for the transport of ethyl alcohol and tobacco products, a copy of copy No 1 shall be sent electronically or by fax to the Poprad Customs Office and the competent customs office).</seg>
<seg id="77">Copy No 2, 3 and 4 shall accompany the goods being transported.</seg>
<seg id="78">According to the Czech legislation, the consignee in the Czech Republic keeps copy No. 2 of the accompanying document issued by the consignor in the Slovak Republic and confirms receipt of the products on copies No. 3 and 4.</seg>
<seg id="79">Confirmed copies No 3 and No 4 shall be sent to the locally competent customs office in the Czech Republic no later than the first working day after completion of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="80">The customs office shall keep copy No 4 and return copy No 3, on which it shall check its accuracy and validity, to the consignee.</seg>
<seg id="81">The consignee shall send copy No 3 to the consignor in SR no later than the working day following receipt of the copy.</seg>
<seg id="82">Transport in Slovakia is considered to have ended on the date of receipt of the products by the consignee.</seg>
<seg id="83">The consignor proves the completion of the transport by submitting copy No.3 of the accompanying document confirmed by the consignee and the tax administrator in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="84">Graph 3 — Circulation of the accompanying document during transport (alcohol and tobacco products) started in the Slovak Republic and ended in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="85">In 2006, the Slovak Republic gradually adopted amendments to all laws on excise duties, according to which the consignor of goods under suspension of duty is obliged to send a copy of copy No.1 of the accompanying document electronically or by fax to the customs office of the consignor with territorial jurisdiction before the transport begins.</seg>
<seg id="86">The document proving completion of the transport of ethyl alcohol and tobacco products shall be copy No 3 of the accompanying document certified by the consignee and his competent tax authority.</seg>
<seg id="87">Document No 3, certified by the consignee, showing that the transport of mineral oils, wine and beer has ended.</seg>
<seg id="88">Confirmation by the tax authorities of another Member State of receipt of the said goods by the consignee shall be required if the latter is required, under the legislation of the Member State concerned, to endorse copy No 3 of the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="89">2.3 Registration of initiated and terminated transport operations kept by customs authorities in the Czech Republic and Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="90">There is no single electronic system in place to monitor the transport of goods under suspension of tax between Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="91">Decision 1152/2003/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council of 16 June 2003 on the introduction of an electronic system for the transport and monitoring of excise products requires Member States and the European Commission to introduce, from 1 July 2009, an electronic system (Excise Movement and Control System) to enable excise authorities in each Member State to obtain real-time information on the transport of goods.</seg>
<seg id="92">The system will allow the electronic transmission of accompanying documents, which are currently only used in paper form, and will contribute to simplifying the movement of goods under the suspension arrangement and to ensuring more effective control of the movement of untaxed products within all Member States.</seg>
<seg id="93">National transport databases of the Member States will be part of this system.</seg>
<seg id="94">The Customs Administration of the Czech Republic records all transport operations initiated and completed on the territory of the Czech Republic in the module Records of Selected Products (hereinafter referred to as "EVV").</seg>
<seg id="95">All customs authorities in the Czech Republic have online access to the system.</seg>
<seg id="96">In the case of transport carried out only on the territory of the Czech Republic, tax administrators can obtain information about the start or end of the transport immediately after the registration of the accompanying document by the customs office in the EVV.</seg>
<seg id="97">The customs office shall release the tax security for the transported products provided by the consignor at the time of registration of the end of the transport by the customs office of the locally competent consignee.</seg>
<seg id="98">Customs offices in Slovakia use a database based on the application software SysNed, which ensures the automation of their activities in the administration of excise duties and communication with the systems of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="99">By registering the tax warehouse, the tax warehouse operator or the beneficiary in the SysNed application software, this data is automatically transferred to the System for Exchange of Excise Data (SEED) database.</seg>
<seg id="100">3. Preparation and conduct of cooperation</seg>
<seg id="101">The first coordination meeting between representatives of the SAO-CR and representatives of the SAO-SR took place in January 2006.</seg>
<seg id="102">The two parties have become acquainted with the legislation on excise duties and with the organisation of the administration of excise duties in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="103">Particular attention was paid to the procedure of the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and Slovakia in authorising, respectively starting and ending the transport of products subject to excise duty under the duty suspension regime and the exchange of information between the excise tax authorities of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="104">At the meeting it was agreed that the Czech and Slovak parties: - will process the total data on the quantity of excise products transported from the Czech Republic to Slovakia and vice versa, whose transport started during the audited period, - will compare the data on mineral oil transport, - Combined Nomenclature code 2710 and 2711 and ethyl alcohol, - Combined Nomenclature code 2207 and 2208 under the conditional exemption regime initiated in the Czech Republic and terminated in the Slovak Republic and vice versa in November 2004 and September 2005.</seg>
<seg id="105">During the inspections, the periods examined were extended by the months of October and November 2005 and during those months the transport of tobacco products under suspension of excise duty was also inspected.</seg>
<seg id="106">Tables 1 and 2 show the total quantity of excise products transported under the duty suspension arrangement between Czech and Slovak tax subjects during the audited period.</seg>
<seg id="107">4. Comparison of transport registers of goods under suspension of excise duty</seg>
<seg id="108">The SAO-CR provided the Slovak side with a database of transport completed in the Czech Republic, which contained a total of 5 876 items listed on accompanying documents, of which 5 738 items related to mineral oils, 134 items of ethyl alcohol and 4 items related to tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="109">The SAO of Slovakia provided the Czech side with a database of transport completed in Slovakia, which contained a total of 3,319 items listed on accompanying documents, of which 696 items related to mineral oil, 2,066 items of ethyl alcohol and 557 items of tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="110">The SAO-CR compared data on transport operations listed in the register of commenced transport operations in the Czech Republic with data on terminated transport operations registered in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="111">The results of the comparison are presented in Table 3.</seg>
<seg id="112">The SAO-CR compared the traffic data in November 2004 and September 2005 with the Slovak Customs Administration database, which the SAO handed over at the beginning of the audit.</seg>
<seg id="113">The database did not contain data allowing reliable approval of individual transport operations, and therefore only 63% of the traffic initiated could be assigned.</seg>
<seg id="114">Individual transports were assigned according to multiple data, e.g. consignor, consignee, date of transport, quantity of products transported.</seg>
<seg id="115">Data on transport operations initiated in the Czech Republic and terminated in Slovakia in October and November 2005 were compared by the SAO-CR with the database of the Slovak customs administration, which contained all data according to accompanying documents, on the basis of which 93 % of the initiated transport operations were unambiguously assigned.</seg>
<seg id="116">In the database of the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic, data on the quantity of mineral oils were given in litres or tonnes depending on the type of mineral oil.</seg>
<seg id="117">The quantity of ethyl alcohol was in most cases expressed in litres, but this could be converted into litres of absolute alcohol on the basis of the percentage of alcohol indicated in the database.</seg>
<seg id="118">The quantities of tobacco products were given in pieces, in thousands and in kilograms, depending on the type of tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="119">In the case of transport operations initiated in the Czech Republic, the termination of which could not be reliably verified in the Slovak database or the quantity of products transported did not match, the accompanying documents were checked.</seg>
<seg id="120">Documents accompanying 487 shipments of ethyl alcohol, mineral oils and tobacco products were checked.</seg>
<seg id="121">The audit of these documents was carried out at the customs offices, where the SAO-CR performed the audit.</seg>
<seg id="122">For transport operations authorised by other customs offices, accompanying documents were requested through the DG.</seg>
<seg id="123">The Czech side asked the Slovak side to verify the realization of 141 transport operations for which the customs offices in the Czech Republic did not document the confirmed copies No.3 of the accompanying document, or the quantity of products indicated on the accompanying document did not match the quantity of products indicated in the database.</seg>
<seg id="124">In addition, data on transport registered in the Slovak database were transmitted to the Slovak side, but this data was not included in the transport database of the Czech customs administration.</seg>
<seg id="125">The SAO of Slovakia searched the database of the Slovak customs administration for 95 transports.</seg>
<seg id="126">The verification of the remaining 46 shipments was requested by the locally competent customs offices, which proved their completion with copies of the accompanying documents.</seg>
<seg id="127">The Slovak side forwarded to the Czech side copies of accompanying documents on the basis of which the transport services were identified also in the Czech database, with the exception of the transport operations carried out by two Czech tax entities, which were not found in the Czech database of initiated transport operations.</seg>
<seg id="128">Examination of these cases revealed:</seg>
<seg id="129">- in the Slovak transport database, 11 alcohol transports in the total amount of 276.7 litres of alcohol carried out by the Czech tax entity in 2004 and 20 alcohol transports in the total amount of 404.66 litres of alcohol carried out in 2005 were registered.</seg>
<seg id="130">The SAO-CR found that these were transports of taxed products, for which the consignor does not need the tax administrator's consent.</seg>
<seg id="131">The consignor informed the tax administrator in writing of the start of the transport. The transport was carried out on the basis of accompanying documents used for the transport of products under a duty suspension arrangement;</seg>
<seg id="132">- in the Slovak transport database, a total of 94 mineral oil transports, code of the Combined Nomenclature 2710 11 21, were registered in the total volume of 173 thousand litres carried out by the Czech tax entity between September 2004 and December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="133">The SAO-CR found that between May 2004 and June 2005 the tax entity carried out transport of 102 thousand litres of untaxed mineral oils without the appropriate authorisation.</seg>
<seg id="134">The taxpayer held a special authorisation for the receipt and use of exempt products, under which he could supply untaxed products only to the holder of the same authorisation.</seg>
<seg id="135">He did not notify the customs office in the Czech Republic of the start of the transport and did not provide a tax guarantee of CZK 1,207,680 for the transported products.</seg>
<seg id="136">Between July 2005 and December 2005, the taxpayer transported 71 thousand litres of taxed mineral oils to the territory of SR. Again, he failed to fulfil a legal obligation by failing to notify the customs office of the start of the transport operations.</seg>
<seg id="137">Transport of products put into free tax circulation in the tax territory of the Czech Republic to another Member State may be initiated by the consignor in the Czech Republic without the consent of the customs office, but the consignor is obliged to inform the customs office in writing before the transport begins.</seg>
<seg id="138">A taxpayer purchasing products put into free circulation in another Member State is required to declare the quantities and ensure the tax before they are taken away.</seg>
<seg id="139">Products may be transported only with a simplified accompanying document, the particulars of which are governed by Regulation No 3649/92.</seg>
<seg id="140">This Regulation also allows the use of an accompanying document for movements under suspension of duty, but this document must clearly indicate that it is a ‘simplified accompanying document for tax control purposes (products subject to excise duty)’.</seg>
<seg id="141">The same rules on the transport and admission of products put into free circulation in another Member State apply in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="142">In those cases, the taxable persons transported the products put into free circulation with an accompanying document for transport under the suspension arrangement, the 3rd and 4th copies of which were submitted by the recipient to the tax authorities in the Slovak Republic for verification.</seg>
<seg id="143">The customs authorities in Slovakia registered these transport operations in the database of transport under the suspension arrangement, as the accompanying documents did not state that it was a simplified accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="144">The SAO of Slovakia compared the transport database of the Czech customs administration with the transport database of the Slovak customs administration and found:</seg>
<seg id="145">- in the databases, the quantity of products transported was given inconsistently, e.g. mineral oil was given in litres, in hectolitres or in kilograms; ethyl alcohol was given in litres or litres of alcohol, making it more difficult to compare the quantity of goods transported;</seg>
<seg id="146">- the quantity of ethyl alcohol transported in the invoices did not correspond to the quantity recorded in the databases,</seg>
<seg id="147">- not all related invoices were listed in the databases,</seg>
<seg id="148">- two alcohol shipments from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic carried out in November 2004 in a total volume of 47 237 litres of alcohol were registered in the database of the Slovak customs administration, which were not found in the database of the Czech customs administration.</seg>
<seg id="149">The Slovak side handed over copies of the accompanying documents to the Czech side.</seg>
<seg id="150">5. International exchange of information between customs authorities of the Czech Republic and Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="151">Until 30 June 2005, the conditions for cooperation between the administrative authorities of the Member States responsible for administering excise duties were governed by Council Directive 77/799/EEC concerning mutual assistance by the competent authorities of the Member States in the field of direct taxation, certain excise duties and taxation of insurance premiums.</seg>
<seg id="152">On 1 July 2005, Regulation No 2073/2004 entered into force, laying down the rules and procedures allowing the competent authorities of the Member States of the European Union to cooperate and exchange the information necessary for the correct assessment of excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="153">Each Member State shall designate a central liaison office which shall liaise with other Member States in the field of excise duty administration and shall be responsible for exchanging information on movements of excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="154">In the Czech Republic, the “Excise Liaison Office” (hereinafter referred to as “ELO ČR”) was set up in the DG to ensure the exchange of information in the field of excise duties between the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="155">With effect from 1 May 2004, the ELO at the Poprad Customs Office was responsible for ensuring the management of the systems for controlling the movement of excise goods (SEED, MVS, EWSE) and the exchange of information in the framework of mutual administrative assistance between the Member States of the European Union and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="156">With effect from 1 July 2005, the tasks of ELO are carried out by the ELO Unit (based in Poprad) of the Excise Department of the Customs Directorate of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as ‘ELO SR’).</seg>
<seg id="157">Under Article 3(3) of Regulation No 2073/2004, the central liaison office is responsible in particular for: - the exchange of data held in the electronic register of the SEED, - the Early Warning System Excise (EWSE), - requests for verification of movements of excise goods sent to or received from other Member States by the Movement Verification System (MVS).</seg>
<seg id="158">The content, scope and functions of the SEED, EWSE and ISA systems are governed by Articles 22, 23 and 24 of Regulation No 2073/2004.</seg>
<seg id="159">SEED - system for the exchange of information on tax subjects trading in excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="160">The system is made up of national excise registers and allows tax authorities in the territory of the European Union to ascertain whether products subject to excise duty are traded by a person authorised to do so.</seg>
<seg id="161">Each national register shall be made available to the competent authorities of the other Member States for excise purposes only.</seg>
<seg id="162">The central liaison office of each Member State shall ensure that persons involved in the movement of excise goods within the territory of the European Union are able to obtain confirmation of the information held in that database.</seg>
<seg id="163">In accordance with § 41 of Act No 98/2004 Z. z., s § 39 of Act No 104/2004 Z. z., s § 46 of Act No 105/2004 Z. z., s § 40 of Act No 106/2004 Z. z. and s § 39 of Act No 107/2004 Z. z. ELO SR maintains an electronic database containing a register of tax warehouse operators, authorised recipients and tax warehouses - the SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="164">Customs offices in SR contribute to the SEED database by registering the tax warehouse, tax warehouse operator or authorised recipient in the SysNed application software, which is automatically linked to ELO SR.</seg>
<seg id="165">For example, if a new tax warehouse operator, beneficiary or tax warehouse is registered in the SysNed database, the related data are automatically transferred to the SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="166">The SAO of Slovakia found that the exchange of SEED databases between the Customs Administration of the Slovak Republic and the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic took place in the audited period usually once a month, exceptionally several times a month.</seg>
<seg id="167">SR Customs received 22 SEED files and sent 25 SEED files.</seg>
<seg id="168">The data are transferred to the SEED database in the Czech Republic from the national register in which all persons authorised to handle products subject to excise duty and issued authorisations for handling such products are registered.</seg>
<seg id="169">Individual customs offices in the Czech Republic do not have access to the international database SEED.</seg>
<seg id="170">Requests from customs offices to provide information from the SEED database of other member countries are obtained only through ELO ČR.</seg>
<seg id="171">EWSE - an early warning system aimed at controlling the transport of excise goods, through which the transport of risky consignments is announced.</seg>
<seg id="172">Transport of certain products subject to excise duty in quantities exceeding the limits laid down in a European Commission regulation and transport assessed as a risk by the tax authority are considered to be risky consignments.</seg>
<seg id="173">The exchange of information takes two forms:</seg>
<seg id="174">- information - sent when the specified limits are exceeded,</seg>
<seg id="175">- a warning message - to be sent if the carriage of goods is assessed as risky.</seg>
<seg id="176">When assessing the level of risk of a consignment, ELO SR uses the SEED database to send an alert message, on the basis of which it checks the data contained in the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="177">If the data in the SEED database do not match the data in the accompanying document (for example, the registration number of the consignee of the goods or the registered office of the consignee does not match), ELO SR shall draw up an alert message to be sent to ELO of the Member State of the consignee of the goods.</seg>
<seg id="178">In drawing up the reports, ELO follows the regulations of the Tax and Customs Commission CED 317 and CED 457, which, among other things, determine the type and quantity of goods in the respective measurement units for the production of information and warning reports.</seg>
<seg id="179">During the audited period ELO SR sent one warning message to ELO ČR.</seg>
<seg id="180">In the Czech Republic, information on initiated transport of products in quantities exceeding the specified limits is generated automatically when entering data from the accompanying document into the database at the time of transport approval.</seg>
<seg id="181">If the tax administrator in the Czech Republic evaluates the shipment as a risk based on his own analysis, he will process the so-called warning message, which he will send to the relevant Member State through ELO ČR.</seg>
<seg id="182">In 2005 ELO ČR sent two warning messages to ELO SR.</seg>
<seg id="183">The ISA - the system for controlling the movement of goods - makes it possible, through the ISA's requests, to check the individual movements of products subject to excise duty, as well as to check the specified route of transport between the bodies mentioned in the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="184">The exchange of information takes place on the basis of a request in which the ELO of the sending country specifies its requirements.</seg>
<seg id="185">The system is used in particular in cases where the consignor accepts copy No 3 of the accompanying document and requests e.g. a refund of excise duty, and in cases where the information contained in the accompanying document cannot be verified in the SEED international database.</seg>
<seg id="186">During the audited period, ELO SR sent 33 requests to the Ministry of Foreign Affairs.</seg>
<seg id="187">ELO ČR sent ELO SR 25 requests to MVS.</seg>
<seg id="188">Customs offices in the Czech Republic most often checked the data contained in the accompanying documents, in particular the quantity of products received or dispatched or whether the consignor of products mentioned in the accompanying document is entitled to dispose of products subject to excise duty if this fact could not be verified in the international database SEED.</seg>
<seg id="189">The MVS applications received were forwarded in both countries to the customs offices locally responsible for the consignee or consignor of excise products.</seg>
<seg id="190">The customs authorities examined the required data and communicated the result of the investigation to the other Member State via ELO.</seg>
<seg id="191">6. Summary</seg>
<seg id="192">The cooperation of the SAO-CR and the SAO-SR enabled to compare the basic legislation governing the area of excise duties in both states, the procedure of the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in the initiation and termination of transport of products under suspension of tax exemption between the two states, the registration of such transport and to compare the exchange of information between customs authorities within the framework of international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="193">6.1 Comparison of legislation governing excise duties in the Czech Republic and Slovakia revealed differences:</seg>
<seg id="194">(a) the procedure followed by tax entities and tax authorities when initiating the transport of products under a duty suspension arrangement.</seg>
<seg id="195">Transport of products under the conditional exemption regime can be initiated by a tax entity in the Czech Republic only with the consent of the tax administrator, who authorizes the commencement of transport on condition that the transported products have been provided with a tax guarantee in the amount of the tax to which they are subject.</seg>
<seg id="196">The commencement of the transport of products under suspension of duty in the Slovak Republic is not subject to authorisation by the tax authority.</seg>
<seg id="197">During the audited period, the taxpayer was obliged to notify the tax authorities of the start of the transport of alcohol and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="198">He was able to start the transport of mineral oils, beer and wine without informing the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="199">In 2006, the Slovak Republic gradually adopted amendments to all laws on excise duties, according to which the consignor of goods under suspension of duty is obliged to send a copy of copy No.1 of the accompanying document electronically or by fax to the customs office competent for the consignor before the transport begins.</seg>
<seg id="200">(b) within the time limits for dispatch of copy No 3 of the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="201">The recipient in the Czech Republic is obliged to send copies No. 3 and 4 of the accompanying document to the tax administrator for verification no later than the following working day after the end of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="202">Verified copy No 3 must be sent to the sender no later than the following working day after receipt from the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="203">The consignee in Slovakia is obliged to send to the consignor of the products copy No 3 certified by the tax administrator and the consignee of the products no later than the 15th day of the month following that in which he received the goods.</seg>
<seg id="204">6.2. Customs authorities in both the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic keep electronic records of transport of products under the conditional exemption regime.</seg>
<seg id="205">The content and method of keeping this register is not regulated by law in the Czech Republic or Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="206">The customs authorities in both countries enter in the register all data from the accompanying documents on the basis of which the transport is carried out.</seg>
<seg id="207">For the monitoring of the movement of goods under suspension of duty between Member States of the European Union, there is currently no single electronic system allowing excise authorities in each Member State to obtain real-time information on the movement of goods.</seg>
<seg id="208">According to Decision 1152/2003/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council of 16 June 2003, the introduction of an electronic system for monitoring movements of excise products is foreseen from 1 July 2009.</seg>
<seg id="209">On the basis of the agreement on cooperation in control activities, the Czech side handed over to the Slovak side a database of transport of products under suspension of duty initiated in the Slovak Republic and terminated in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="210">The database contained 5 876 entries for mineral oils, ethyl alcohol and tobacco products transported.</seg>
<seg id="211">The Slovak side forwarded to the Czech side a database of transport of products under suspension of duty initiated in the Czech Republic and terminated in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="212">The database contained 3 319 entries for mineral oils, ethyl alcohol and tobacco products transported.</seg>
<seg id="213">The Czech side compared the data on transport operations listed in the register of commenced transport operations in the Czech Republic with the register of transport operations terminated in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="214">The Slovak side compared the data on the transport of goods under the conditional exemption scheme started in the Slovak Republic and ended in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="215">Comparison of data was hampered by the fact that the quantity of goods transported was not uniformly reported in the databases.</seg>
<seg id="216">In cases where it was not possible to unambiguously attribute the data of individual transport operations in both registers, the accompanying documents were checked and no violations of the suspensive regime or cases of tax evasion were detected.</seg>
<seg id="217">Based on the findings of the parallel controls, it can be concluded that the transport register can provide Member States with valuable information to improve the administration of excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="218">The establishment of an electronic system for the movement and control of excise goods within the meaning of Decision No 1152/2003/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council will allow the electronic transmission of the movement document and more effective control of movements under suspension of excise duty within the territory of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="219">Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="220">This report was drawn up in the Czech, English and Slovak languages.</seg>
<seg id="221">The report was signed by the President of the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic and the President of the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic.</seg>
</p>
</doc>
<doc docid="testsuite-segment_65-KA_09_11_OCR" genre="news" origlang="en" sysid="CUNI-Transformer2020">
<p>
<seg id="1">Value Added Tax Administration in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Report on the results of the follow-up</seg>
<seg id="3">Opening Word</seg>
<seg id="4">Taxes are generally a key source of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="5">It goes without saying that the Supreme Audit Institutions (SAIs) should focus their attention on this area.</seg>
<seg id="6">An example is value added tax (VAT) fraud.</seg>
<seg id="7">In their case, a loss of EUR 100 billion is estimated each year in the European Union (EU).</seg>
<seg id="8">Already in 2005, the participants of the VI EUROSAI Congress in Bonn agreed on the need for very close cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="9">In the framework of this cooperation, SAIs can exchange control procedures, find the best solutions, etc.</seg>
<seg id="10">VAT is a very suitable area for control cooperation as it is the only tax harmonised within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="11">The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (SAO) and the Federal Court of Auditors (Bundesrechnungshof, BRH) conducted the first parallel audit in the field of VAT in 2006.</seg>
<seg id="12">The report was published in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="13">As VAT fraud is not confined to a single country but is widespread throughout the EU, close cooperation between SAIs is needed to ensure a comprehensive evaluation of the steps taken to address this problem.</seg>
<seg id="14">Both SAIs therefore decided to further develop their cooperation in this area and carried out a parallel follow-up.</seg>
<seg id="15">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="16">Control number: (CZ) 09/11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892</seg>
<seg id="17">Subject of the audit: (CZ) Value Added Tax Administration (D) Bilateral audit with SAO (follow-up)</seg>
<seg id="18">Objective of control:</seg>
<seg id="19">(CZ) The aim of the auditing operation was to examine the procedure of the tax authorities in the administration of VAT, in particular to verify the procedure for dealing with selected cases of commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter referred to as "Germany"), and to examine the procedures of the tax administrations of both countries in the framework of international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="20">(D) The auditing operation was designed to evaluate the measures taken by the tax administration to implement the recommendations issued by the SAO and BRH.</seg>
<seg id="21">It was also intended to cover other areas related to VAT.</seg>
<seg id="22">The resulting control findings were intended to be compared with established good practice (if any).</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited period covered the years 2006 to 2008 and, in the case of relevant connections, the preceding and following periods until the end of the audit.</seg>
<seg id="24">2. Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions</seg>
<seg id="25">The subsequent verification of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="26">During previous parallel inspections, suspicious cases of intra-community transactions were detected.</seg>
<seg id="27">Some of them required further examination.</seg>
<seg id="28">On the basis of the audit findings, both SAIs formulated recommendations concerning the administration of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="29">The follow-up carried out was to evaluate the measures taken in response to these recommendations and to examine the selected suspected cases.</seg>
<seg id="30">The audit also focused on selected cases of high-risk intra-community transactions, mutual assistance in the recovery of claims and the implementation of VAT checks on large tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="31">During the audit of the VAT administration in selected areas in both countries, the auditors came to the following audit findings:</seg>
<seg id="32">1. Previous inspection recommendations</seg>
<seg id="33">• Recommendation 1: Conditions for the registration of payers should be harmonised across the EU</seg>
<seg id="34">In previous parallel inspections, a comparison of the VAT registration systems in the two countries revealed differences.</seg>
<seg id="35">As the different ways of registering pose problems, both SAIs recommended harmonising the conditions for registering payers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="36">This recommendation has been put forward at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="37">The proposal to amend Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 on administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax and repealing Regulation (EEC) No 218/92 (hereinafter "Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003") called for the extension of existing databases within the EU, including the VAT payer tax identification number database.</seg>
<seg id="38">He also amended the common standards for the registration and deregistration of taxpayers.</seg>
<seg id="39">The SAIs expected EU Member States to agree on appropriate standards to support their decision to exclude unreliable traders from the VAT system as quickly as possible.</seg>
<seg id="40">However, the latest version of the document, agreed by the EU Member States in the ECOFIN framework, no longer covers the issue.</seg>
<seg id="41">Both SAIs regret that the idea of common minimum standards has been abandoned.</seg>
<seg id="42">However, they continue to see this intention as a relevant prevention tool in the fight against VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="43">• Recommendation 2: Monthly Summary Reporting</seg>
<seg id="44">In the context of international cooperation, a previous monitoring exercise recommended that all EU countries introduce a monthly deadline for the submission of recapitulative statements to allow for a more timely verification of intra-community transaction values.</seg>
<seg id="45">Council Directive 2008/117/EC amending Directive 2006/112/EC on the common system of value added tax to combat tax evasion connected with intra-Community transactions reduces the period for which recapitulative statements of intra-EU transactions are submitted to one month.</seg>
<seg id="46">In the Czech Republic, this measure was implemented through the Value Added Tax Act with effect from 1 January 2010, in Germany it was implemented from 1 July 2010.</seg>
<seg id="47">In Germany, the obligation to submit monthly recapitulative statements was not introduced by the deadline in accordance with the applicable EU rules, while in the Czech Republic it was.</seg>
<seg id="48">• Recommendation 3: Comparison of data in VAT returns and recapitulative statements in Germany to achieve greater reliability of VIES data and consideration of linking the two systems for VAT returns and recapitulative statements</seg>
<seg id="49">The German tax administration accepted BRH’s recommendation and set up a working group to explore possible solutions.</seg>
<seg id="50">Work is still ongoing and BRH will closely monitor further developments.</seg>
<seg id="51">• Recommendation 4: Sharing the successful criteria, components and approaches of the risk management system at EU level Based on the results of the previous control action, both SAIs agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by one Member State alone.</seg>
<seg id="52">Successful criteria, components and approaches of the risk management system need to be exchanged and implemented in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="53">If this is not the case, fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="54">The audit found that our two Member States have different risk management systems which have their own strengths and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="55">In this area, the SAO audited EUROCANET, which allows the exchange of information within the EU, while BRH focused on the German participation in the so-called risk management platform.</seg>
<seg id="56">2. Follow-up of selected intra-community transactions</seg>
<seg id="57">During the previous audit operation, business transactions where there were doubts about their completion or irregularities in the reporting of business transactions in tax returns or recapitulative statements by taxpayers from both countries were jointly examined.</seg>
<seg id="58">Both SAIs selected nine cases for follow-up, which included intra-community movement of goods between the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="59">The inspections carried out by the tax authorities of the countries concerned have not been concluded by the date of completion of our previous joint inspection operation.</seg>
<seg id="60">The subsequent audit operation verified that most of the tax procedures related to the selected cases of commercial transactions between payers from the Czech Republic and Germany were concluded and that adequate measures were taken by the tax administration of the Czech Republic or Germany (e.g. additional adjustment of VAT or avoidance of input tax refund).</seg>
<seg id="61">3. Check selected risk intra-community transactions</seg>
<seg id="62">High-risk cases of intra-community transactions carried out by EU payers included in EUROCANET were selected for the audit.</seg>
<seg id="63">EUROCANET is a tool for detecting risky tax payers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="64">Member States' participation in the scheme is voluntary.</seg>
<seg id="65">The Czech Republic is an active participant in EUROCANET, while Germany has a passive status.</seg>
<seg id="66">It is unsatisfactory for an active scheme participant if some Member States refuse to participate actively.</seg>
<seg id="67">Due to the fact that the German tax administration did not participate in the EUROCANET data exchange, it was not possible to obtain any information on which suppliers with the German VAT ID were assessed as being at risk.</seg>
<seg id="68">As part of the audit, the SAO found cases of common commercial transactions as well as cases of suspected involvement in carousel transactions or fraudulent behaviour related to VAT.</seg>
<seg id="69">Tax authorities have limited possibilities of controlling risky transactions, especially with regard to missing traders, and mere physical verification of documents can hardly prove any fraudulent behaviour to the taxpayer.</seg>
<seg id="70">A similar situation arises for the tax authorities when imports and exports to third countries are linked to intra-Community carousel shops.</seg>
<seg id="71">In such cases, it would be appropriate to ensure greater cooperation between customs and financial authorities in order to identify goods and irregularities in transport documents and also to monitor their physical movement within the EU towards the final consumer.</seg>
<seg id="72">Germany, like some other countries, is hesitant to actively participate in EUROCANET due to the lack of a sufficient legal basis.</seg>
<seg id="73">In Germany, other tools are being used to detect high-risk taxpayers, which have so far proved useful to the German tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="74">There is a need to communicate and exchange experiences between EU Member States in this area.</seg>
<seg id="75">The EU Council reached a political agreement on a draft regulation amending Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003.</seg>
<seg id="76">Its main innovation is the creation of the EUROFISC network.</seg>
<seg id="77">The experience gained so far in using EUROCANET should feed into the creation of this new VAT fraud network.</seg>
<seg id="78">4. Mutual assistance for the recovery of claims</seg>
<seg id="79">In the area of international recovery assistance, all EU Member States follow the same European legislation.</seg>
<seg id="80">Therefore, the way in which requests for international recovery assistance are handled is the same in the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="81">The SAO and the SAO compared the statistics submitted by both Member States to the European Commission for the years 2006-2008.</seg>
<seg id="82">The data contained in these statistics did not match.</seg>
<seg id="83">Both SAIs consider it useful to renegotiate the statistics at EU level in order to find a way to avoid persistent inconsistencies.</seg>
<seg id="84">Without this, the statistics will not be reliable and comparable.</seg>
<seg id="85">In addition, SAIs agree that reliable statistics should contain more information on VAT.</seg>
<seg id="86">It would probably be useful for the Commission to produce, on the basis of more detailed statistics, an analysis to help Member States to strengthen the effectiveness of the fight against VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="87">In the view of both SAIs, this means helping Member States with low recovery rates to increase their recovery rates to at least the EU average.</seg>
<seg id="88">If a Member State so wishes, the Commission should actively participate in this process.</seg>
<seg id="89">5. Scrutiny of large tax entities</seg>
<seg id="90">SAI analysed the legal situation regarding VAT control of large tax entities (VDS) in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="91">In addition, they gathered information from tax authorities by means of a questionnaire on the areas that SAI considered essential for managing this issue.</seg>
<seg id="92">It is clear from the replies received that the situation in the two countries is developing differently.</seg>
<seg id="93">The Czech Republic has a system in place to guide the selection of risk-prone cases based on a large volume of relevant data (e.g. information from tax inspections carried out, data from balance sheets and profit and loss statements, etc.).</seg>
<seg id="94">This ensures efficient management and analysis of VAT control in general.</seg>
<seg id="95">A dedicated financial office for the management of VDS is planned to be established in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="96">A similar system does not yet exist in Germany, which makes it difficult to manage and analyse VAT controls in general.</seg>
<seg id="97">Germany has so far focused more on selecting the individual cases in question, in particular on the basis of data from the VAT return and recapitulative statement.</seg>
<seg id="98">The analysis of these data relies on different risk management components, which will be reinforced.</seg>
<seg id="99">3. Progress of control action</seg>
<seg id="100">3.1 Progress of the audit operation in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="101">The audit was carried out between May 2009 and February 2010 by the Division II of the State Budget Revenue Department and the territorial departments IX. Plzeň, X. České Budějovice, XIII. Brno and XV. Ostrava.</seg>
<seg id="102">The audited bodies were: the Ministry of Finance of the Czech Republic (hereinafter also “the Czech Ministry of Finance”) and 25 financial authorities (hereinafter also “FÚ”): FÚ Brno II, FÚ Brno III, FÚ Brno IV, FÚ Břeclav, FÚ Domažlice, FÚ Hodonín, FÚ in Hradec Králové, FÚ in Cheb, FÚ in Jablonec nad Nisou, FÚ in Karlovy Vary, FÚ in Ostrava, FÚ FÚ in FÚ, FÚ FÚ, FÚ FÚ in Prague, FÚ4.</seg>
<seg id="103">The audit conclusion of this audit operation was approved by the College of the Supreme Audit Office on 27 April 2010.</seg>
<seg id="104">3.2 The follow-up in Germany</seg>
<seg id="105">The audit was carried out between February 2009 and February 2010 by the Indirect Tax Inspection Service and by the staff of the designated Regional Audit Offices in Berlin, Frankfurt am Main and Munich.</seg>
<seg id="106">Following the selection of a sample of cases, a number of Länder were informed of the mission of the inspection operation.</seg>
<seg id="107">In addition to the interviews at the Federal Ministry of Finance, the auditing operation took place in the following Länder: • Bavaria, • Hamburg, • Hessen, • North Rhine-Westphalia, • Saxony.</seg>
<seg id="108">Included were the tax files of the following tax authorities: • Erlangen, Zentralfinanzamt München (Central Tax Office in Munich), Hof, Schwandorf, Regensburg, Weiden in der Oberpfalz, Grafenau; • Hamburg-Nord (Hamburg-North), Hamburg-Hansa, Hamburg für Großunternehmen (Hamburg-VDS);</seg>
<seg id="109">In addition, discussions took place with the tax offices of Mühlacker, Reutlingen, Starnberg, Verden, Erfurt, Leipzig, Halle-Süd (Halle-jih) and with the tax directorates of Frankfurt am Main, Chemnitz and Münster.</seg>
<seg id="110">A report on the audit findings was submitted to the Federal Ministry of Finance in April 2010.</seg>
<seg id="111">3.3 Cooperation between the two audit institutions</seg>
<seg id="112">As part of the preparation of the parallel control actions, a meeting of representatives of the two audit institutions was held in September 2008 to discuss and determine control topics.</seg>
<seg id="113">Subsequently, in December 2008, the leaders of both SAIs signed an agreement to cooperate in the implementation of parallel controls.</seg>
<seg id="114">At the Bonn meeting in June 2009, the audit teams informed each other of the initial results achieved during the preparation of the audit, discussed possible audit approaches and agreed on the way forward.</seg>
<seg id="115">The second meeting took place in Prague from 2 to 4 December 2009.</seg>
<seg id="116">The inspection teams exchanged previously collected findings and agreed on a timetable for the preparation of the joint report.</seg>
<seg id="117">Both SAIs decided to focus on: • follow-up of the implementation of the recommendations made in the previous report; • screening of selected cases of intra-community transactions between tax payers from the Czech Republic and Germany that were not resolved during the previous parallel check; • screening of selected cases of intra-community transactions between tax payers from the Czech Republic and Germany that were classified as high-risk cases; • checking of the tax administration's progress in the area of international assistance in the recovery of VAT claims; • tax audits of large companies.</seg>
<seg id="118">A report on the results of the parallel control actions was prepared during a workshop in June 2010.</seg>
<seg id="119">4. Control of VAT administration in selected areas</seg>
<seg id="120">4.1 Evaluation of recommendations from previous inspection</seg>
<seg id="121">4.1.1 Evaluation of recommendations in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="122">Recommendation 1</seg>
<seg id="123">Conditions for the registration of payers should be harmonised across the EU.</seg>
<seg id="124">Based on the results of the previous audit, the SAO recommended modification of the conditions of VAT registration and introduction of a new rule for cancellation of registration in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="125">The modified conditions should make it possible to reduce more effectively the risk of possible evasion of VAT collection.</seg>
<seg id="126">In this context, it was found that the tax authorities in some cases did not use the right to cancel the VAT registration of taxpayers who did not comply with the obligations arising from Act No. 235/2004 Coll., on Value Added Tax (hereinafter referred to as the "VAT Act").</seg>
<seg id="127">The Czech Ministry of Finance has not yet proposed an amendment to the provision introducing an obligation for tax administrators to cancel VAT registration for taxpayers in case of repeated non-submission of VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="128">According to the VAT Act, the tax administrator may cancel the registration of the tax payer “ex offo” in cases where: (a) the payer has not performed, without giving the tax administrator a reason, for a period of twelve consecutive months of performance; (b) the payer has not fulfilled his obligations under this Act; (c) the payer ceases to be a taxable person.</seg>
<seg id="129">In the previous audit, it was found that the applicable legislation allowed the Tax Office for Prague 1 to cancel the VAT registration on 31 January of the following calendar year for so-called non-established payers who did not incur any obligation to declare and pay the tax during the current calendar year.</seg>
<seg id="130">The FCO for Prague 1 often did not cancel the VAT registration of these payers, because the relevant provision provided for insufficient time for the cancellation of the registration.</seg>
<seg id="131">This problem was remedied by an amendment to the VAT Act with effect from 1 January 2009.</seg>
<seg id="132">The tax administrator is entitled to cancel the registration of the non-established taxpayer in case the taxpayer has not supplied any taxable goods or services or exempt goods or services with the right to deduct VAT in the previous calendar year.</seg>
<seg id="133">Recommendation 2</seg>
<seg id="134">Monthly Summary Reporting</seg>
<seg id="135">In the context of international cooperation, a previous monitoring exercise recommended that all EU countries introduce a monthly deadline for the submission of recapitulative statements.</seg>
<seg id="136">The Council Directive reduces the period for which recapitulative statements of intra-EU transactions are submitted to one month. This measure was implemented in the Czech Republic through the VAT Act with effect from 1 January 2010.</seg>
