<seg id="566">This figure does not provide an overview of selected control periods with respect to individual entrepreneurs.</seg>
<seg id="567">VAT inspectors focus on the most recent tax assessment period; They also have the right to carry out VDS checks.</seg>
<seg id="568">However, the statistics produced at federal level for the special VAT control units do not provide information on the classification of tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="569">• Are there any statistics or records on the nature of the additional tax revenue generated, disaggregated e.g. according to the following criteria:</seg>
<seg id="570">i. net increase in tax liability (e.g. in cases where the taxpayer has unduly applied a reduced VAT rate instead of the standard tax rate);</seg>
<seg id="571">ii. only nominal increase in tax liability (e.g. transfer of a fully qualified VAT case to another tax period);</seg>
<seg id="572">iii. additional collection of the tax revenue (payment of the additional tax due).</seg>
<seg id="573">Czech Republic:</seg>
<seg id="574">The Czech Tax Administration monitors the number of tax verifications carried out, the volumes of tax additionally assessed broken down by type of tax, by the number of tax entities audited and by the number of tax periods audited.</seg>
<seg id="575">Other tax procedures (local investigations, complaints procedures) are followed in the same way.</seg>
<seg id="576">Time data and amounts of additional taxes paid are recorded as a separate task.</seg>
<seg id="577">Statistics on general debts broken down by type of tax are also kept, but not by declared tax or tax established by the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="578">Germany: No, the uniform statistics at federal level for tax inspectors and special VAT inspection units do not distinguish between these criteria.</seg>
<seg id="579">Moreover, most of the tax administrations visited do not distinguish these differences.</seg>
<seg id="580">• Are there control areas that generate high additional revenue?</seg>
<seg id="581">Czech Republic: Yes, the tax administrator has the right to collect tax payers for verification based on criteria that can be linked to selected indicators in special sections of the ADIS.</seg>
<seg id="582">Germany: There are no regulations at federal level.</seg>
<seg id="583">It follows that uniform statistics at Federal level for tax inspectors and special VAT inspection units do not provide such data.</seg>
<seg id="584">However, there is one coordinated approach between the finance ministers of the Länder and the federal government.</seg>
<seg id="585">In the ZAUBER database, tax inspectors or tax investigators from the Länder must record the increased tax (VAT) they have imposed if it exceeds a certain amount.</seg>
<seg id="586">In such a case, it must specify, for example, the nature of the increase in tax liability assessed.</seg>
<seg id="587">• What are the most common findings?</seg>
<seg id="588">Czech Republic:</seg>
<seg id="589">- VDSs claim an undue right to deduct input tax in respect of supplies and services:</seg>
<seg id="590">• which have not been used to carry out any economic activity pursuant to Section 72(1) of the VAT Act;</seg>
<seg id="591">• which have been used for representation pursuant to Section 75(3) of the VAT Act;</seg>
<seg id="592">• on the basis of tax documents which did not meet the requirements set out in Section 73(1) of the VAT Act;</seg>
<seg id="593">- The VDS did not declare output VAT pursuant to Section 21(1) of the VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="594">Germany: It has been noted that there are no regulations at federal level.</seg>
<seg id="595">It follows that uniform statistics at Federal level for tax inspectors and special VAT inspection units do not provide such data.</seg>
<seg id="596">Findings concerning VAT are not separately registered by the Länder if they result from the VDS tax inspections.</seg>
<seg id="597">However, in the ZAUBER database, where tax inspectors or tax investigators from the Länder have to enter the increased tax (VAT) liability they have imposed if it exceeds a certain amount, the Federal Central Tax Office is able to analyse this information.</seg>
<seg id="598">• Does the tax administration carry out analyses of the areas of control that generate a high ‘return’ and draw the consequences for management?</seg>
<seg id="599">Czech Republic: Yes, for example, they are launching nationwide audits focused on risky commodities or the subject of economic activity.</seg>
<seg id="600">Germany: There are no regulations at federal level.</seg>
<seg id="601">The uniform statistics at federal level for tax inspectors and special VAT inspection units do not provide data on audit areas that generate high ‘returns’.</seg>
<seg id="602">There are different views on the process of analysis as well as on the management of cases in terms of materiality.</seg>
<seg id="603">Some regional tax offices provide special information, but its use is at the discretion of the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="604">4.5.4 Comparison and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="605">The differences in the replies of the two Member States show that the Czech Republic provides a system that collects a lot of data from the tax inspections carried out, as well as data from the financial statements - balance sheets and profit and loss statements.</seg>
<seg id="606">Based on a wide range of data, the Czech Republic is able to guide the selection of risk-prone cases.</seg>
<seg id="607">The same applies to the analysis and management of VAT control in general.</seg>
<seg id="608">In 2012, the establishment of a specialised financial office for the management of VDS is planned in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="609">In Germany, the tax administration does not collect this information.</seg>
<seg id="610">It follows that it is more difficult to carry out those tasks in a similar manner.</seg>
<seg id="611">However, Germany's philosophy places more emphasis on the selection of individual cases on the basis of the data from the submitted tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="612">The risk management components will therefore be strengthened and improved.</seg>
<seg id="613">Expert auditors must be able to assess the exact amount of VAT on the basis of adequate reference notes.</seg>
<seg id="614">Both SAIs agree that Member States should be able to ensure adequate financial management as well as an adequate risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="615">This will help to reduce VAT revenue shortfalls.</seg>
<seg id="616">As a result, the revenue from VAT collection will increase and the risk detection rate for unreliable entrepreneurs will improve.</seg>
<seg id="617">5. Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="618">The cooperation of both SAIs on parallel controls of the VAT administration met the objectives set by the SAO and BRH.</seg>
<seg id="619">The two SAIs have become better acquainted with each other's systems in the following areas: • intra-community transactions; • VAT risk management, in particular as regards the selection of risk-prone transactions; • VAT recovery assistance; and • VAT control of large tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="620">Thanks to mutual cooperation, differences in VAT fraud detection strategies as well as differences in the above mentioned areas of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany have been revealed.</seg>
<seg id="621">The audit findings were compared and used to identify best practices.</seg>
<seg id="622">In addition, both SAIs hope that the results achieved will provide an impetus for stakeholders to launch a debate on approaches and strategies within Member States, including at European Commission level.</seg>
<seg id="623">The extremely valuable experience and knowledge gained from the cooperation between the two SAIs can serve as an encouragement for the implementation of future control actions in the field of VAT administration.</seg>
<seg id="624">6. Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="625">The report was drawn up in Czech, English and German and signed by the President of the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic and the President of the Federal Court of Auditors (Bundesrechnungshof) of the Federal Republic of Germany.</seg>
